<HEADLINE> Berisha Wins Second Term as President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Albania's President Sali Berisha
today won a second five-year term as president of the country in
the presidential election in the People's Assembly (parliament).
</P>
<P>
In the 140-seat assembly, Berisha, the only candidate for the
post, won 113 votes out of 118 legislators who participated in the
poll. He was nominated by the governing Democratic Party which
holds 122 seats in the parliament.
</P>
<P>
Under Albania's law, the president is elected by the assembly
in a secret ballot. Berisha was first elected head of state in
April 1992 after the nation's first opposition party, the
Democratic Party, won elections for the parliament.
</P>
<P>
Berisha, who was born in Tropoja, north Albania, in October
1944, graduated from the Medical Department of Tirana University
in 1967.
</P>
<P>
He was co-founder of the nation's first opposition party, the
Democratic Party, at the end of 1990.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, the assembly declared a state of emergency
throughout the country, responding to two months of protests
sparked by the collapse of popular pyramid investment schemes.
</P>
</TEXT>
