<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Qiao on Breakthroughs in Reforming State Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Major breakthroughs must be made
in reforming its loss-making state sector in 1997, said Qiao Shi,
China's top legislator, here today.
</P>
<P>
He sset forth this request at a group discussion of the Fifth
Session of the Eighth National People's Congress (NPC) together
with the Hebei delegation, when reviewing the government work
report delivered by Premier Li Peng on March 1.
</P>
<P>
"Greater strides must be taken to set up a modern corporate
system with government department to be separated from business
operations and focusing on macro economic control," said Qiao, who
is also a Standing Committee member of the Political Bureau of the
Chinese Communist Party (CPC) Central Committee.
</P>
<P>
"Progress has been scored over recent years, but many difficult
and pressing tasks are still ahead in reforming the state-owned
enterprises," he said.
</P>
<P>
One year has passed since the Ninth Five-Year Plan for Economic
and Social development was launched, and this year will be crucial
for the realization of the blueprint, according to Qiao.
</P>
<P>
State-owned enterprises should pool their investments and funds
in upgrading their techniques, equipments and quality of products,
Qiao urged.
</P>
<P>
"Only in this way, can our enterprises stand the fierce
competition in both domestic and international markets, and
survive and grow," he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
"All relevant parties should help create favorable conditions
for the reform of the state-owned enterprises," he said.
</P>
<P>
On the macro economic situation in China, Qiao said, China has
finally achieved an economic "soft landing" after years of
enhanced efforts in macro-economic control and in-depth reforms in
the fields of taxation and finance.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the entire national economy maintained a sustained,
rapid growth, but the prices dropped steadily.
</P>
<P>
"This was not easy, especially for a populous developing
country like China, to score such a success," Qiao noted.
</P>
<P>
However, China should be aware of a host of problems to cope
with in the course of its progress, and have to deepen its reform
and improve its economic work, Qiao said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
