<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mubarak: Egypt Tries to Discourage Israeli Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
said today Egypt is doing its utmost to dissuade Israel from
following through the new Jewish settlement project in East
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
When inspecting the construction sites of Toshki Canal in
Southern Egypt, Mubarak told reporters that Jerusalem and the
latest developments of the Palestinian-Israeli track would top the
agenda of his meeting with Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin
Netanyahu during the latter's visit to Cairo Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu's visit here comes exactly a week after Israel
approved the building of 6,500 housing units for the Jewish
settlers in Har Homa (Gabal Abu Ghoneim), a tree-covered hill in
East Jerusalem taken by Israel from Jordan in the 1967 Mideast
War.
</P>
<P>
Calling on Netanyahu to shun any step regarding Jerusalem
before reaching a relevant agreement with Palestine, Mubarak said
that the Israeli government should realize the complications of
its settlement plans that have outraged Palestinians and sparked
criticism from the Arabs, the United States and the European Union.
</P>
<P>
"The establishment of this new settlement before starting the
final status negotiations regarding Jerusalem would complicate
the peace march," he warned.
</P>
<P>
But the president said he hopes to convince Netanyahu of the
risks involved in the settlement-construction process and its
adverse effect on the peace march.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak continued to say that there are no problems between
Egypt and Israel whatsoever, but his country is concerned about
realizing peace and stability and it has exerted strenuous
efforts to let the peace drive move in its right direction.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, a key mediator in the Arab-Israeli peace negotiations,
is the first Arab country to make peace with Israel but ties
remain cool between them.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli prime minister paid the first visit to Egypt last
June shortly after he took office. 
</P>
</TEXT>
