<HEADLINE> Arafat: Israeli Housing Plan Torpedos Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian President Yasser
Arafat has accused Israel of trying to torpedo peace process in
the Middle East by its decision to build a new Jewish settlement
in Arab east Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
"The decision of the Israeli government to build a settlement
... is very dangerous and is aimed at torpedoing the peace
process," Arafat said on Sunday at a dinner sponsored by the
Palestinian-American Congress after he arrived in Washington that
evening.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian leader is scheduled to meet with President Bill
Clinton and Secretary of State Madeleine Albright during his
four-day visit here.
</P>
<P>
He is certain to express his grave concern over the new housing
project approved by the Israeli government last Wednesday to build
6,500 homes in Arab east Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians want to establish an independent state in the
occupied territories with east Jerusalem as its capital, while
Israel is obviously intended to integrate the east Jerusalem,
captured in the 1967 Middle East war, into the west part of the
city and declare it as its capital in spite of opposition of the
international community.
</P>
<P>
"The Israeli government decision (of building the new
settlement in east Jerusalem) is a flagrant violation of United
Nations resolutions and of our agreements with Israel," Arafat
told members of the Palestinian-American Congress.
</P>
<P>
Hanan Ashrawi, the Palestinian minister of higher education,
said Arafat would stress to Clinton that peace moves were
threatened by the Israeli decision on the settlement when they
meet on Monday.
</P>
<P>
"It's very clear the Palestinian people are not going to sit
back and accept the implication of the Israeli decision," she
said.
</P>
<P>
The United States has criticized Israel for its housing
project, saying it complicated an already complex situation and
was not a step to "build confidence and trust" between the
Israelis and Palestinians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
