<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Government to Allocate Special Funds for Displaced Workers (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 3 (Xinhua)-- The State Council, China's cabinet,
has decided to set aside 30 billion yuan this year as reserve fund
for mergers and bankruptcies of state-owned enterprises and for
reemployment programs that will provide jobs for workers to be
displaced by such mergers and bankruptcies.
</P>
<P>
This was revealed today by Zhu Rongji, vice premier of the
State Council and a member of the Standing Committee of the
Political Bureau of the Communist Party of China (CPC) Central
Committee, in a group discussion with deputies to the National
People's Congress that has been in session since last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Zhu said the central government will increase the amount of
such reserves on a year-to-year basis, while local governments
should also support reemployment programs by raising money from
different sources.
</P>
<P>
Provincial governments and relevant cities must waste no time
in working out re-employment programs for displaced workers so
that state-owned enterprises can become profitable in about three
years, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to the vice premier, there are about 10 million
redundant workers in China's debt-ridden enterprises.
</P>
<P>
"Providing conditions for a good settlement of these workers
is an important way to help money-losing state enterprises out
of their difficulties," he said. "And this can be done only by
carrying out reemployment programs."
</P>
<P>
He said reemployment programs are a uniquely Chinese insurance
measure that is meant to protect the interests of the working
class at a time when China does not yet have a well-functioning
social security system.
</P>
<P>
"We should persist, resolutely and unswervingly, in carrying
out reemployment programs," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970304.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Government to Allocate Special Funds for Displaced Workers (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Zhu said the most important thing on this year's economic
agenda is to work for a marked progress in reform of the
state-owned sector. The fundamental way out, he said, is "to
unswervingly implement a series of important instructions by Jiang
Zemin to 'reform, reorganize and upgrade' state-owned enterprises."
</P>
<P>
The vice-premier emphasized the importance of economic
restructuring and the need to allow money-losing enterprises to
merge or go bankrupt.
</P>
<P>
"Since the majority of industrial products are in over-supply,
state-owned enterprises should work hard to restructure instead of
building new plants," he said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of bankruptcy and the merging of state-owned
enterprises, he said, "Bankruptcies should be standardized;
mergers should be encouraged."
</P>
<P>
He called for preventing what he termed "fake" bankruptcies
that are meant to evade debt repayment.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of economic development in central and western areas,
he said the central government has given 90 percent of the fiscal
transfer payment to these areas since 1995 and poured large
amounts of investment money there for capital construction
projects.
</P>
<P>
He said the central government has given priority to
exploitation of natural resources and infrastructure construction
in these areas and encouraged coastal areas to invest in these
areas, in railway construction in particular.
</P>
<P>
According to the vice-premier, the Lanzhou-Urumqi Railway
opened to traffic two years ahead of schedule and the
Nanning-Kunming Railway will be completed soon. Other railways
such as Xi'an-Ankang and South Xinjiang are under construction.
All these railways are in underdeveloped central and western
regions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
