<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Satisfied with Russia-EU Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
said here today that he was satisfied with his meeting with
visiting EU leaders, describing it as "a good dialogue."
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin was speaking after his talks in the Kremlin with Dutch
Prime Minister Wim Kok, whose country currently holds the
six-month rotating presidency of the European Union, and European
Commission President Jacques Santer, Itar-Tass news agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
"We are satisfied with how the European Union is developing and
how integration is going in the union," Itar-Tass quoted Yeltsin
as saying.
</P>
<P>
The talks in the Kremlin were also attended by Russian Prime
Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin, Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov,
Oleg Davydov, Minister for Foreign Economic Relations and Dmitry
Ryurikov, assistant to the president on international affairs.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin held a separate meeting with the EU leaders at
Government House before the Yeltsin meeting.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, they discussed concluding a permanent
agreement between Russia and the EU, a broad range of trade and
economic issues and the problems of NATO's planned eastward
expansion which Russia opposes.
</P>
<P>
Santer told reporters after the meeting that there were
"stronger partnership relations between Russia and the European
Union." He believed relations would develop dynamically in the
future.
</P>
<P>
Summits between Russia and the EU are held regularly. In 1994,
a summit was held on the Greek island of Kerkyra (Corfu), and in
Moscow in 1995 and 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
