<DOCNO> XIE19970304.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Consumer Spending Up 0.7 Percent in January </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 3 (Xinhua) -- U.S. consumer spending
increased by 0.7 in January, outpacing the 0.3 percent gain in
personal incomes, the U.S. Commerce Department reported today.
</P>
<P>
The department said that consumer spending totaled 5.3 trillion
dollars at a seasonally adjusted annual rate, up from 5.26
trillion in December.
</P>
<P>
It was the biggest increase since last October when the
spending gained by 0.9 percent. The increase followed a 3.4
percent gain in last three month of 1996 which helped boost the
U.S. economic growth by a strong 3.9 percent annual rate.
</P>
<P>
Consumer spending represents about two-thirds of the economic
activity in the country.
</P>
<P>
The report said that spending on durable goods rose by 1.7
percent in January after dropping 0.7 percent the previous month.
</P>
<P>
Spending on nondurable goods such as food and fuel increased by
0.3 percent following a slower 0.1 percent gain in December.
</P>
<P>
Spending on services advanced by 0.7 percent, faster than the
0.5 percent increase a month earlier.
</P>
<P>
The department said U.S. personal incomes totaled an annual
rate of 6.65 trillion dollars, up from 6.63 trillion in December.
</P>
<P>
The increase was the smallest since it edged up at a 0.1
percent in October.
</P>
<P>
Still, much of the increase was attributed to cost-of-living
increases in federal programs such as Social Security, changes in
the earned income credit program and pay raises for federal
civilian and military personnel.
</P>
<P>
In fact, private wages and salaries, the most closely watched
component of income, fell by 9.5 billion dollars after jumping by
41.6 billion in December.
</P>
<P>
Disposable income -- income after taxes -- rose 0.6 percent,
slower than the 0.7 percent a month earlier.
</P>
<P>
The combination of incomes and spending meant that Americans'
saving rate -- savings as a percentage of disposable income --
remained unchanged at 5.4 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
