<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, March 3 (Xinhua) -- An east African conference on
labor issues has identified areas of harmonization and adopted
recommendations to reestablish the East African Community after
three days of deliberation here, Radio Uganda reported today.
</P>
<P>
Closing the conference here yesterday, Ugandan State Minister
for Foreign Affairs Rebecca Kadaga thanked the delegates for
their selfless commitment.
</P>
<P>
She said it is only when issues are tackled in this manner
that people come to effective results.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the incorporation of labor into the East African
Cooperation, Kadaga was quoted as saying that everyone is looking
forward to improving standards of the people, when areas of
migration at the level of legislation are addressed, with regular
meetings of the three partner states.
</P>
<P>
She said this will lead to closer cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The conference recommended issues leading to creation of
effective machinery allowing workers, employers and governments
to form stronger social partnerships. This tripartism was
commended at the national, sub-regional and regional levels.
</P>
<P>
The conference also tackled migration and employment in the
region, the issue of child labor as a program of action was set.
</P>
