<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-03 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Minister: No Deal With PNA Over Settlement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Defense Minister
Yitzhak Mordechai today denied that Israel had made a deal with
the Palestinian National Authority (PNA) over a controversial
building plan in eastern Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the Knesset (Parliament) Foreign Affairs and
Defense Committee, Mordechai rebuffed the claims that Israel had
promised further troop withdrawals from the West Bank to allay
PNA's anger over Israel's decision to build a settlement in the
Har Homa neighborhood in southeastern Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
"I don't find any engagement between the Har Homa decision and
any other decision," he told the state-run Israel Radio.
</P>
<P>
Israel has delayed the first phase of further pullouts, which
should be completed within this week under the Hebron agreement
signed last month. Local media reports said that Israel might
consider widening the scope of further pullouts in order to mute
the Palestinian anger over Har Homa issue.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai, at the same time, called on Palestinians to refrain
from violence in reaction to the Har Homa project. "We are asking
the PNA and the Palestinian people to continue to build peace
between Palestinians and Israelis, and not to use any violence in
this situation," he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister told the committee that until now the PNA had
been trying hard to prevent violent response to the Har Homa
project. But he went on to say that no one could predict what
would happen after PNA leader Yasser Arafat returns from his
ongoing visit to the United States.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai did not rule out the possibility of local violences
launched by some radical Palestinians, which could lead to a
situation that is out of PNA control.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether Israel would halt the further pullouts if
violence broke out when Israeli bulldozers were sent to the
construction site, Mordechai said that Israel would do anything
necessary to ensure its security. But he again urged the
Palestinians to "continue to negotiate, and to find a nice track"
for pushing forward the peace process.
</P>
<P>
On the situation in South Lebanon, Mordechai said he had
checked with the U.S., France and Britain whether they were ready
to send peace-keeping troops to replace the Israeli troops there,
but had been rejected by the three countries.
</P>
<P>
The minister again rejected the idea of unilaterally
withdrawing troops from South Lebanon, saying the Hezbollah
forces would keep pushing on to the Israeli border and
threatening security of its northern region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
