<HEADLINE> Palestinian State Will Be Established: Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Defying Israel's warning
against declaring independence, a Palestinian spokesman today
claimed the Palestinian state will be created anyway.
</P>
<P>
Ahmad Abdel Rahman, secretary of the Palestinian National
Authority (PNA), told reporters in Gaza that "Palestinian state
will be established whether (Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin)
Netanyahu accepts that or not."
</P>
<P>
Rahman was commenting on the warning issued by Netanyahu
Sunday night when he made a tough speech at the gathering of Likud
Central Committee held in Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu warned PNA President Yasser Arafat that declaring
independence in reaction to Israel's building plan in eastern
Jerusalem would be a grave mistake that could end the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
Attending the urgent meeting of the Arab League in Cairo
earlier Sunday, Arafat said that he might declare a Palestinian
state in reaction to Israel's decision to build a settlement in
the Har Homa neighborhood in southeastern Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu told 2,000 enthusiastic party supporters: "We will
know how to react and we have a very good answer." But he did not
elaborate what actions he would take.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Sunday, Israeli President Ezer Weizman also cautioned
Arafat against declaring a Palestinian state now, saying it would
be "a terrible mistake" that could destroy the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The issue of Jerusalem has been at the center of the
Israeli-Palestinian disputes. While Israel has declared whole
Jerusalem as its eternal and indivisible capital, the PNA hopes to
create a Palestinian state with the eastern Jerusalem, occupied by
Israel in the 1967 War, as its capital.
</P>
<P>
On the Har Homa project, Rahman said that the plan is doomed to
failure. "The destiny of what they call Har Homa will not be
better than the fate of Yamit Settlement," he said, referring to
the settlement built in the Sinai Peninsula which Israel captured
from Egypt.
</P>
<P>
The Yamit Settlement was later destroyed by Israel itself
before turning Sinai back to Egypt after the two countries
signed a peace treaty in 1979. 
</P>
</TEXT>
