<HEADLINE> Improvement of Investment Climate Urged in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe should further improve
the investment climate to attract more foreign capital, British
High Commissioner to Zimbabwe Martin Williams said here today.
</P>
<P>
On the eve of the Confederation of British Industry-organized
investment and trade conference on Zimbabwe in London, Williams
said while the Zimbabwe government has made tremendous progress
in creating an environment conducive to foreign investment, more
needed to be done.
</P>
<P>
He said some of the major steps that have been taken to
improve the Zimbabwean investment climate are the signing of
investment protection agreements with investing countries, the
setting up of the Zimbabwe Investment Center, which he described
as a "dynamic organization", and the introduction of the export
processing zones.
</P>
<P>
"All these are very positive developments but there are
certain elements that can be made better," he said, citing the
huge budget deficit as one of the problem areas.
</P>
<P>
He added investors need to be confident and certain about
their investments, hence the need for clear investment policies.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe, who arrived in London
today, will deliver a keynote address at the one-day conference,
to be held on Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
