<HEADLINE> HSBC's Positive Outlook on Hongkong's Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Hongkong's economic fortunes are
closely aligned to China's. HSBC has a "very positive" outlook on
the transition of Hongkong to a Special Administrative Region,
HSBC Chief Executive said here today.
</P>
<P>
John Bond, Group Chief Executive, made the remarks while he was
announcing the Group's operating profit in 1996.
</P>
<P>
He said: "China is forecasting impressive growth of around 9
percent over the next few years. Inflation has been successfully
contained and a range of reforms initiated which will contribute
to greater economic efficiency and higher standard of living for
the Chinese people."
</P>
<P>
Expressing his confidence on HSBC's business in Hongkong, Bond
said: "The HSBC Group's strategy is to remain focused on our
customers in Hongkong and China, to invest in our businesses there
and to continue to offer high-quality products at competitive
prices."
</P>
<P>
The Group made a profit before tax of 4,524 million pounds
(7,238 million US dollars) in 1996, an increase of 852 million
pounds (1363 million US dollars), or 23 percent, over 1995.
</P>
<P>
The total capital ratio for the Group strengthened during the
first half of 1996 and remained strong at the year-end at 15.3
percent; the tier 1 capital ratio increased during the year to 9.9
percent from 9.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Group's total assets at 31 December 1996 were 237 billion
pounds (379 billion US dollars), an increase of 10 billion pounds
(16 billion US dollars), or 4 percent, since year-end 1995. At
constant exchange rates, assets grew by 25 billion pounds (40
billion US dollars), or 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
While HSBC Holding plc is satisfied with its performance, Group
Chairman Sir William Purves said: "1997 will be a year filled, for
us, with challenges and oportunities, marked, most importantly, by
the transition of Hongkong to Special Administrative Region of
the People's Republic of China." 
</P>
</TEXT>
