<HEADLINE> US Construction Spending Increases in January </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Construction spending in the
U.S. increased by 0.4 percent in January after a decline of 0.9
percent in December, U.S. Commerce Department said today.
</P>
<P>
The department reported that residential, nonresidential and
government spending totaled 589.8 billion dollars at a seasonally
adjusted annual rate in the month, up from 587.4 billion in last
December.
</P>
<P>
The spending in January was 5.5 percent higher than that of the
same month last year.
</P>
<P>
U.S. construction spending in December dropped because of bad
weather in the Western areas. It was the first decline since the
spending fell 0.7 percent last July.
</P>
<P>
The report said that spending on apartments and condominiums
rose 1.5 percent following a 4.8 percent decline in December.
</P>
<P>
Nonresidential spending advanced 2.9 percent, regaining most of
the 3 percent loss a month earlier.
</P>
<P>
Government spending edge up by a small 0.1 percent after
falling 2.6 percent in December.
</P>
<P>
Residential spending, including home improvements, increased
0.4 percent, the third straight increase.
</P>
<P>
But spending on single-family homes -- more than 25 percent of
total outlays -- was unchanged from December when outlays inched
up 0.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
After the strongest year in nearly a decade, U.S. analysts
expect housing activity to flatten in 1997 but continue at a
robust pace. 
</P>
</TEXT>
