<HEADLINE> Demand for Foreign Currency Likely Drop in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's demand for foreign
currency could drop as it becomes more expensive to import
finished goods which now attract punitive tariffs.
</P>
<P>
Stanbic Bank's money treasury manager Andy Hodges said
although in general, the tariffs would have no impact on the
foreign exchange market, demand for foreign currency might drop
in the long-run.
</P>
<P>
"People might reduce the importation of some goods, but the
fast moving consumer goods will continue coming in, and these on
their own are not of much significance in influencing foreign
currency demand on the market," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he said the country's foreign currency reserves are
more than sufficient besides the unprecedented demand experienced
during the last two months of last year.
</P>
<P>
He said the foreign currency situation is healthy with about
five-and-half months import cover. 
</P>
