<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Money Supply on Rise in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Broad money supply (M3) in
Zimbabwe grew by 31 percent in 1996, far exceeding the original
target of 22 percent set by the Reserve Bank of Zimbabwe (RBZ).
</P>
<P>
The RBZ today blamed the expansion in money supply on
increased private sector and government borrowing, with credit to
the former rising by 4.688 billion Zimbabwe Dollars (426 million
U.S. Dollars).
</P>
<P>
M3 is defined by the central bank as currency in circulation
plus demand, savings and term deposits with banks.
</P>
<P>
"Broad money supply (M3) grew by 31 percent over the 12-month
period to December 1996. This was a reversal of developments in
October and November when M3 growth fell sharply from 33.8
percent in September to 11.8 percent and 10.5 percent,
respectively, following the tightening of accommodation
conditions to discount houses by the bank," the RBZ said.
</P>
<P>
The RBZ last year set a money supply growth target of 22
percent, which it said then was sufficient to support private
sector credit expansion of at least 20 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970304.0041 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Algerian Legislature Adopts Electoral Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Algeria's transitional legislature,
le Conseil National de Transition (CNT), Sunday adopted an
electoral law on the establishment of a two-chamber parliament
with a total of 524 seats, according to reports reaching here.
</P>
<P>
The lower house of parliament will have 380 seats, each
representing a constituency of 80,000 people, while those
departments (provinces) with a population of more than 350,000
will have at least four seats, said the law.
</P>
<P>
The Algerian capital Algiers will have at least 24 seats
because of its large population representation.
</P>
<P>
The upper house of parliament will have 144 seats, with each of
the country's 48 departments having two seats, while one third of
its seats will be designated by the president of the republic.
</P>
<P>
During an extraordinary session on January 25, the CNT adopted
a new law on political parties and a text on election regulations,
which installed a proportionate system to replace one based on a
two-round majority votes.
</P>
<P>
The Islamic Salvation Front won the legislative elections in
1991 after obtaining a majority of votes in two rounds of
pollings.
</P>
<P>
The results of the elections were canceled by the Algerian
army. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
