<DOCNO> XIE19970304.0042 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bomb Blast Rocks Karachi Newspaper Office </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, March 3 (Xinhua) -- A powerful time-bomb ripped a
newspaper office in Pakistan's southern city of Karachi early
today, causing minor casualties but major damage.
</P>
<P>
Two employees of the Urdu language daily newspaper Qaumi Akhbar
were slightly injured by flying glass when the bomb went off at
5:53 a.m. today in the newspaper's building in Karachi, Pakistan's
biggest city and capital city of Sindh Province.
</P>
<P>
Bomb disposal experts discovered that the bomb was a home-made
device of a 400-gram TNT flake with a timer, sources said.
</P>
<P>
The bomb, reportedly wrapped in a packet, was placed on the
first floor of the four-story building and its impact made a hole
with a diameter of 14 inches, the bomb experts were quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Fortunately, no staff were in the office at the time of the
explosion because they usually go to work at around 6 a.m.
</P>
<P>
The damage caused by the blast was estimated by the executive
editor of the newspaper, Mukhtar Aqil, at 10 million rupees
(250,000 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The explosion shattered windows, badly damaged computers,
scanner, air conditioners and other equipment in the office, Aqil
was quoted as saying. Nearby offices were also damaged in the
blast.
</P>
<P>
No group or people have claimed responsibility so far for the
incident.
</P>
<P>
Chief Minister of Sindh Province, Liaquat Ali Jatoi, rushed to
the scene of the blast and ordered that an inquiry be conducted
into the incident and a committee formed in this regard.
</P>
<P>
The government will take necessary measures to enforce law and
order in Karachi, he said.
</P>
<P>
Karachi police have described the blast as an act of terrorism
and set up teams to investigate it.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan's Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif expressed deep concern
later in the day over the bomb blast, which he said amounts to an
assault on the freedom of the press.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister asked Sindh provincial authorities to probe
into the incident and net the culprits as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
Today's bomb blast is the fourth terrorist attack in Pakistan
this year.
</P>
<P>
Twelve people including a religious party leader were killed
and about 30 others injured on January 18 when a bomb exploded in
the eastern Pakistan city of Lahore.
</P>
<P>
At least seven people including the director of the Iranian
Cultural Center were killed on February 20 by unidentified gunmen
in Multan in the eastern province of Punjab.
</P>
<P>
Eight days later, in another bombing in Lahore, at least three
people were killed and about a dozen others injured.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan's new government has vowed to curb the rising violence
and crime and ensure a stable and safe living environment for the
people. And this is widely seen as a major challenge to the Sharif
government besides the economic crisis, because, as observers here
pointed out, if their safety of life and property cannot be
protected, the Pakistanis will lose confidence in the government.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
