<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Medical Practitioners Discuss Malaria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The Ministry of Health and Child
Welfare of Zimbabwe is running a malaria workshop for medical
practitioners countrywide in the wake of a malaria epidemic which
has already killed twice as many people this year compared to the
same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The five-day workshop which started in Kariba Town of north
Zimbabwe today is being attended by medical practitioners from
the government, city councils and the private sector.
</P>
<P>
According to the workshop, malaria has already killed over 200
people so far this year compared to over 100 last year and the
epidemic is expected to get worse because of the excessive rains.
</P>
<P>
Over 6,000 estimated deaths occurred last year due to malaria
although the figure could have been higher as some of the cases
went unreported in remote areas, the workshop said.
</P>
<P>
A statement from the Health Ministry said delegates at the
ongoing workshop will discuss ways of reducing mortality and
morbidity due to malaria by better management of complicated and
severe cases. 
</P>
</TEXT>
