<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Vows to Build Har Homa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Rebuffing international
criticism of the Har Homa (Jabal Abu Ghneim) project in
Jerusalem, Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu today vowed
that the Jewish neighborhood will be built.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio today quoted Netanyahu as reaffirming Israel's
decision to go ahead with the construction of 6,500 housing units
in the Har Homa neighborhood in the southern outskirts of
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
During a visit to Jerusalem's Abu Tur neighborhood today,
where work to improve the infrastructure got under way, Netanyahu
also stressed Israel's commitment to construct housing units for
Palestinians in east Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
"We are absolutely committed to the idea that Jerusalem is
the city of all its residents, not just Jewish residents,
but also Arab residents," Netanyahu said. "All the Jerusalem
residents are entitled to equal development."
</P>
<P>
Jerusalem Mayor Ehud Olmert, who accompanied Netanyahu during
the tour, was quoted as saying that construction projects in other
Palestinian neighborhoods are expected to begin within the next
few days.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the Israeli government approved the plan to build
6,500 Jewish homes in Har Homa, of which 2,450 will be completed
in the first three years.
</P>
<P>
In parallel, the government said it would start to build
3,015 units for Palestinians in 10 existing neighborhoods within
the city limits, though it would boost that number to 9,000
units over an unspecified time.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian officials reacted angrily to the building plan,
saying the Israeli government's decision is a violation of law
and its agreements with the Palestinians, and has put the
peace process in danger.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian National Authority President Yasser Arafat has
called on the UN Security Council and the Arab League to help
stop the construction in Har Homa.
</P>
<P>
The Har Homa issue is surely to be a highlight at today's
meeting between United States President Bill Clinton and Arafat,
who is currently paying a visit to Washington.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. had expressed its "disappointment" last week over the
Israeli government's decision to go ahead with the construction of
the new Jewish neighborhood in Jerusalem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
