<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat: Israel Plans to "Squeeze and Isolate Jerusalem" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian President Yasser
Arafat said on Monday that Israel's plan to build Jewish homes in
Arab east Jerusalem was designed to "squeeze and to isolate
Jerusalem."
</P>
<P>
Arafat, who arrived in Washington for a four-day visit, was
speaking before his talks with President Bill Clinton at the White
House.
</P>
<P>
"Their target is to squeeze and to isolate Jerusalem, but at
the same time to build settlements at the entrance of Bethlehem,"
the Palestinian leader told reporters at a photo session with
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
Clinton also expressed his regret over the Israeli government's
decision to construct the new settlement in east Jerusalem, saying
it could only build "mistrust".
</P>
<P>
"The important thing is on both sides to be building confidence
and working together," he said. "And so I would have preferred the
decision not have been made because I don't think it builds
confidence. It builds mistrust."
</P>
<P>
the Israeli decision to build the Jewish homes in east
Jerusalem was seen by the Palestinians as an attempt to cement
Israel's hold over the entire city.
</P>
<P>
Arafat accused Israel of trying to torpedo peace process in the
Middle East by its housing project.
</P>
<P>
"The decision of the Israeli government to build a settlement
</P>
<P>
... is very dangerous and is aimed at torpedoing the peace
process," he told members of the Palestinian-American Congress at
a dinner meeting on Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
"Not one single house should be added" in east Jerusalem. He
said that part of the city "was Arab, is Arab, will remain Arab
and eventually would become capital of Palestine."
</P>
<P>
Tensions are high in the West Bank over the housing project.
the Palestinian legislature called a general strike to protest
with shops and schools shut down.
</P>
<P>
Over the weekend, Israeli troops fired on Palestinian workers
at a roadblock and four tombstones were smashed at a Jewish
cemetery in Hebron.
</P>
<P>
Arafat came to Washington on Sunday from Cairo, where he
attended an emergency meeting of the Arab League.
</P>
<P>
He told the 22-member Arab League that the settlement issue was
an attempt by Israel to blast the peace process to smithereens.
</P>
<P>
"We say that there can be no peace without Jerusalem and no
peace with settlements. Steelements and peace do not go together,
and there will be no peace as long as Israel violates our rights
in Jerusalem," he said.
</P>
<P>
Arafat also suggested that he could declare a Palestinian state
in response to Israel's housing project.
</P>
<P>
"We are supposed to declare the setting up of a Palestinian
state in five years, but what would happen if I declare it right
here? What would he (Benjamin Netanyahu) do then? It's
tit-for-tat, and we have our weapons, too," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
