<HEADLINE> Ethiopia to Formulate New Culture Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The Ethiopian Ministry of
Information and Culture today announced that a new culture policy
aiming at ensuring the equality and respect for all cultures in
Ethiopia is in the pipeline.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to local journalists here, Worku Nida, head of
Culture Department of the ministry said "the policy is hoped to
produce citizens who are well-informed about their culture and
are ready to preserve and be proud of it".
</P>
<P>
Worku said, the policy is being formulated on the basis of the
principles of the United Nations Education, Science and Culture
Organization and takes into consideration the relevant
experiences of other countries.
</P>
<P>
The policy, he said, the first of its kind in the country,
intends to discourage harmful traditional practices that inflict
physical and psychological damages on individuals and promote
useful values.
</P>
<P>
According to the official, the new policy will be presented
for discussion at a symposium scheduled to be opened here early
next week. Over 200 renowned individuals, professionals,
representatives of regional states, elders, various religious
institutions and women's affairs bureaux are expected to take
part in the symposium. 
</P>
</TEXT>
