<HEADLINE> OAU Calls for Speedy Resolution of Lockerbie </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The Organization for African
Unity (OAU) has urged the Security Council of the United Nations
to facilitate the speedy and definite resolution of the Lockerbie
bombing issue.
</P>
<P>
South African Foreign Minister Alfred Nzo said in Pretoria
today that an OAU-appointed five-country committee has put three
alternatives before the UN Security Council to help the
resolution of the issue.
</P>
<P>
The committee proposed that the trial of the two suspects be
held in a neutral country to be determined by the Security
Council, and that the suspects be tried at the International
Court of Justice in Hague in the Netherlands in accordance with
Scottish law.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the committee also proposed to set up a special
criminal tribunal at the International Court of Justice
Headquarters.
</P>
<P>
The OAU Council of Ministers called on the UN Security Council
to accept one of the proposed options, thereby facilitating the
speedy and definite resolution of the dispute, Nzo said.
</P>
<P>
The OAU also appealed to the Security Council to abandon
sanctions imposed on Libya after the explosion.
</P>
<P>
A time-bomb exploded on an American Pan-AM 747 aircraft as it
flied over Lockerbie, Scotland in 1988, killing more than 200
passengers and crew, and 11 people on the ground. It was
allegedly planted by two Libyan agents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970304.0056 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Several U.S. States Battle Floods After Storms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 3 (Xinhua) -- At least 18 people were killed
in flooding and tornadoes in Mississippi, Tennessee, Kentucky and
Ohio, in addition to the 24 killed by tornadoes in Arkansas in the
last couple of days.
</P>
<P>
More than 200 people were injured and hundreds of houses were
destroyed in the worst storms in recent years in Arkansas, where
President Bill Clinton has declared disaster area of nine
counties.
</P>
<P>
The states are battling flood in the wake of the storms and
continued heavy rain.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the mid-southern states, flooding also
devastated hundreds of homes in West Virginia.
</P>
<P>
West Virginia Gov. Cecil Underwood declared a state of
emergency Sunday in 14 counties, allowing the National Guard to
assist.
</P>
<P>
Many streams were still rising toward flood crests today, and
flash flood watches remained in effect for many counties.
</P>
<P>
In Kentucky, officials in north-central Louisville and
Jefferson counties said that 40,000 homes and businesses had been
flooded.
</P>
<P>
In northeastern Kentucky, 90 percent of the 2,700 residents in
Falmouth have been evacuated as the town was devastated by the
South Fork of the Licking River. Many people sought refuge atop
their homes.
</P>
<P>
The Licking River at Falmouth was expected to crest at a record
52 feet (15.85 meters) today, easily surpassing the record 47.1
feet (14.36 meters) in March 1964, the weather service said.
</P>
<P>
The flooding water was flowing downstream toward the Ohio
River, posing threat of worst flooding since 1964 along a stretch
from Madison to Tell City, Indiana.
</P>
<P>
Ohio Gov. George Voinovich had declared a state of emergency
for a total of 14 counties.
</P>
<P>
Most of the Tennessee remained under a flash-flood watch and
Southern Illinois braced for more flooding today after overnight
rainstorms added more water to already burgeoning rivers and
creeks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
