<HEADLINE> Japan to Help Set up Data Bank in Angola </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Angola's Ministry of Public Works
said here today that Japan will help the African country set up a
geographical data bank.
</P>
<P>
Manuel Paulo, an official from the ministry, said that a
delegation from Japan International Cooperation Agency arrived
here yesterday to discuss and decide a concrete plan for the
establishment of the data bank with Angolan leaders.
</P>
<P>
The two sides signed a cooperation protocol in December, 1996,
under which Japan promised to assist Angola to set up a
geographical data bank, he added.
</P>
<P>
In the first stage, geographical data in the area of 200,000
square kilometers along coast will be collected and stored into
the bank, according to the protocol.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese delegation will end its working visit to Angola
on Thursday. 
