<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-03 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- Kuwait inaugurated an international data and
technology exhibition "Info 97" today to have a wide variety of
computers, sophisticated and applied softwares and office systems
on display.
</P>
<P>
Kuwaiti Minister of Communication Jasem Mohammad Al-Oun told
reporters after the inauguration ceremony at Kuwait International
Fair ground that "such exhibitions reflect Kuwait's bright image
and its keenness on keeping up with modern technology."
</P>
<P>
He said that Kuwait was among the leading states in
establishing such exhibitions in order to provide various age
segment of the society with their interests.
</P>
<P>
The "Info 97" exhibition which will last until March 13, displays
products of 48 Kuwaiti, the United Arab Emirates and Iranian
companies specialized in assembling and marketing computers and
its accessories.
</P>
<P>
It provides a comprehensive coverage of modern technology
regarding personal computers, programs, training, consultary,
office systems and security systems.
</P>
<P>
The computer market in Kuwait started to significantly
flourishing since 1992, especially in 1996 after the internet
was introduced to the country.
</P>
<P>
One of the organizers said they expected to receive around
30,000 domestic and foreign visitors who would "take advantage
of the exhibition's facilities."
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- Kuwait Petroleum Corporation, the state-owned
company in charge of oil products marketing, said in a statement
today that it would change the prices of its liquid petroleum gas,
propane and butane this month.
</P>
<P>
It said propane gas price would be reduced to 270 U.S. dollars
per tonne from 320 dollars, while butane gas price would stand at
277 dollars per tonne compared with 305 dollars per tonne in
February.
</P>
<P>
The decrease in liquid petroleum gas prices was due to a
decrease in demand in the international market, especially from
the Far East, Europe and Japan, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The decrease in demand was because of the end of winter
in most of these countries.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- A two-day seminar on cooperation in the oil
field between the oil-rich Kuwait and oil-importing country Japan
ended here today with a series of recommendations for the
promotion of the bilateral cooperation relations.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait Petroleum Corporation's international relations director
Abdel Majeed Al-Shatti said that during the seminar, both sides
focused on the need to promote relations between Kuwait and Japan
in all oil-related fields.
</P>
<P>
He said the seminar covered the issue of new Japanese
specifications for oil products, such as unleaded fuel, which
will be produced in Kuwait early 1998.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese center, which is considered one of the most
important centers in Japan in the field of research,
proposed a joint project on means of dealing with oil lakes.
</P>
<P>
Japan imports 60 percent of its purchased oil from
Gulf countries and it is expected to climb to 80 percent
by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
A series of seminars between the two sides to exchange points
of view and information in the field of oil industries would be
followed, Al-Shatti said.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The number of housing starts in Israel dropped
16.7 percent to 52,870 last year from 63,470 in 1995, the Central
Bureau of Statistics in Israel announced Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Most of the decline was in the public sector, where there
were 19.040 starts, down 31 percent from 1995. But housing
constructions completions increased 28 percent last year to
48,880, the largest rise being in the public sector which
doubled to 15,670.
</P>
<P>
The housing market was expected to suffer from a continued
slowdown this year, reflecting the decline in new housing
starts in 1996. Bank Tefahot forcasts new housing starts would
fall to 40,000 this year, below expected demand. The decline
was mainly caused by restrictions imposed on lending by banks
to the real estate sector, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel's foreign currency balance totaled 13.974
billion U.S. dollars last month, an increase of 1.182 billion
dollars over January, according to the Israel's Central Bank.
</P>
<P>
Capital movements by the business sector and investments in
Israel were the main causes of the rise in foreign currency
balance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
