<DOCNO> XIE19970304.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-03 20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran, Turkey Agree to Get Rid of Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Ankara and Tehran agreed here today
that necessary measures will be taken to get rid of the diplomatic
crisis from the expulsion of ambassadors by both sides.
</P>
<P>
This was expressed in a statement by Ali Tuygan, special envoy
of Turkish President Suleyman Demirel, shortly after his meeting
with Iranian President Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish envoy delivered a message from the Turkish
president to Rafsanjani during the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Before his departure to Ankara, Tuygan said "We discussed
recent problems in our relations and we have agreed that
necessary measures should be taken."
</P>
<P>
"We don't want to see such problems again in the future," the
envoy was quoted by a Turkish diplomat as saying.
</P>
<P>
Tuygan described the meeting with the Iranian president and
other officials as "fruitful," but he declined to give the content
of the message from his president or the reply from Rafsanjani.
</P>
<P>
Tuygan, who arrived here Sunday morning in a bid to remove the
trouble in the Ankara-Tehran relations, left here tonight for
home.
</P>
<P>
However, an informed source said that the message is in
connection with Iran's retaliatory move in expelling Turkish
ambassador and consul general.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian Foreign Ministry demanded Saturday that Turkish
Ambassador Osman Koruturk and Consul General Ufuk Ozsancak leave
Iran in a tit-for-tat move against the Turkish government.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish consul general in Iran's northwestern city of
Orumieh was declared by the Iranian government as "persona
non-grata" for his involvement in activities inconsistent with
diplomatic norms.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the Turkish government expelled the Iranian
Ambassador and two other diplomats because of their statements
about Islam and fundamentalism.
</P>
<P>
Iran's parliament Sunday reviewed the latest development in
Iran-Turkey relations. Alaeddin Boroujerdi, Deputy Foreign
Minister for Asia-Pacific Affairs, and Iranian Ambassador to
Turkey Mohammad Reza Baqeri presented reports on the latest
developments on the bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
Hassan Rowhani, secretary of Supreme National Security Council,
said that the problems arising in Tehran-Ankara relations have
been caused by U.S.-engineered plots.
</P>
<P>
Rowhani, also vice-speaker of the Parliament, expressed his
hope that the two friendly and brotherly countries would
continue their relations in a cordial and desirable manner.
</P>
</TEXT>
