<HEADLINE> S. African FM on Zairean Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The Zairean government and
rebel movement will hopefully have reached a formal agreement on
resolving the on-going conflict in eastern Zaire by March 19,
South African Foreign Affairs Minister Aflred Nzo said today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters in Pretoria, Nzo said some formal
agreement will have been reached between Zairean President Mobutu
Sese Seko and rebel leader Laurent-Desire Kabila before the
proposed regional summit, scheduled on March 19 in Nairobi,
Kenya.
</P>
<P>
Civil fighting between Mobutu's government force and rebel
fighters in eastern Zaire since last October has caused an exodus
of million of refugees in the region.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Mobutu's special envoy Honore Ngbanda and Kabila
arrived in South Africa and held separate talks with senior
government officials, including President Nelson Mandela and Nzo,
in a bid to seek a lasting solution to the conflict.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Nzo said a report on peace talks in South Africa
last week will be made available at the Nairobi summit, where the
tense situation in Zaire will be discussed with the expected
attendance of Mobutu and Kabila.
</P>
<P>
Nzo also confirmed that the Organization of African Unity had
decided at its recent Council of Ministers meeting to hold an
extraordinary summit in Lome, Togo on March 25 and 26 to discuss
further steps to broker a peace settlement in eastern Zaire.
</P>
<P>
He further stressed there is no alternative to people in
dispute than to sit down and discuss their problems. 
</P>
