<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Most Germans Pessimistic about Euro </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 3 (Xinhua) -- A survey released here today found
that most of the Germans are pessimistic about the planned single
European currency -- the Euro, saying that it would pose a risk
for the German economy as well as for their personal well-beings.
</P>
<P>
The survey conducted jointly by the Institute for Marketing of
the Muenster University and the Bielefelder Market Research
Institute showed that only 20 percent of the over 2,000
respondents said they were Euro-optimists. The rest were either
pessimistic or had not the least interest in the Euro.
</P>
<P>
Many of those interviewed also said they needed to know more
about the planned single currency.
</P>
<P>
The Euro is due to launched by the European Union by January 1,
1999, and will eventually replace all the currencies of the
participating states. 
</P>
</TEXT>
