<HEADLINE> Gulf Countries Denounce Israel's Housing Decision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The six Gulf Cooperation
Council (GCC) states today called on the Israeli government to
"immediately stop implementing its dangerous decision to establish
Jewish settlements in East Jerusalem."
</P>
<P>
GCC Secretary General Jamil Hujailan said in a statement in
Saudi capital city of Riyadh that the decision posed an extreme
threat to the peace process in the Middle East, saying it was a
warning that violence and atmosphere of tension would return to
the area.
</P>
<P>
He said the decision was a violation of international laws and
Oslo agreements and would abort the Israeli commitment to solving
the issue of Jerusalem in the final stage of the
Israeli-Palestinian peace negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli government last week ratified a decision to
construct 6,500 new housing units in the Har Homa (Jabal Abu
Ghneim) settlement in Jerusalem which was occupied by Israel
following the 1967 Arab-Israeli war.
</P>
<P>
The decision drew the resentment of Palestinians and Arab
Islamic world and it was also opposed by the United States and
European states.
</P>
<P>
Palestinians staged protests and appealed to the world to
block the project they said threatened the Middle East peace
process.
</P>
<P>
The pine-covered Jabal Abu Ghneim, known by Israelis as Har
Homa, is located next to the Arab village of Um Tuba. Israel
confiscated their portion of the mountain in 1991 to build 6,500
homes for Jews.
</P>
<P>
The official called on the Israeli government to halt all
decisions and resolutions aimed at changing the political,
geographic, historic, demographic and legal status of East
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The statement also recalled the GCC firm stances supporting
the accomplishment of a just, lasting and comprehensive peace
in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
GCC is composed of Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, the United Arab
Emirates, Oman, Qatar and Bahrain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
