<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-03 20:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Continues Bombardment in South Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Israeli forces continued today
bombardment at guerrilla targets in south Lebanon when a
five-nation committee is holding a meeting at Lebanon's border
town of Naqoura to consider an Israeli complaint against
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Security sources in south Lebanon said that the Israeli
occupation forces in the so-called "security zone" fired
artilleries at a number of targets in Iglim Al-Toffah,
a mountain area some 60 kilometers southeast of Beirut.
</P>
<P>
Israeli artillery shelled the hill of Jabel Al-Rafih and
vicinities of Sujoud and Rihan in the heights, which is often
used by Lebanese Muslim guerrillas as a springboard to launch
attacks at the Israeli self-carved buffer zone.
</P>
<P>
No casualties were caused in the bombardment, the anonymous
security sources said.
</P>
<P>
Guerrillas of the pro-Iranian Hezbollah, or Party of God,
announced that they attacked a foot patrol of the South Lebanon
Army (SLA) militia backed by Israel this afternoon, killing and
wounding several militiamen.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, the Islamic Resistance, the military wing of
Hezbollah, said that its fighters detonated a bomb targeting the
SLA patrol in the Jezzine area.
</P>
<P>
Sawt Jenoub Radio, organ of the SLA militia, confirmed that a
vehicle of the militia was destroyed in the bombing attack on
the Saidoun road this afternoon, and two militiamen inside were
seriously injured.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, Israeli jet fighters rocketed Jabel Safi in Iglim
Al-Toffah without causing casualties.
</P>
<P>
The raiding warplanes drew anti-aircraft fire from Hezbollah
and Lebanese army gunners stationed in the area, but no direct
hits were reported.
</P>
<P>
The daily trade of fire in south Lebanon continued as the
cease-fire monitoring committee comprising representatives of
France, Israel, Lebanon, Syria and the United States is holding
a meeting in the headquarters of the U.N. peacekeeping forces.
</P>
<P>
The committee started the meeting at 11:00 a.m. (0900 GMT) to
look into a complaint filed by Israel claiming that Lebanese
guerrillas fired from a civilian area at an Israeli patrol last
Friday, thus violating the cease-fire understanding Lebanon and
Israel reached in April, 1996.
</P>
<P>
One Israeli soldier was killed and three others were wounded
in the attack.
</P>
<P>
The so-called "April understanding," under which the monitoring
committee was set up, demands civilians on both sides of the
border be kept apart from military operations.
</P>
<P>
This is the fifth meeting of the five-state committee since
this year, and the 14th since its first meeting in August,
1996.
</P>
<P>
The state-run Lebanese National News Agency said today that
until today, the committee has received 14 complaints,
including six lodged by Israel and eight by Lebanon, in which
the two sides accused each other of breaching the cease-fire
understanding.
</P>
<P>
Since the truce was reached last April, seven Lebanese
civilians have been killed in Israeli retaliatory operations in
revenge for guerrilla attacks in the border strip.
</P>
<P>
Brokered by the U.S. and France, the cease-fire understanding
ended a 17-day Israeli blitz against Hezbollah militants in
south Lebanon, in which some 200 Lebanese, mainly civilians,
were killed.
</P>
<P>
The Jewish state established the 1,100 "security zone" in
1985 to protect northern Israel from cross-border attacks.
</P>
</TEXT>
