<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former CIA Agent Pleads Guilty to Selling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Harold J. Nicholson, the
highest-ranking official of the U.S. Central Intelligence Agency
(CIA) ever charged with espionage, pleaded guilty today to selling
U.S. secrets to Russia.
</P>
<P>
Local press reports quoted Nicholson as telling a U.S. district
judge in Alexandria, Virginia, that "I plead guilty, your honor."
He admitted to a single charge of conspiracy to commit espionage.
</P>
<P>
Nicholson, 46, was the second national security official to
plead guilty to spying for Russia in the past few days. Last week,
Earl Edwin Pitts, a former FBI counter-intelligence agent, pleaded
guilty to selling classified information.
</P>
<P>
Nicholson, who was arrested last November, admitted that he
sold Russian spies documents, photo negatives and information
relating to the national defense of the United States to the
Russians for some 180,000 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Chief U.S. District Court Judge James Cacheris accepted
Nicholson's plea and set sentencing for June. Nicholson could
receive up to a life sentence and a 250,000 dollar fine.
</P>
<P>
However, under a plea agreement, the sentence could be reduced
to a range of 21 years and 10 months to 27 years and three months.
</P>
<P>
Federal officials and attorneys said that Nicholson, like
Pitts, sought to avoid a life sentence by agreeing to plead guilty
and cooperate with authorities for further investigation of the
case.
</P>
<P>
Nicholson, a 16-year veteran CIA agent, served as the agency's
operations officer at several foreign posts. Before he returned to
to the U.S. to train recruits, he was station chief in Romania and
deputy chief in Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
His latest assignment was a branch chief in the Middle East
division of CIA's counterterrorism center.
</P>
<P>
He was accused of providing Russia names and planned
assignments abroad of the new recruits he had been working with
from 1994 to 1996.
</P>
<P>
Nicholson was the second CIA agent in two years to plead on to
the Soviets and got a life sentence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
