<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Protest over Nuclear Storage in Northern Germany, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 3 (Xinhua) -- People in northern Germany set a
barricade on fire today in protest over the storage of nuclear
waste in their area, said reports from the town of Dannenberg,
Lower Saxony.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of protesters gathered in and around Dannenberg with
several thousand police standing by. People clogged with tractors
and barricades the road linking the town with Gorleben, 15
kilometers away, which is the final destination of the trainload
of nuclear waste.
</P>
<P>
Protesters also dug a trench in the middle of the road, which
was 10 meters wide and two meters deep.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that 16 people were detained in a clash with
police at the village of Quickborn, where a road was blocked by
several hundred people.
</P>
<P>
The train carrying six containers of highly-radioactive spent
nuclear fuel rods arrived at Lower Saxony this afternoon across
from Baden-Wuerttemberg state after several delays.
</P>
<P>
Police had to remove protesters, iron bars and other obstacles
from railway tracks.
</P>
<P>
There were also bomb threats. A police spokesman voiced concern
over the potential for violence from extremists among the about
10,000 peaceful protesters.
</P>
<P>
The containers of nuclear waste from southern Germany and
France will be reloaded on heavy lorries at Dannenberg on Tuesday
for Wednesday transportation to an underground storage depot at
Gorleben.
</P>
<P>
Security cost for the nuclear transport is estimated around 100
million marks (60 million U.S. dollars), with 30,000 police
officers mobilized to shield the shipment -- the biggest police
operation in postwar Germany.  
</P>
</TEXT>
