<HEADLINE> ECOWAS Envoys to UN United for Common Interest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 3 (Xinhua) -- West African ambassadors to the
United Nations have formed an organization aimed at protecting
the collective interests of the sub-region at the world body, the
News Agency of Nigeria reported today.
</P>
<P>
The organization, called the ECOWAS Group of Ambassadors to
the UN, was established at a meeting of the representatives of
all the 16 members of the Economic Community of West African
States (ECOWAS) in New York over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
The formation of the group, which may eventually seek an
observer status at the UN, is an idea "whose time has come" and
received enthusiastic response of ECOWAS ambassadors, the report
said, quoting the Nigerian ambassador to the UN Ibrahim Gambari.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, a goodwill message to the group by
Nigeria's Head of State General Sani Abacha, in his capacity as
the ECOWAS chairman, was highlighted at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
In the message, the ECOWAS chairman expressed the hope that
the meeting will lead to the establishment of an effective and
permanent pressure group at the UN to complement "our efforts to
achieve the purposes of our community."
</P>
<P>
He listed a number of areas in which the group could assert
its influence, including taking the lead in obtaining urgent
financial, material and political support of the international
community to supplement ECOWAS' efforts in Liberia.
</P>
<P>
As a sub-regional organization, ECOWAS has been working
towards an end of the seven-year-old civil war in Liberia, which
is also a member country.
</P>
<P>
A peace accord was signed by former rival warring factions of
Liberia last August. According to the agreement, general
elections is scheduled to be held in May this year in war-ravaged
Liberia.
</P>
<P>
Abacha also charged the group to rally support for
Secretary-General Kofi Annan, an ECOWAS citizen, and to seize the
opportunity of his tenure to ensure that the interests of the
sub-region, especially in the socio-economic activities of the
UN, are well protected, the report said.
</P>
<P>
According to the Nigerian ambassador to the UN, who convened
and hosted the meeting, Nigeria and Benin will work out the
modalities for the organization and submit them to the next
meeting of the group.
</P>
<P>
The time and date of the group's second meeting is not
disclosed. But Gambari said the West African envoys will work
to implment the "guidance" provided in Abacha's message.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
