<HEADLINE> Greece Concerned Over Situation in Albania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Greece is watching developments in
neighboring Albania with great concern and has appealed to all
sides to act with restraint, Undersecretary of the Greek Foreign
Ministry Yiannos Kranidiotis said today.
</P>
<P>
There is a large ethnic Greek monority in the south of the
neighboring country. At the same time, Greece fears that tens of
thousands of Albanians might try to flee over its border, making
Athens especially conscious of the explosive situation in Albania.
</P>
<P>
"We are watching, with attention and concern, the situation and
we want a return to stability and normalcy in the neighboring
country which is our friend," Kranidiotis told an emergency news
conference. "We are ready to deal with whatever irregular
developments may arise. We are in constant contact with the
Defense Ministry and with the Ministry of Public Order. There is
constant readiness on the part of the military and the police at
the border."
</P>
<P>
A Foreign Ministry team is monitoring Albania continuously and
is in contact with the Greek embassy in Tirana and the consulate
in the town of Gjirokaster, Kranidiotis said.
</P>
<P>
Athens also urged the European Union to hold an emergency
meeting to deal with the crisis.
</P>
<P>
"Yesterday we made a proposal for the foreign ministers of
southeastern Europe to meet, with the aim of adopting a plan of
action for Albania," Alternate Foreign Minister George Papandreou
told reporters. He also said that last week Greece had called on
representatives of the EU, the United States, Russia and Balkan
countries to meet in Athens to work out how they could help
Albania and Bulgaria. 
</P>
</TEXT>
