<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat, Clinton Discuss Mideast Tensions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 3 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
held an hour of talks with Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat in the
Oval Office discussing a wide range of issues concerning the
Middle East peace process, the White House said today.
</P>
<P>
The talks focused on the situation after the Israeli government
decided to build a new Jewish settlement in Arab east Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
"They talked at great length... on the Israeli decision to
build in Har Homa (Arab east Jerusalem). The chairman was clearly
very concerned and emotional on the subject," White House
spokesman Mike McCurry told reporters at a briefing. "The
president certainly understood the basis of that emotion."
</P>
<P>
Before his talks with Clinton, Arafat told reporters at the
White House that the Israeli move to build Jewish homes in east
Jerusalem, snatched by Israel during the 1967 Middle East war, was
designed "to squeeze and to isolate Jerusalem" and build
settlements at the entrance of Bethlehem.
</P>
<P>
"The target is to squeeze and to isolate Jerusalem, but at the
same time to build settlements at the entrance of Bethlehem," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Siding with Arafat, Clinton criticized Israel's decision for
the housing project in east Jerusalem, saying the move could only
"build mistrust" between the Israelis and Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
"I would have preferred the decision not have been made because
I don't think it builds confidence. It builds mistrust," he told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli move to establish Jewish neighborhood in Arab east
Jerusalem was seen by the Palestinians as an attempt to cement
Israel's hold over the entire city.
</P>
<P>
The Israelis have declared an undivided Jerusalem would become
its capital in spite of oppositions from the Arab world as well as
the international community.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians want to establish an independent state with
Arab east Jerusalem as their capital. And the Israeli move
certainly provoked strong oppositions from their Palestinian
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Tensions are high in the West Bank with Palestinians shutting
down their shops and schools in a general strike to protest the
Israeli housing project.
</P>
<P>
Public transportation came to a halt and workers stayed home
from their jobs throughout the West Bank, Gaza Strip and east
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Arafat said he was "sure" that Clinton "will push forward to
prevent" the Israeli move to build Jewish housing.
</P>
<P>
But Clinton sidestepped questions on Jerusalem's status,
reiterating instead the long-standing U.S. position that the issue
needed to be worked out in final talks between the Israelis and
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
"I do not believe, now that the parties have reached the
agreement they reached in 1993, and they have made this the final
status issue, that the United States can serve any useful purpose
by saying, or especially by doing, anything which seems to
prejudge what should be a final status issue between the parties,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the two sides are at "a difficult moment" in the peace
process, "but I think we can work through it and go forward."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
