<HEADLINE> Tanzania Calls for Establishment of Food </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Deputy Minister for
Industries and Trade of Tanzania, Shamim Khan today called on
local manufacturers to do some efforts for diversification from
agriculture to set up food processing industries for export.
</P>
<P>
Opening a three-day workshop on future development of
Tanzanian agro-processing industry here, Khan said Tanzania
should also have emphasis on quality and cost effectiveness to
acquire a competitive edge.
</P>
<P>
According to the deputy minister, local manufacturers are at
present facing strong competition from foreign manufactured
products.
</P>
<P>
"They not only face stern competition on export markets in
Europe and the US, but also in neighboring countries of Kenya,
Uganda, Zimbabwe and South Africa," the deputy minister said.
</P>
<P>
The workshop organized by the Small Industries Development
Organization (SIDO) of Tanzania in collaboration with the
Commonwealth Secretariat, is aimed at enhancing agro-food
processing in the country.
</P>
<P>
Topics to be discussed at the workshop include the
introduction of quality systems into the food chain, investment
needs of modern manufacturing infrastructure, the increase of the
workforce and women participation in the food processing industry
in the country. 
</P>
