<HEADLINE> BMW Signals Interest in Rolls-Royce </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Bernd Pischetsrieder, boss of German
carmaker BMW, made the so far clearest signal today in a press
interview to indicate interest in Britain's luxury carmaker
Rolls-Royce.
</P>
<P>
The daily newspaper Die Welt quoted him as saying that "the
brand name Rolls-Royce would fit very well into our product
lineup." The BMW boss was however quick to note that Rolls-Royce
was not currently up for sale.
</P>
<P>
Pischetsrieder's remarks were so far the clearest signals that
showed BMW's interest in the British carmaker.
</P>
<P>
At the end of 1994, BMW agreed with the British company
Vickers, to which Rolls-Royce is subordinate, to build engines for
Rolls-Royce and to cooperate in engin research and development.
</P>
<P>
BMW is already involved in the British auto industry with its
purchase of Rover. Pischetsrieder told Die Welt that Rover would
be profitable again in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the BMW-Rover share of the world market will
rise to 2.0 percent from the 1.8 percent at present. 
</P>
</TEXT>
