<HEADLINE> Britain Urges Peacekeeping Force to Leave Together </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Britain said today that the
troops sent into Bosnia by the Western allies should leave
together, indicating differences with the U.S. on the issue.
</P>
<P>
"I regard the operation that we're undertaking as being a NATO
operation," British Defense Secretary Michael Portillo told
reporters before meeting U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen at
the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
Cohen had repeatedly affirmed that the U.S. troops in Bosnia
will surely leave by mid-1998 when the mandate of the peacekeeping
force expires. He insists the Europeans continue the job of
peacekeeping if needed.
</P>
<P>
However, Portillo said, "we went in together, we are working
together, and we shall leave together."
</P>
<P>
The United States contributes some 8,000 troops to the
so-called Stabilization Force in Bosnia. Britain, France and other
European countries are also major contributors.
</P>
<P>
Besides the peacekeeping issues in Bosnia, the two defense
secretaries are expected to focus on the enlargement of the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
Portillo said that Russia, which is strongly opposed to the
enlargement, now had to face the reality.
</P>
<P>
"I think Russia now recognizes that there will be new members
of NATO, and Russia is now engaged constructively in creating with
us a new NATO-Russia charter," Portillo said.
</P>
<P>
"I believe that can be a very important part of the new security
architecture of Europe," he noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
