<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-03 21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Complains of Bogging Down of Oil-for-food </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Iraq today complained of a delay
by the U.N. in granting the oil-for-food contracts, saying only
nine out of the 222 deals submitted have been approved.
</P>
<P>
At a news conference here, Commerce Minister Mohammed Mehdi
Saleh attributed the bogging down of the oil-for-food program to
power politics.
</P>
<P>
He said that the volume of the 222 contracts Iraq signed with
foreign companies and submitted to the U.N. Iraqi Sanctions
Committee for approval total about 673.9 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. allows Iraq to sell 2 billion U.S. dollars worth of
oil every six months starting from last December to buy food,
medicine and other daily necessities badly needed in Iraq during
the on-going six-year-old U.N. sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The nine approved contracts, which are valued at 253 million
dollars, include three for wheat, another three for baby milk and
the other three separately for rice, medicine and tea.
</P>
<P>
The first shipment of wheat by a French company will hopefully
arrive in Iraq by the end of March, said the minister, adding that
the distribution will begin as soon as the shipment comes.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi official accused the United States and Britain of
deliberately delaying the approval of the contracts, saying the
two countries are responsible for the deaths of Iraqi people
during the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. imposed sanctions on Iraq after its August 1990
invasion of Kuwait. It is reported that in the past several years
more than one million Iraqis died of diseases and malnutrition,
most of whom are women, children and the aged.
</P>
<P>
But the United States and Britain, both permanent Security
Council members, remain deeply suspicious of Iraq. They insist
that the U.N. imposes tight controls to make sure the supplies
are distributed fairly and not used for military purpose,
observers here noted.
</P>
<P>
Contracts to sell food and medicine must be approved
unanimously by the Iraqi Sanctions committee, consisting of
representatives of all the 15 Security Council members.
</P>
<P>
Saleh also criticized Japan for following the U.S. "inhumane
policy" in the implementation of the "oil-for-food" deal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970304.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Belgian PM Asks Renault to Seek Alternative to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Belgian Prime Minister Jean-Luc
Dehaene today called on the French auto producer Renault to find an
"alternative" to its plan to close a plant in Vilvoorde, Belgium,
which will result in the mass lay-off of 3,100 workers.
</P>
<P>
Renault's plan to close its Vilvoorde plant triggered an angry
protest from all walks of life in Belgium, and 4,000 workers of the
Vilvoorde plant demonstrated today in Brussels to protest the plan.
</P>
<P>
Asked by an interviewer of the French television channel two
whether Belgium is considering retaliatory measures against France,
Dehaene said, "We have not gone that far."
</P>
<P>
"What we want for the moment is that there should be the
concertation, that we look for alternatives and that one does not
make the closure point-blank, which we don't understand," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that he understands the anger expressed by Belgian
workers who, he said, could ask themselves: "We have accepted the
measures of flexibility, to what good does not make to work in
concertation with Renault for arriving at this result?"
</P>
<P>
Dehaene also warned that among the Belgian workers and in the
public opinion of Belgium, "there is a reaction which risks to take
the form" of a retaliation against France.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that the debate of depth could take place, that this
decision could be reviewed and that one could return Renault
Vilvoorde in the entire Renault," he said.
</P>
<P>
Dehaene has written a letter to the European Commission asking
the latter to verify if Renault's decision conforms with European
social legislations.
</P>
<P>
The decision to close Vilvoorde plant has also been condemned by
French unionists, who are afraid that Renault's restructuring plan
would result in a mass lay-off of 3,000 workers in France.
</P>
<P>
Renault has decided to cut its present 12 assembly lines in
Europe to eight by 1998, because of a 5 billion franc (1 billion
U.S. dollar) loss in 1996 and fierce competition in the European
auto market.
</P>
<P>
Several unions of France, Belgium and Spain have called for a
one-hour strike by Renault workers in these countries Friday to
protest the restructuring plan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
