<HEADLINE> Egyptian PM: Giant Projects Ensure Better Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Prime Minister Kamal
el-Ganzouri said today his country's giant canal construction
projects will bring better life for the Egyptian people.
</P>
<P>
After inspecting the construction site of the Toshki Canal in
the South Valley, Ganzouri said that to have a better life, 62
million Egyptians have to move out of the narrow, old Nile valley,
which accounts for only 4 percent of Egypt's total area.
</P>
<P>
The two giant projects, Al-Salam canal in the northeast and
Toshki canal in the south will be vital in providing water for the
cultivation of vast land in Sinai and Western Desert and building
new communities in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
The various projects will add about 25 percent to the 3.2
million hectares of existing cultivated land in the country in the
next 20 years, he was quoted by Egypt's Middle East news agency as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The development of the south, which represents 48 percent of
Egypt's area, costs 33.4 billion U.S. dollars in annual
investments.
</P>
<P>
He said several contracts were signed for the establishment
of cement factories, a plastic pipes factory and a hotel in the
new valley area.
</P>
<P>
"A lot of problems in the old valley will be resolved once
people start to move to the south," he said.
</P>
<P>
In January Egypt inaugurated the Toshki project designed to
draw water from the Nile to create millions of hectares of
agricultural land in the parched Western Desert. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
