<HEADLINE> Iraqi Deputy PM Criticizes UN Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD,March 3 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq
Aziz criticized here today chief of United Nations Special
Commission (UNSCOM) on Iraq Rolf Ekeus for his recent
contradictory remarks.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Iraqi News Agency (INA), Aziz said
that Rolf Ekeus, chairman of UNSCOM on dismantling Iraqi mass
destruction weapons, made some contradictory statements, adding
that in his capacity as a U.N. official, Ekeus should have
carried out his mission on the basis of "objectivity and
neutrality."
</P>
<P>
While in Baghdad, Ekeus aired multi-colored statements
suggestive of positivity, whereas in Kuwait his statements are in
favor of Kuwaiti rulers, said the deputy prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Aziz said that during his last visit to Moscow, which
came prior to his regular bi-monthly visit to Baghdad, Ekeus
spoke in such a balanced tone harmonious with the Russian
discreet stance and yet his London statements were virtually in
line with the British anti-Iraqi climate.
</P>
<P>
"To deal with such contradictory views, we have often put
them forth for discussion with the Security Council
member-states," Aziz stressed.
</P>
<P>
Concerning the position of the Security Council member-states
in this respect, Aziz said some members like the U.S. and Britain
are pleased with and support what Ekeus said. However, he said,
others "are seeking objectivity, and it is to those members we
intend to convey the facts."
</P>
<P>
Aziz appealed to the UNSCOM to submit a fair report to the
Security Council without hesitation, which would consequently
usher in implementing U.N. resolution 687 which calls for lifting
the embargo on Iraq so that it can purchase essential supplies
on condition that all dangerous weapons are removed from the
country.
</P>
<P>
The UNSCOM has refused to lift crippling economic sanctions on
Iraq after its 1990 invasion of Kuwait until it is satisfied with
Iraqi compliance.
</P>
<P>
Aziz left for Moscow today, where he will discuss with Russian
leaders the work of the UNSCOM and the necessity for the
U.N. committee to wrap up its work as soon as possible, according
to the INA. 
</P>
</TEXT>
