<DOCNO> XIE19970304.0089 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Medical Team Finds US Embargo Hurts Cubans' Health </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 3 (Xinhua) -- A U.S. medical team returning
from Cuba found that the U.S. economic embargo on Cuba has had a
devastating impact on the health of ordinary people in the
country.
</P>
<P>
"Our medical delegation found the tightening of the embargo has
had unintended consequences on the health of the Cuban people,
including unnecessary suffering and deaths," Dr. Peter Bourne,
board chairman of the American Association for World Health, told
a news conference.
</P>
<P>
The association in a report said that the tightening of the
embargo in 1992 had blocked Cuba's access to drugs and medical
technology made by U.S. companies or their European subsidiaries.
</P>
<P>
It said that the embargo, imposed in the early 1960s to isolate
the Cuban government and tightened in 1992, made it virtually
impossible for Cuba to get spare parts for medical equipment and
denied it access to important drugs.
</P>
<P>
The report found that in 1991, Cuban doctors had regular access
to about 1,300 medicines, but that has now dropped to fewer than
900.
</P>
<P>
The medical team also found that the water supply in Cuba is
made with U.S.-made pipes and equipment. Because of the shortage
of equipment supply, water cleanliness has deteriorated,
contributing to a rise in diarrheal diseases, typhoid and other
water-borne diseases. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970304.0090 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
