<HEADLINE> Xinhua International News Summary at 1530 GMT, March 4 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA ATA -- The number of civil servants in Kazakhstan is to be
slashed by half and the number of ministries cut by a third as
part of a wide-ranging government shake-up ordered by President
Nursultan Nazarbayev to boost efficiency and save money.
</P>
<P>
The president signed a decree Tuesday reducing the number of
government staff by half, the number of ministries from 21 to 14,
ministerial level committees from 13 to four and other government
institutions by almost two thirds from 14 to five.
</P>
<P>
PARIS -- United Nations Secretary-General Kofi Annan said that
U.N. armed intervention in eastern Zaire will be necessary, if the
warring factions in Zaire refuse to reach a cease-fire to allow
humanitarian aid to reach tens of thousands of refugees.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the weekly "Jeune Afrique" published
Tuesday, Annan said that armed intervention would allow the
evacuation of and save the lives of tens of thousands of Rwandan
Hutu refugees caught in the fighting between Tutsi rebels and
Zairean government troops.
</P>
<P>
ISLAMABAD -- Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif has ordered
that all available state land should be distributed among the
landless tenants.
</P>
<P>
Sharif asked the authorities concerned to work out all relevant
 details of the scheme and finalize them immediately, a press
release issued by the prime minister's office said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
SEOUL -- South Korean President Kim Young-sam Tuesday appointed
former Seoul Mayor Koh Kun as his new prime minister in a bid to
rescue his image from the effects of the recent Hanbo loans
scandal.
</P>
<P>
Koh replaces Lee Soo-sung who was sacrificed after 15 months in
the job to carry the can for the scandal involving loans to Hanbo
Steel company which collapsed in January under six billion
U.S. dollars of debt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
