<HEADLINE> China to Speed up Housing Construction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 4 (Xinhua) -- China plans to build 1.2 billion
sq m of urban housing between 1996 and 2000 in a bid to turn the
industry into a new economic growth point, Minister of
Construction Hou Jie said here today.
</P>
<P>
"The Ninth Five-Year Plan (1996-2000) period is an important
one for China's urban development and housing construction," Hou
said at a press conference in the Great Hall of the People.
</P>
<P>
"China will use the macro control means to achieve coordinated
urban economic and social development and to accelerate the
construction of housing to make it a new hot consumption spot and
a new economic growth point," he said.
</P>
<P>
To that end, China will build an average annual 240 million sq
m of housing in the urban areas in the years before the end of the
century, raising the per capita living space of urban Chinese to
nine sq m.
</P>
<P>
The minister revealed that fixed-asset investment in urban
public engineering facilities will total 480 billion to 600
billion yuan in the five years to 2000.
</P>
<P>
China will also build 2.79 billion sq m of housing in the
countryside and in rural towns to speed up urbanization, Hou told
journalists.
</P>
<P>
He said that China scored great achievements in housing
construction since its founding in 1949, especially since the
launching of the economic refrom and opening-up drive in 1979.
</P>
<P>
Between 1979 and 1996, China invested 1137.9 billion yuan in
urban housing construction. The rural areas registered an average
annual housing construction of 500 to 700 million sq m during the
period.
</P>
<P>
During the period, a total of 13.8 billion sq m of housing was
built, 2.8 billion sq m in the urban area and 11 billion sq m in
the rural area. As a result, 150 million Chinese families moved
into new houses.
</P>
<P>
Despite all this, the minister pointed out, a housing shortage
still exists, seriously in some areas.
</P>
<P>
"The situation is yet to be improved fundamentally," Hou said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that currently China has three million families with a
per head living space of less than four sq m while the per capita
living space of 19 provinces and autonomous regions is below the
national average.
</P>
<P>
In Chinese cities, about 40 percent of the houses are not
adequately equipped and another 30 million sq m of housing is in
dangerous conditions, Hou said.
</P>
<P>
"China's immense population of 1.2 billion and an annual net
increase of 14 million have resulted in a great pressure of demand
for housing," he said.
</P>
<P>
For reasons such as irrational pricing, China now has more than
50 million sq m of completed building space that are left vacant,
including 30 million sq m of housing space, he said, adding that
the government will take proper measures to make it easier and
cheaper for individuals to buy or rent houses.
</P>
<P>
"The central government will make some concessions on taxes.
Local governments will make some concessions on charges for the
use of the land. The banks will make some concessions on
interests. And the developers will make some concessions on
profits," Hou said.
</P>
<P>
Other measures Hou mentioned include the provision of more
mortgage loans and the introduction of payment by instalments.
</P>
<P>
Hou's deputy Tan Qingliang said that China is paying greater
attention to housing quality while increasing the construction
area.
</P>
<P>
Another deputy Li Zhendong said that China currently has a
common public fund of 38 billion yuan for housing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
