<HEADLINE> Legislators on Protection, Development of Marine Resources </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Deputies to the Fifth Session of
the Eighth National People's Congress (NPC), China's legislature,
have submitted a dozen bills concerning the protection and
development of the country's marine resources.
</P>
<P>
The legislators suggested that a system of maritime laws be
perfected and special administrative bodies be established as soon
as possible to improve the current situation in the management of
the country's exploration of marine resources.
</P>
<P>
In May of 1996, China joined the UN Convention on Maritime Law,
according to which the sea area under China's jurisdiction
increased to about 3 million sq km from 380,000 sq km.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Du Bilan, a noted oceanographer, said that with the
development of science and technology, the mankind is attaching
more attention to seas and oceans, which cover 71 percent of the
global surface.
</P>
<P>
"The one who owns the sea owns more wealth," she noted. "For a
country like China, which has a population of 1.2 billion, to
speed up orderly development of marine resources is an important
way to achieve a sustainable growth."
</P>
<P>
However, marine and environment experts attending the current
NPC session noted that in China's coastal areas there exist
problems such as explorations of sea areas in violation of the law
of nature, which are detrimental to marine resources and
environment.
</P>
<P>
Each year, they said, the country lost several billion yuan as
a result of deterioration of marine resources caused by pollutant
discharges alone.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, irregular development of marine cultivation caused
negative effects on sea embankments and navigation courses, and
rampant fishing depleted aquatic resources, which resulted in
problems, they said.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Du Bilan said: "It has become imperative to strengthen
the comprehensive maritime control."
</P>
<P>
She and other legislators suggested that the country take
prompt steps to complete its maritime legal system, so as to
define the state ownership of the sea, and put an end to
activities for wilful use of sea areas and beaches by some
departments and individuals in the coastal areas.
</P>
<P>
Apart from eight laws concerning maritime affairs already
adopted or being discussed by the NPC, they said, it is also
necessary to formulate other laws, such as the law on paid use of
sea areas, and the law on the management of marine resources
development.
</P>
<P>
The legislators also set forth a series of advices, which
include the setting up of a "national maritime committee" headed
by senior leaders of the State Council, and a "state bureau of
maritime management" jointed run by the National Bureau of
Oceanography and the Ministry of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the National Bureau of Oceanography showed that
between 1980 and 1995, China's maritime economic output rose at an
average annual rate of 28 percent, and reached 220 billion yuan in
1996.
</P>
<P>
Experts predicted that by the year 2000, the total value of
maritime economic output is expected to account for more than five
percent of China's gross national product. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
