<HEADLINE> Asia-Pacific G-6 Agree to Cooperate on Financial Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Senior financial and monetary
officials from five Asia-Pacific countries and the United States
today agreed to cooperate insecuring stability in their financial
markets.
</P>
<P>
At the first meeting of the so-called Group of Six (G-6) forum,
representatives from Australia, China, Hong Kong, Japan, Singapore
and the United States gained "mutual understanding on their
economic situations by discussing financial market developments"
and agreed on joint efforts to maintain stability on the financial
markets, said Takatoshi Kato, Japan's vice finance minister for
international affairs, who chaired the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Participants "frankly" exchanged views on the macroeconomic
policies of each member, Kato told a press conference, although
they failed to lay down a concrete framework for cooperation.
</P>
<P>
He said similar meetings will be held regularly, with the next
set for Singapore in a year's time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
