<HEADLINE> Kazakhstan to Streamline Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA ATA, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The number of civil servants in
Kazakhstan is to be slashed by half and the number of ministries
cut by a third as part of a wide-ranging government shake-up
ordered by President Nursultan Nazarbayev to boost efficiency and
save money.
</P>
<P>
The president signed a decree today reducing the number of
government staff by half, the number of ministries from 21 to 14,
ministerial level committees from 13 to four and other government
institutions by almost two thirds from 14 to five.
</P>
<P>
The Ministries for the Economy, Trade and Industry, Housing and
Construction, the State Committee for Prices and Anti-Trust Policy
and for Statistics and Analysis will be merged into the Ministry
of Economy and Trade.
</P>
<P>
The Ministries of Culture, Education and Youth, Tourism and
Physical Culture and the State Commission of the National Policy
will be merged into the Ministry of Education and Culture.
</P>
<P>
The reforms, the result of several months of study, will also
be extended to local government level, Nazarbayev said.
</P>
<P>
The president also spoke about the new investment law passed at
the end of February and said Kazakhstan will strengthen the
management of foreign investment to ensure it is used effectively.
</P>
<P>
He said Kazakhstan will encourage foreigners to widen their
investment away from energy and toward domestic manufacturing to
boost its competitiveness so that imports can be substituted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
