<HEADLINE> HK Reaffirms Fair Charges for New Airport </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Airport Authority
(AA) today rejected claims made by the International Air Transport
 Association (IATA) that the airport charge levels at the Chek Lop
 Kok New Airport would harm Hong Kong's role as an aviation
center.
</P>
<P>
"Some of the recent figures quoted by IATA, such as an alleged
loss of one million visitors a year to Hong Kong, are highly
speculative," AA Corporate Development Director Clinton Leeks said
 today.
</P>
<P>
The AA is responsible for developing and managing the new
airport.
</P>
<P>
"Consultations with IATA and other groups over fees at the new
airport at Chek Lap Kok are still in progress," he said. "As the
level of fees has not yet been decided upon, such suggestions are
alarmist rather than helpful to the common aim, which is to
continue to develop Hong Kong's role as a center of aviation in
the region."
</P>
<P>
Leeks said the new airport's charges would be fair and
reasonable and would be based on the "user pays" principle, with
no subsidies being paid out of the public purse.
</P>
<P>
The AA would continue consultations with IATA in the fifth
round of talks on the issue, according to Leeks.
</P>
<P>
Being built on a reclaimed island in the west of Hong Kong, the
 Chek Lap Kok airport is expected to be completed in April 1998,
to replace the existing Kai Tak International Airport, whose
capacity is almost saturated.  
</P>
</TEXT>
