<HEADLINE> Egyptian, French Presidents to Discuss Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The Egyptian and French presidents
will discuss the latest Mideast peace development in Paris,
France, French ambassador to Cairo said today.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Egyptian MENA news agency, Ambassador
Jean Marc Rochereau de la Sabliere hailed efforts exerted by
President Hosni Mubarak to promote the Mideast peace
process.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak will stop over Paris Friday en route to his March 10
visit to the U.S. capital of Washington.
</P>
<P>
During the one-day visit, Mubarak will "follow up his
consultations with French President Jacques Chirac regarding
different crucial issues," said the ambassador.
</P>
<P>
They will discuss the current situation in the Middle East as
well as the latest developments on the Syrian and Lebanese peace
tracks, de la Sabliere said.
</P>
<P>
"France is greatly interested in the views expressed by
President Mubarak," he added, saying that France believes that
Egypt is a major and essential partner in reinforcing peace in
the region.
</P>
<P>
The European Union (EU), especially France, played a major role
in realizing a United States-sponsored cease-fire understanding
last April which ended a 17-day Israeli blitz on Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the ambassador criticized Israel's plan to set
up new Jewish neighborhoods in East Jerusalem and said France
considers it an obstacle hindering the peace march.
</P>
<P>
Regarding the desire expressed by U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright to give France a greater role in the peace
process, the French diplomat said that there is a continued dialog
between Washington and Paris in spite of some differences in
viewpoints.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. is playing a crucial role in the peace process, he
noted, noting that the French role is a complementary not a
competitive one.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and Israel are reported to have gradually retreated
from excluding Europe from the peace process in the region where
it has been the major financier.
</P>
<P>
Assuring that Europe's role would not collide with
Washington's, he urged coordinated efforts to remove all obstacles
hindering the peace march.
</P>
<P>
Europe in general and France in particular have an" effective
positive role" and such a role can "not contradict with the
American one," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
