<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Says Armed Intervention in Zaire may be Necessary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 4 (Xinhua) -- United Nations Secretary-General
Kofi Annan said that U.N. armed intervention in eastern Zaire will
be necessary, if the warring factions in Zaire refuse to reach a
cease-fire to allow humanitarian aid to reach tens of thousands of
refugees.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the weekly ``Jeune Afrique'' published
today, Annan said that armed intervention would allow the
evacuation of and save the lives of tens of thousands of Rwandan
Hutu refugees caught in the fighting between Tutsi rebels and
Zairean government troops.
</P>
<P>
``If the member states (of the United Nations Security Council)
succeeded very rapidly... in imposing a lasting ceasefire which
allows the creation of a human corridor, we don't need armed
intervention. If not, we should resort to this solution,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
Some 160,000 Hutu refugees Sunday fled the refugee camp of
Tingi-Tingi, 250 kilometers southeast of the strategically key
city of Kisangani, to escape the advancing rebels led by
Laurent-Desire Kabila.
</P>
<P>
During his visit to Paris last week, Annan relaunched a
U.N. appeal for the dispatch of a multi-national force to eastern
Zaire.
</P>
<P>
``Three months ago, while the question of an intervention force
was posed for the first time, these member states (of the United
Nations Security Council) told us that they did not see refugees
in eastern Zaire. Today, the reappearance of tens of thousands of
people in distress is evidence,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
The United States and Canada scrapped a plan to send a
multi-national force to Zaire after some 600,000 Hutu refugees
suddenly returned to Rwanda from Zaire in early December. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970304.0108 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zhu Calls for More Attention to Agriculture (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-Premier Zhu Rongji
urged governments at all levels to attach still more importance to
the agriculture development at the time of a good harvest.
</P>
<P>
"The better yields we have just harvested, the more attention
we should pay to the agriculture," said Zhu, who is also a
Standing Committee member of the Political Bureau of the Chinese
Communist Party (CPC) Central Committee.
</P>
<P>
At a panel discussion of Jilin delegation of the Fifth Session
of the Eighth National People's Congress (NPC), to deliberate
Premier Li Peng's government work report delivered on March 1, Zhu
said China set another record farm yield last year after a good
harvest in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The increase in the farmers'income was the biggest ever in
history, thanks to the correct policies of the Party Central
Committee and the State Council on agriculture and hard work of
relevant departments and localities, Zhu added.
</P>
<P>
"However," he noted, "we should be aware of the country's weak
agricultural infrastructure and that dependence on the natural
conditions has not entirely been altered."
</P>
<P>
"We still do not dare to say that stable farm yields cannot be
maintained, for the situation differ from year to year," Zhu
noted.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the good harvests were not reaped nationwide in an
all-round way, he said, noting that the production of cotton and
edible oil decreased to varying extent.
</P>
<P>
"From a long-term point of view, the problem of adequate grain
production has not been resolved in China, so that we should never
be over-optimistic," Zhu warned.
</P>
<P>
Governments at all levels should neither transfer their energy
nor slacken their efforts, he said. Zhu called for their attention
to the piling of agricultural materials, slow sales of
fertilizers, grain seeds and farming tools.
</P>
<P>
"Since the founding of New China, there were several major
downturns in agriculture. They were all directly related to the
slackened efforts by the government after good harvests, in
addition to other reasons," Zhu quoted President Jiang Zemin as
saying.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970304.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zhu Calls for More Attention Paid to Agriculture (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Zhu cited protecting and encouraging farmers' initiatives as
the basis of all agricultural work.
</P>
<P>
Because of insufficient storage capacities in many parts of the
country, the good harvest last year has brought some difficulties
to major grain producers, especially China's northeastern region,
including the Jilin province.
</P>
<P>
To solve this problem, the central government has just
allocated a large sum of special funds to build temporary storages
and dispatch trains to transport surplus grain to other areas, Zhu
acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
And the central government has spent a great deal to purchase
the abundant grain from farmers, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We have to guarantee that farmers earn more as they produce
more, and stabilize the grain purchase price at the reasonable
level set by the central government," Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
"It is the most direct, effective and practical call to
stabilize grain prices at the reasonable level and purchase all
grains in the hands of farmers, which is aimed to pool efforts for
agricultural development this year," Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that agriculture should be given the top priority
in the government's economic work, so as to keep up the steady
growth of agriculture and rural economy.
</P>
<P>
He urged all localities and departments to ensure adequate
input into agriculture, and the implementation of all preferential
policies aimed at supporting agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the sown acreage of cereals, cotton and other main
crops, should be ensured and increased burdens for farmers after a
good harvest be prohibited.
</P>
<P>
The relevant department should vigorously enforce rules,
regulations and disciplines, funds for grain purchase should not
be misused and no IOUs be issued in this regard, the vice-premier
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
