<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Renault to Cut 2,764 Jobs in France </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 4 (Xinhua) -- French auto group Renault will cut
2,764 jobs in France this year and carry out re-structure 1,032
jobs within the group, the media quoted union sources as saying
today.
</P>
<P>
Although it wouldn't confirm the figures, the Renault
management said it would present an employment plan to the central
staff committee on March 13.
</P>
<P>
The news comes on top of last week's announcement by the
company that it would close its assembly plant in Vilvoorde,
Belgium, in July with the loss of 3,100 jobs. Renault has a total
workforce of 140,000.
</P>
<P>
The French lay-off plan is aimed at "continuing the reduction
of the workforce while maintaining the recruitment of young
people," Agence France-Presse reported.
</P>
<P>
The cuts would be the biggest by the partially-privatized
company since it fired some 3,700 workers in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Renault also plans a progressive early retirement program for
300 workers, who will be replaced by 150 younger workers, AFP
quoted the union sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
A French union group, the Federation-CFE-CGC of Renault
metallurgy centers, today called on "French and Belgian public
powers to take exceptional measures to avoid this human waste."
</P>
<P>
It called for "the injection of emergency funds to save French
automobiles," as the French government has done for the country's
iron and steel industry, textile industry and banks.
</P>
<P>
Renault unions have called a one-hour strike on Friday in all
plants in France, Belgium and Spain to protest against the
shutdown of the Belgian factory.
</P>
<P>
Renault was privatized in stages in 1994 and 1996. The French
state still holds a 46 percent stake of the company.
</P>
<P>
Renault reported a loss of 5 billion francs (1 billion U.S.
dollars) in 1996, which it blamed on the globalization of the auto
market and strong competition from other European automakers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
