<HEADLINE> Syria Vows Adherence to Peace Despite Israeli </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Syria has reiterated its
adherence to the peace process despite an Israeli government
decision on building a Jewish neighborhood in East Jerusalem,
local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The official media said that Syria has not lost faith in the
peace quest despite all forms of extremism and provocation
demonstrated by the Israeli government headed by Prime Minister
Binyamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
In an editorial, the official Damascus daily "Al Thawra" said
that the Netanyahu cabinet's determination to implement the
settlement project in occupied East Jerusalem is a flagrant
challenge to international legitimacy and relevant
U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
The editorial also charged that the Israeli move constitutes an
aggression against Arabs, against peace and against all values and
principles of justice in the world.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper added that the Netanyahu government does not
attach any weight to peace, and it is not prepared to return the
occupied lands and rights to their legitimate owners, and will not
relinquish its settlement and expansionist plans even if it has to
antagonize the whole world.
</P>
<P>
"Al Thawra" stressed that Syria is still endeavoring, seriously
and sincerely, to revive the hopes of peace and guard against its
collapse. Therefore, Syria is waging a diplomatic drive throughout
Europe to brief European leaders about the realities of the
situation in the region, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli Ministerial Committee on Jerusalem agreed last
Wednesday on the establishment of the new Jewish settlement in
East Jerusalem, the first stage of which consists of 2,500 housing
units out of the total 6,500. 
</P>
</TEXT>
