<HEADLINE> Indonesian Government Plans to Liquidate "Ailing" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government is
preparing a regulation which would increase the competitiveness of
banks and liquidate "ailing" banks, a senior official said here
today.
</P>
<P>
"It is like a car which slows down. It should be pulled over,
otherwise it will disturb the traffic," Minister of Finance Mar'ie
Mohammad said when explaining the results of last week's ASEAN
finance ministers' meeting in Phuket, Thailand.
</P>
<P>
He said such competitiveness should be increased in the face of
trade liberalization in the service sector, particularly in the
financial sector, such as banking, insurance and pension fund.
</P>
<P>
He thus called on "ailing" banks to merge with "healthy" ones
to improve their performance.
</P>
<P>
The government has arranged mergers and even given tax
facilities to ease the process, he added.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Bank Indonesia (central bank) governor J. Soedradjad
Djiwandono also called on banks to tighten their internal controls
to ensure all divisions, especially credit and treasury divisions,
do business prudentially.
</P>
<P>
Bad loans at Indonesia's 239 commercial banks reached 10.4
trillion rupiah (4.34 billion US dollars) as of the end of
November 1996. This was 3.26 percent of their total credits in the
same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
Mar'ie said ASEAN (Association of Southeast Asian Nations)
finance ministers last week agreed to hold joint training in the
financial sector.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN finance ministers last Saturday (March 1) signed two
agreements related to trade and monetary system liberalization in
the region.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN groups Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines,
Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam.  
</P>
</TEXT>
