<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Foreign Minister Refutes False Media Reports about Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Foreign Minister Qian
Qichen today refuted recent untruthful coverage of the Hong Kong
question by some foreign media.
</P>
<P>
Qian, who is also a vice premier of the State Council, said
that, according to some Western media reports, it seemed as if
China were "lawless" in Hong Kong: disbanding Hong Kong's
Legislative Council and repealing its laws.
</P>
<P>
"I can safely say that the authors of these sensational reports
know nothing about the real situation in Hong Kong, nor do they
have the wish to do so," Qian said at a group discussion attended
by Guangdong deputies to the National People's Congress, which has
been in session here since last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Annex Three to the Basic Law of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (HKSAR) clearly stipulates that only six
national laws shall apply in the HKSAR, he pointed out, adding that with
Hong Kong and the inland area implementing their own laws
respectively, there is no question whatsoever of applying inland
laws in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The Standing Committee of the National People's Congress has
decided to retain all of Hong Kong's existing laws, ordinances and
regulations except a dozen or so laws and several clauses, he
said.
</P>
<P>
And China has not abolished a few unsuitable clauses in some
laws, leaving them to the future government of the HKSAR for
decision, he said.
</P>
<P>
Qian affirmed the Chinese government's stand of adhering to the
Sino-British Joint Declaration and the Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
"No matter how complicated and changeable the international
situation is, China will strictly follow the principles of `one
country, two systems', `Hong Kong people governing Hong Kong' and
`a high degree of autonomy', to accomplish a smooth transition of
Hong Kong and its smooth return," he said.
</P>
<P>
With the election and appointment of the chief executive of the
HKSAR and the appointment of 23 principal officials for the future
SAR government, and with the establishment of the Provisional
Legislative Council of the HKSAR that includes 33 members from the
British Hong Kong Legislative Council, a smooth transition is
assured, he said.
</P>
<P>
"At a time like this, no one would believe reports saying that
China has `disbanded the Legislative Council' and 'repealed
laws'," he said. "Hong Kong people's confidence is on the rise."
</P>
<P>
Despite drastic changes in the international arena
over the past few years, he pointed out, China's development is
"unstoppable."
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that China wants to focus on reform, opening-up
and modernization and that a stable and prosperous China will
become an important force in safeguarding world peace.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
