<HEADLINE> Northeast China City Pushes Food Processing Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Changchun, the capital of
northeast China's Jilin Province, intends to take advantage of its
abundant grain and livestock to become a major food-processing
base in China.
</P>
<P>
An important grain producer, Changchun produced a record 7.5
million tons of grain last year, providing a firm foundation for
the local animal husbandry. Its corn production, which contributes
a large amount to local grain output, is expected to give an
impetus as well to development of such local industries as
pharmaceuticals, textiles, and paper.
</P>
<P>
A big corn development company with annual processing capacity
of 300,000 tons is expected to be built by the end of the year,
and the city plans to increase its annual corn processing capacity
to 1.8 million tons by the turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
Changchun has jurisdiction over more than 145 towns and
townships, providing a total of 650,000 tons of meat a
year. Experts predict that by the year 2000 Changchun will be able
to process more than 400,000 head of cattle, one million pigs, and
100 million chickens a year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
