<HEADLINE> East China Province Planning Six Railroad Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUJIAN, March 4 (Xinhua) -- China's Fujian Province, where
there is an average of only 3.3 cm of railway for each person,
compared with the national average of five cm, is planning to
build six major railways to link it with neighboring provinces.
</P>
<P>
The six proposed lines, which will take the form of
Sino-foreign joint ventures, include one running along the coast
between Fuzhou, the provincial capital, and Xiamen, a special
economic zone.
</P>
<P>
The schemes are expected to extend the total length of local
rails to 2,500 km and will be connected to national trunk lines.
</P>
<P>
For a long time, the lack of railroads in Fujian has hampered
development of the local economy and the province's efforts to
improve its investment environment.
</P>
<P>
In 1993, the Local Railroad Construction Corporation of Fujian
Province was set up by the provincial government, with a
registered capital of 180 million yuan, to deal with this. It
currently has property worth more than two billion yuan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
