<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-04 14:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Says 5 "Red Army" Members Detained in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Japan has notified Lebanon that
eight Japanese citizens, including five members of the Japanese
"Red Army," were detained by the Lebanese authorities, Adnan
Addoum, Lebanon's state prosecutor, announced here today.
</P>
<P>
Addoum held a meeting in his office this morning with a
Japanese security delegation, which was sent to Beirut on the
second day after the detention was first exposed on February
17.
</P>
<P>
At the end of the meeting, the state prosecutor told a
press conference that the Japanese security delegation told
him that five Japanese belonging to the "Red Army" were detained
in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
He added that the Japanese delegation also said that there
are three other Japanese citizens detained by the Lebanese
authorities and they are not members of the radical Japanese
group.
</P>
<P>
Addoum declined to disclose names of those Japanese citizens
who the Japanese delegation claimed were detained in Lebanon,
noting that the information needed to be confirmed.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese officials had denied earlier that the Lebanese
security forces had taken into custody any members of the "Red
Army" in an search-and-arrest campaign on February 15.
</P>
<P>
However, the state prosecutor clarified today that the security
forces launched the campaign against Asians after obtaining
information on a clandestine group falsifying tourist documents
and entry visas.
</P>
<P>
Alluding that the detainees could not be immediately handed
over to Japan, Addoum underlined that if it is proved that
they have committed crimes on the Lebanese land, they will
be tried in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
An envoy of Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto had a
series of meetings in Beirut Monday separately with Lebanese prime
Minister Rafik Hariri, Foreign Minister Farez Boueiz and
President Elias Hrawi in an addition to Addoum.
</P>
<P>
Judicial sources said that Hiroshi Hirabayashi, chief foreign
policy advisor to the Japanese premier, and the Lebanese state
prosecutor exchanged pictures and fingerprints of the detainees.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese Foreign Ministry issued a statement earlier
today, saying that among the Asian detainees in Beirut are
five members of the "Red Army," including Kozo Okamoto.
</P>
<P>
Okamoto was sentenced to life imprisonment in Israel for
an involvement in the shootout in Tel Aviv's Lodd Airport in
1972 in which 24 people were killed and some 100 others
wounded, but he was released in a Palestinian-Israeli prisoner
swap in 1985.
</P>
<P>
The Radical Japanese "Red Army" was accused of being
responsible for a series of terrorist attacks in the Middle East
and elsewhere in the 1970s and 1980s. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
