<HEADLINE> Ramos Urges Congress to Pass Tax Reform Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos
today urged the country's bicameral congress to speed up its
deliberation of a reform program on income taxation, the
Presidential Press Office said.
</P>
<P>
Ramos, who is now in India on a three-day visit, made the call
in a handwritten memorandum faxed to Executive Secretary Ruben
Torres.
</P>
<P>
Ramos said he expects the income tax reform plan to move from
the House of Representatives to the Senate by March 13 when the
next meeting of the Legislative-Executive Development Advisory
Council opens.
</P>
<P>
Ramos wrote the memorandum in response to a statement made
Monday by Senate President Ernesto Maceda, who said the bills
restructuring income taxes will not go through the congress by May
1 because the lower house has dragged its feet on the issue.
</P>
<P>
The income tax reform bill is the last part of the country's
Comprehensive Tax Reform Program to be approved by the congress.
The congressional passage of the bill is among the requirements
for the Philippines' exit program from the International Monetary
Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
The Philippines, whose economic development has been under the
supervision of the IMF for 35 years, is expected to graduate from
the world financial body by June this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
