<DOCNO> XIE19970304.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Measles Cases Decline in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Health Secretary
Carmencita Reodica said today that measles cases declined by 30
percent in the country's capital region during the last week of
February.
</P>
<P>
There were 97 cases admitted to the San Lazaro Hospital, the
main state-run infectious disease hospital in Manila, with no
deaths last week as compared with the 133 cases recorded in the
previous week.
</P>
<P>
A significant decrease was also noted in the cases coming from
the region's Valenzuela and Quezon City, the Philippine News
Agency quoted Reodica as saying.
</P>
<P>
There were 11 cases in Valenzuela and 15 cases in Quezon City
in the third week of February, while the following week registered
only five and four cases respectively.
</P>
<P>
Reodica noted that the successive decreases in the number of
cases demonstrated the positive response of the public to the
efforts of the Health Department in controlling the disease.
</P>
<P>
"Health programs are vital instruments for healthy and
productive individuals," Reodica said. "But the cooperation of the
public as proven by the voluntary submission of their children for
measles vaccination is the true mechanism by which this health
goal is achieved."
</P>
<P>
However, she added, efforts like immunization, information and
education campaigns need to be sustained in order to reduce the
number of children susceptible to measles.
</P>
<P>
The total number of measles cases admitted to San Lazaro
Hospital since January 1 stands at 1,889 including 74 deaths.
</P>
<P>
Most of the said cases were found to be in the age group of one
to four years, Reodica said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
