<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Nuclear Waste Train Reaches Dannenberg, 8 Hours Late </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The train carrying nuclear waste
reached Dannenberg early today, eight hours behind schedule, where
its cargo would be loaded on heavy trucks for Wednesday
transportation to an underground storage depot at Gorleben, about
20 kilometers away.
</P>
<P>
About 5,000 anti-nuclear protesters demonstrated in this town
of northern state of Lower Saxony, about 1,000 of them involved in
violent clashes with the police, said reports reaching here.
</P>
<P>
It was not yet available how many people were injured or
arrested in the clashes.
</P>
<P>
A total of 30,000 police were mobilized to shield the train --
the biggest police operation in postwar Germany, with the security
cost being estimated around 100 million marks (60 million
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The train carried six containers of highly-radioactive spent
nuclear fuel rods, with four from two power plants in southern
Germany and two from a French nuclear reprocessing plant.
</P>
<P>
It was put together in the town of Walheim in southern state of
Baden-Wuerttemberg and started on its 20-hour trek across Germany
on Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
Late Monday, several hundred protesters lied on the railway
tracks linking Lueneberg with Dannenberg to block the train, two
of these people chained themselves to the rails.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the train stranded for 13 minutes near the town of
Goettingen as protesters entered a railway tunnel and hurled
stones at police.
</P>
<P>
Anti-nuclear protesters in Dannenberg earlier Monday clogged
the road heading for Gorleben with tractors and barricades, who
also dug a 10-metre-wide and 2-metre-deep trench in the middle of
road and set a barricade on fire.
</P>
<P>
On the way to Dannenberg, police had to remove protesters, iron
bars and other obstacles from tracks. There were also bomb threats
and a police spokesman voiced concern over the potential for
violence from extremists among demonstrators. 
</P>
