<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-04 14:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu: Har Homa Construction Delayed Only for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin
Netanyahu announced today that the controversial Har Homa
building in East Jerusalem would be delayed for a few days for
technical reasons.
</P>
<P>
The first stages of the controversial building project, which
will build 2,500 of the total 6,500 housing units in three
years, was originally expected to start today with Housing
Ministry surveyors coming to work at the construction site.
But Netanyahu ordered the delay Monday night until "certain
technical and legal factors" were resolved.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in an interview with the state-run Israel Radio,
Netanyahu reiterated the delay was only due to technical
reasons. He also denied that it was connected to his
scheduled visit to Egypt Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu is expected to hold discussions with Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak and other officials on the current
situation following Israel's decision last week to build the
settlement in Har Homa. The Egyptian government has strongly
criticized the Har Homa settlement decision, saying it was
unacceptable and harmful to the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the criticism by U.S. President Bill Clinton
on the Har Homa decision, Netanyahu said that there was
nothing new in the U.S. opposition to any Israel's building
plan in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters Monday before holding talks with
visiting Palestinian Authority President Yasser Arafat, Clinton
said he preferred the Har Homa decision, which he called
would build mistrust, had not been made.
</P>
<P>
Clinton added that when the Israeli government made the
decision on the Har Homa project, it had taken into account all
possible reactions.
</P>
<P>
Israel has come under strong international criticism over the
Har Homa issue, as Arafat was striving to solicit all pressures on
Israel to reverse the decision.
</P>
<P>
On the further Israeli troop pullout from the rural areas of
the West Bank which has been also delayed, Netanyahu reaffirmed
his commitments to carrying out the withdrawals after the cabinet
makes a decision Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israeli right-wing politicians criticized Netanyahu
for delaying the Har Homa project. Uzi Landau, Chairman of
the Knesset (Parliament) Foreign Affairs and Defense Committee,
said today that Netanyahu's hesitancy had opened the way for
outside pressure.
</P>
<P>
Landau also blasted Netanyahu for not presenting to the U.S.
government a list of Palestinian violations of the peace
accords during his visit to Washington last month. He claimed
that this allowed Arafat to win points by attacking the Har
Homa project.
</P>
<P>
In reaction to press reports that the government might
agree to widen the scope of further troop withdrawals to
appease the Palestinian anger over the Har Homa decision, a
group of rightist lawmakers are meeting this afternoon to
formulate their pressure on the government not to hand over
more land to the Palestinian side.
</P>
<P>
Michael Kleiner, head of the Front for Land of Israel
that comprises 17 Knesset members, said that the group would
oppose hand-over of any land in Area C, which is now under
total Israeli control. 
</P>
</TEXT>
