<HEADLINE> China to Set up Altaist Institute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, March 4 (Xinhua) -- China is planning on setting up a
state institute for Altaists as part of the efforts to promote
studies in the field of Altaic languages, which comprises the
Turkic, Tungusic, and Mongolian subfamilies.
</P>
<P>
Some 50 national minorities in Middle, West, and Fareast Asia,
and in Eastern Europe belong to the family, including 18
nationalities from China, such as Uygurs, Mongolians, and Manchus.
</P>
<P>
Altaist studies were developed in the 1960s, and since that
time the Permanent International Altaistic Conference (PIAC) has
held 36 international conferences.
</P>
<P>
Major studies have been made in languages, literature, history,
and religions.
</P>
<P>
Altaist studies in China began in the 1980s and developed
quickly with a great number of papers having been published on the
Altaic language, literature, history, philosophy, religion, and
folk ways.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
