<HEADLINE> China on Move To Build New Chemicals City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Construction of a huge 1.4-
billion-yuan chemicals complex has begun in the city of Cangzhou
in north China's Hebei Province.
</P>
<P>
The project, expected to produce 20,000 tons of TDI annually,
marks a new step in the country's effort to build its third
chemical industrial city in Cangzhou, about 200 kilometers south
of Beijing, officials from the municipal government told Xinhua
News Agency.
</P>
<P>
TDI is a kind of raw material used to make various chemical
products. Cangzhou is known for its abundance of natural gas and
gasoline, and it also can produce 1.5 million tons of raw salt
each year. These factors combined have laid a sound foundation for
the city to develop its chemical industry, they said.
</P>
<P>
As construction of the complex forges ahead, officials said,
building of 10 large-scale projects revolving around the Cangzhou
Oil Refinery and a gigantic chemical base of chlorine soda have
entered a "substantial" stage. The refinery-related projects and
the chemical base are estimated to cost over three billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Cangzhou has more than 600 chemical enterprises. Its fertilizer
plant, oil refinery and chemicals complex, well known both at home
and abroad, have become pillar industries of the burgeoning city.
</P>
<P>
So far, a project capable of producing 10,000 tons of resin has
gone into operation and an 80-million-yuan caustic soda plant has
started production.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
