<DOCNO> XIE19970304.0157 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 500 People in Nanjing Become Organ Donors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Many Chinese have decided to make
a final contribution to society - by donating organs for medical
research.
</P>
<P>
In Nanjing, the capital of east China's Jiangsu Province, more
than 500 people have joined the Friends of Organs Donors group, an
unofficial organization that solicits people to donate organs to
hospitals and medical institutes when they die.
</P>
<P>
Many people decided to become donors after they heard that
Deng, who died at the age 93 on February 19, had told his family
to donate his corneas to an eye bank and offer his organs to
medical research after his death.
</P>
<P>
"We're deeply touched by Deng's philosophical view of life and
death. We think we should follow him to make contributions to
medical research," said Professor Yuan Shenglin of Nanjing
Agricultural University, and his wife.
</P>
<P>
And, added Lin Ye, a donor from the Nanjing Meteorological
Institute, "Deng devoted his entire life to the country and the
people. He has set a very good example for us."
</P>
<P>
The number of people who applied for membership in the Friends
of Organs Donors, the first of its kind in China, went from 440 at
the end of February to over 500 at present, according to a report
in Shanghai's "Wenhui Daily". Of them the oldest is 87 years old
and the youngest only 20. About 80 couples have joined the
organization.
</P>
<P>
The proposal to donate organs was made by a dozen retired
government officials and teachers two years ago. The recent
establishment of the organ donors' organization was also
encouraged by local government officials and the Nanjing Red Cross
Society.
</P>
<P>
Although cremation has become popular among Chinese urbanities
because of several decades of reforms, most Chinese still feel a
bit strange about donating parts of their bodies for medical
research, or even organs for living patients.
</P>
<P>
"We'll make a great effort to encourage more people to join us
in this," Lin Ye noted.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
