<HEADLINE> Northwest China Benefiting From Foreign Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, March 4 (Xinhua) -- More than 37,000 women have
learned additional practical techniques and 1,600 have become
literate in northwest China's Gansu Province thanks to an
assistance program of the UN Population Fund.
</P>
<P>
Three poverty-stricken counties have benefited from the "women,
population and development program", one of several successful
programs in the province receiving help from UN organizations and
various countries.
</P>
<P>
The aid began in Gansu in 1982, and 250 projects have been
implemented, with 141 million US dollars in funds.
</P>
<P>
Of six water conservation projects financed by the UN Food
Program, five have been completed and 20,000 hectares of land
improved, 4,000 hectares of forests planted, 1,600 kilometres of
roads built, and more than 10,000 poor households moved to better
places.
</P>
<P>
Funds from Japan, Canada, Australia and other countries and
organizations have helped the province preserve cultural relics,
finance poverty relief, and protect the environment.
</P>
<P>
Gansu also sent more than 4,000 of people abroad to study or
receive technical training, while 100,000 more were trained at
home, obtaining useful information through direct contacts with
foreign experts.  enditem
