<HEADLINE> Iraqi Missile Engines to Be Transported Abroad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Preparations are under way for
shipping Iraqi missile engines abroad for inspection in
accordance with an agreement between Iraq and the U.N. Special
Commission (UNSCOM) on the dismantling of Iraqi mass destruction
weapons, Iraqi newspaper Babyl reported today.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted a U.N. source in Baghdad as saying that work
is in full swing in packing the engines, but he declined to
specify a date for their shipment abroad, saying it will take
place in the near future.
</P>
<P>
The UNSCOM is making sure that Iraq has actually destroyed the
"Scud" missiles Iraq has procured from the former Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
Press reports from the U.N. say that the Security Council has
decided Monday to maintain the sanctions imposed on Iraq for its
failure to abide by the related U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
This decision was taken at a closed-door Security Council meeting
in which Rolf Ekeus, UNSCOM chairman, accused Baghdad of
continuing to hide biological and chemical weapons.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council imposed sanctions on Iraq following
Iraqi invasion of Kuwait in 1990. 
</P>
