<HEADLINE> Thailand to Launch Entertainment Program to Fight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Thailand will create about 1,500
playgrounds nationwide to attract people from drug addiction in a
bid to ease drug abuses in the country, a senior Thai drug
official said here today.
</P>
<P>
The program is designed as one of the country's measures to
prevent drug abuses, said Prija Champaratna, secretary general of
the Office of the Narcotics Control Board (ONCB) of Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The authorities will use open places near governmental
buildings or parking lots to create the playgrounds to attract
more people, especially children, to do exercises or take up
sports activities instead of using drugs, Prija told a press
conference at the U.N. Conference Center in Bangkok.
</P>
<P>
Prija also said that the Thai government has achieved some
progress eradicating drug abuses over the past years, especially
early this year after Chavalit Yongchaiyudh took office as the
country's new prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Chavalit, who is also chairman of the ONCB, is
serious about the crackdown on drug abuses, Prija said, but adding
he hoped to see the efforts continue throughout this year to make
greater achievements.  
</P>
