<DOCNO> XIE19970304.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese, British Experts Reach Consensus on HK Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Experts on the Sino-British
Joint Liaison Group (JLG) reached consensus on Hong Kong's 1997-98
budget at their 19th meeting here today, thus completing their
work on the matter, a Chinese representative on the JLG said.
</P>
<P>
At a news briefing held here today, Chen Zuo'er, head of the
Chinese experts team for the budget, said the consensus will
ensure a smooth transition and normal operation for Hong Kong's
public finance and social services around the handover of Hong
Kong's political power.
</P>
<P>
The budget covers 12 months from April 1, 1997, to March 31,
1998. Since March 1995, the Chinese and British experts on the JLG
had held 19 rounds of talks on the drafting of the budget.
</P>
<P>
Chen said the budget had been drafted in line with the three
principles raised by the Chinese side at the end of January
1996: taking the related stipulations in the Basic Law as the
guideline, taking into account the interests of all sectors in
Hong Kong and systematically drafting the budget on the basis of
cooperation between the Chinese and British sides.
</P>
<P>
During the budget-drafting process, the Chinese side listened
to the opinions and suggestions from various sectors in Hong Kong,
he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that after Tung Chee Hwa was elected as the first chief
executive of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR),
the Chinese side of the JLG timely informed him of the progress
in the budget drafting process.
</P>
<P>
He said the drafting of the budget had taken into consideration
Tung's views and received his support.
</P>
<P>
Chen added that the budget has laid a sound foundation for the
budget of the HKSAR government in the next fiscal year and it will
play an important and positive role in the economic development
and the improvement of people's life in Hong Kong in the coming
years.
</P>
<P>
Facts show that so long as the Chinese and British sides act in
accordance with the Sino-British Joint Declaration on the
Question of Hong Kong and adopt a positive and pragmatic
attitude, Chen stressed, they will remove obstacles in their
talks and contribute to Hong Kong's smooth transition and smooth
transfer of government.
</P>
<P>
Chen said that as the 1997-98 financial budget strides over
June 30, 1997, some special arrangements have been made for its
drafting, enacting and enforcing processes.
</P>
<P>
He said that before the chief executive of the HKSAR was
elected, the budget had to be discussed between and drafted by the
representatives of China's central government and the British
side.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the 1997-98 budget has now been worked out and
the drafting of the 1998-99 budget for Hong Kong will be totally
the responsibility of the HKSAR government.
</P>
<P>
He noted that China's central government will not participate
in working out the next budget and it is confident of the ability
of the HKSAR government to manage public finance well.
</P>
<P>
Chinese and British experts on the JLG held a dinner here
tonight to mark the completion of the budget and Chief Executive
Tung was present at the dinner.  
</P>
</TEXT>
