<HEADLINE> Macao Textile Industry Expects 20 Percent Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Macao's textile and garment-making
industry is expected to grow by 20 percent this year, and will
remain the dominant products for exports, a Macao industry expert
says.
</P>
<P>
Lionel Vai Tac Leong, chairman of the Textile and Garment
Committee of the Macao Productivity and Technology Transfer
Center, said that he estimated the textile and garment-making
industry will receive an extra 20 percent orders this year.
</P>
<P>
Macao's export of textile and garments to the United States,
Macao's leading market of such items, declined slightly after the
US customs imposed special restrictions on imports from Macao. The
export is expected to pick up this year after a consensus was
reached between the US customs and the Macao Government last year.
</P>
<P>
"Macao businessmen are quick to learn new things and have wide
contacts with the rest of world," Leong was quoted by the "Tai
Chung Pou" as saying. "Those advantages will make Macao survive in
the fierce competition from neighboring regions."
</P>
<P>
He said 85 percent of Macao's exports will be textile and
garment products this year as the proportion of toys exports
dropped sharply last year.
</P>
<P>
Textile and garment products and toys are the two leading goods
of exports of Macao.
</P>
<P>
Many Macao toy factories have moved to neighboring Guangdong
Province in China's mainland because the labor cost there is much
cheaper. Some garment factories have also started to move to the
inland because of a shortage of labor in Macao.  
</P>
</TEXT>
