<HEADLINE> Liberia's Warlord Taylor Accused of Hiding Arms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The Liberian peace process which is
currently progressing towards general elections received a jolt
following allegations of a former warring faction led by Charles
Taylor on concealing weapons.
</P>
<P>
Press reports here today revealed allegations that members of
the National Patriotic Front of Liberia (NPFL) led by Taylor have
been hiding their arms instead of handing them over to the
western African peacekeeping force, known as ECOMOG.
</P>
<P>
A former captain with the defunct NPFL was quoted as saying in
Cote d'Ivoire over the weekend that he knew where all the arms
are hidden and could direct ECOMOG to the sites.
</P>
<P>
Disarmament and demobilization of Liberia's rival factions
were concluded in early February this year.
</P>
<P>
During the exercise, more than 30,000, or 91 percent of the
factional fighters, were disarmed by ECOMOG, while some 14,156
pieces of arms, 1.65 million rounds of ammunitions and 4,369
bombs were recovered.
</P>
<P>
However, Taylor denied the charge, saying that it was a
propaganda meant to set ECOMOG against him.
</P>
<P>
"There may be bigger hands behind this one but those hands are
going to fail. ECOMOG must win this war," Taylor said.
</P>
<P>
He also alleged that there are some external forces whose aim
is to destabilize the forthcoming election scheduled for May this
year and probably delay it for two to three years.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG announced that it has uncovered a large amount of
weapons buried at a diamond depository. The cache includes
assorted riffles and rocket propelled grenades discovered during
a raid following information received from the public.
</P>
<P>
The weapons were found at Lofa bridge, about 60 kilometers
west of Monrovia, capital of Liberia. The area was contested by
the former United Liberation Movement (ULIMO) factions before the
disarmament exercise.  
</P>
</TEXT>
