<HEADLINE> China Hopes Signatories Keep WTO Promise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 4 (Xinhua) -- China has urged the signatories to
the World Trade Organization to turn their words into actions, by
keeping their promise to adopt a positive attitude in the
discussion of China's entry into the WTO.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Ministry Spokesman Tang Guoqiang told a press conference
here today that some WTO members recently had stated that they
would make positive gestures for China's accession to the WTO.
</P>
<P>
"We wish that these parties keep their words in solving some
practical problems in the process of talks," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that China held extensive bilateral discussions on the
WTO issue with Japan, the European Union and the United States
between January and February.
</P>
<P>
These discussions have laid the foundation for the third
meeting of the WTO Working Party on China to be held in Geneva
this month, he said.
</P>
<P>
"China is willing to accept the trade rules that are
universally accepted by all other WTO signatories," he said. "But
we cannot accept excessive, irrational demands." 
</P>
