<HEADLINE> South Korean President Names New Prime Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, March 4 (Xinhua) -- South Korean President Kim Young-sam
today appointed former Seoul Mayor Koh Kun as his new prime
minister in a bid to rescue his image from the effects of the
recent Hanbo loans scandal.
</P>
<P>
Koh replaces Lee Soo-sung who was sacrificed after 15 months in
the job to carry the can for the scandal involving 600 million
U.S. dollars of loans to Hanbo Steel company which collapsed in
January.
</P>
<P>
In a secret vote today by 256 of the 299 legislators in the
National Assembly, the country's parliament, Koh was approved by a
vote of 198 to 51, with three abstentions and four invalid votes.
</P>
<P>
Koh Kun, current head of Myongji University, was the mayor of
Seoul from 1988 to 1990 under former President Roh Tae-woo, but
quit in a row with the administration over a corrupt land deal
involving the same Hanbo Group.
</P>
<P>
Koh's appointment was well received since he is considered a
politically neutral person with managerial expertise and is widely
respected.
</P>
<P>
He also enjoyed an unblemished reputation during his 30-year
career in public service, receiving support from more than 40
opposition legislators in the parliamentary vote. 
</P>
</TEXT>
