<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Growing into Leading Corn Producer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, March 4 (Xinhua) -- China is becoming one of the
world's leading corn producers and processors, following years of
bumper harvests and the successful diversification of the staple
agro-produce.
</P>
<P>
Total acreage of maize now tops 20 million ha. In 1996, China
harvested more than 100 million tons of corn, a record high output
that accounted for one-fifth of the world's total, sources from
the Ministry of Agriculture said.
</P>
<P>
Corn, rice and wheat are three major crops in the world. And
production of corn is considered a yardstick for measuring a
nation's grain producing capacity and its level of husbandry.
</P>
<P>
Maize is planted throughout China, but three major producing
areas -- the North, the Huanghuai Plains, and the Southwest --
account for four-fifths of the country's total output, while using
only one-fourth of its total acreage.
</P>
<P>
The northern maize area envelops Jilin, Heilongjiang, Liaoning
and Hebei provinces, while Huanghuai Plains cover Shandong, Henan
and Jiangsu provinces and the Southwest involves Yunnan, Guizhou
and Sichuan provinces.
</P>
<P>
Experts attribute the dramatic rise of corn output to the use
of science and technology in growing the crops and the remarkable
expansion of its acreage. Over the past several decades, China has
nurtured a few generations of high-yield maize seeds, which have
helped boost per-hectare yield five times over with the aid of
fertilizer. In the 1950s, the country's total corn output was 16
million tons.
</P>
<P>
By adopting diversified development and processing techniques,
China has turned corn into feed, industrial raw materials and
export commodities.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
