<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Needs One Million New Jobs Annually </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Lagos, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria needs to create one million jobs
annually in order to catch up with growth in its population, the
"Vanguard" reported today.
</P>
<P>
Issac Aluko-Olokun, a member of the Vision 2010 Committee was
quoted as saying this at a workshop on Nigeria's Vision 2010 in Lagos
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The former Chairman of the National Planning Commission under
the interrim national government said that Nigeria's population
of 102 million will double in 20 years.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that 34 percent of the population now live below the
poverty line, with only 10 percent above the poverty line.
</P>
<P>
The unemployment rate announced by the government is less than two
percent, but the true situation might be far worse than that. A report
in 1996 said more than half of the country's youths are jobless.
</P>
<P>
To make it worse, Aluko-Ololun said, it is not easy to tell where
the jobs will come from, since Nigeria is a consumer nation rather
than a producer nation.
</P>
<P>
He called for massive investment in human capital development
through adequate funding of the educational sector, saying that
education is critical to the success of the economy.
</P>
<P>
He also called for reforming of the country's civil service system,
continued privatization, better infrastructure and improved investment
environment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
