<HEADLINE> Mbeki Warns Black Business Against Parasitic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Deputy President Thabo Mbeki
has warned black business consortiums to decrease their reliance
on pyramid structures as a vehicle for black economic
empowerment, said a source here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the launch of National Empowerment Corporation
(NEC) here Monday, Mbeki said black business should not project
itself as a "parasitic class" that could only thrive on pillaging
state resources.
</P>
<P>
He was reportedly referring to some black empowerment deals
which were limited only to existing economic activities and
created no new jobs.
</P>
<P>
The government would like to see the emergence of more black
consortiums, he said, adding that their investment should focus
on sustainable growth and job creation in sectors such as
manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, NEC chairman Mashudu Ramano said his company would
focus on growing businesses in the industrial, financial
services, printing and retail sectors within the next two years.
</P>
<P>
Ramano said the NEC's major long-term objectives are to
"obtain financial empowerment by acquiring meaningful stakes in
growth sectors, and economic empowerment by participating at an
operational level."
</P>
<P>
The NEC, with a total investment capital of 275 million Rand
(about 60 million US Dollars), would be listed on the
Johannesburg Stock Exchange within three years, added Ramano.
</P>
