<DOCNO> XIE19970304.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Food Structure Changes Likely to Ease China's Grain Shortage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, MARCH 4 (Xinhua) -- The availability of more
processed food items and diversified means of producing them
will help to alleviate China's grain shortage, a team of experts
say.
</P>
<P>
The team, under the Hangzhou-based China Rice Research
Institute, said that the modern concept of nutrition focuses on
the human body's intake of balanced nutrients rather than how many
kilograms of grain a person consumes.
</P>
<P>
The experts are taking steps to persuade people to abandon the
traditional belief that their predominant source of food should be
grain.
</P>
<P>
Jiang Yuming, a research fellow heading the team, said that
grain is rich in carbohydrates but contains relatively small amounts
of amino acids and vitamins which are needed by the human
body. Additionally, he said, it is not economical to feed animals
with grain.
</P>
<P>
A quarter of China's 480 billion kilograms of grain output is
used as animal feed. This practice must be changed, and production
of grain rations for human consumption should be separated from
that of feed, Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
Experiments show that the same tract of land used for green
feed or non-grain food instead of grain production yields three
times more protein, fat, carbohydrate and other nutrients.
</P>
<P>
Those plant nutrients can be translated into non-grain food
when they are eaten by animals, poultry and fish. A greater share
of non-grain food in Chinese people's dietary pattern will not
only improve food quality, but will also save a significant amount
of staple grain for more people.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said the direct consumption of grain is not the best way
to support the world's largest population.
</P>
<P>
The agronomist said production of green nutrients will also
promote China's environmental protection and ensure a sustained
agricultural development.  enditem



nnnn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970304.0180 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Records Nearly 17,000 Land Sale Deals in February </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Land Registry
recorded a total of 16,979 sale and purchase agreements in
February for building units, including residential and
non-residential properties.
</P>
<P>
The figure represents a drop of 13.9 percent from January and
an increase of 85.1 percent over February last year, according to
an official release today.
</P>
<P>
The total consideration of these agreements in the month was
73.5 billion HK dollars (9.42 billion US dollars), down 15.1
percent but up 182.4 percent, respectively, as compared with the
amounts of January this year and February last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
