<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda to Build Power Plant in North </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Uganda has decided to build a new
hydro-electric power plant on Karuma Falls on the river Nile in
the northern part of the country.
</P>
<P>
Local daily The Monitor said today that the plant, at a cost
of 165 million U.S. Dollars, will be built by two construction
firms -- Pakwach Power Plant Ltd. of Uganda and Norway's Norpak
company.
</P>
<P>
The plant will supply electric power to all districts of
northern Uganda and regions of Soroti, Mbale and Tororo in the
east.
</P>
<P>
According to a Norpak survey, the district where the plant is
to be located will need 200 milliwatts to run industries and
domestic appliance.
</P>
<P>
Gabriel Olweny, a Norpak official, said the two companies will
manage power distribution together, but he did not confirm a
launch date for the plant. 
</P>
</TEXT>
