<HEADLINE> 60,000 Mozambican flee Floods in Malawi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, March 4 (Xinhua) -- As many as 60,000 Mozambicans have
fled floods in Malawi, Mozambique's Natural Calamity Prevention
and Combating Department (DPCCN) estimated here today.
</P>
<P>
The Mozambican government is trying hard to bring these
refugees home, the Mozambican Information Agency quoted Zamissa,
the chief of DPCCN who is leading a delegation which just
returned from Malawi, as saying.
</P>
<P>
Despite the help of his department, flood refugees in Malawi
have been in trouble and urgently in need of food, he said.
</P>
<P>
Food and other flood relief are still air-dropped in the
seriously flood-hit Tete and Zambezia Provinces, said Zamissa.
</P>
<P>
Water levels of rivers in Alta Zambezia as well as in Nampula
and Cabo Delgado Provinces are rising in recent days while water
of the rivers of Licungo and Lugela have flooded Alta Zambezia
region, he said.
</P>
<P>
He urged residents living along the rivers to leave these
lowlands for dry upcountry for safety.
</P>
<P>
The rainy season will stop in Alta Zambezia and the two North
Provinces in late March, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Children's Fund has donated 10,000 U.S. Dollars and
medicine to Mozambique since this southern African country made a
call on international community for flood relief last week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
