<HEADLINE> Earthquake Rocks Eastern Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, March 4 (Xinhua) -- A strong earthquake, measuring 5.6
on the Richter scale, rattled the eastern part of Japan today,
disrupting railway services and power supply. But there were no
immediate reports of injury.
</P>
<P>
The epicenter of the quake, which took place at 12:51
p.m. local time, was in the Izu region in Shizuoka prefecture,
about 100 kilometers (60 miles) southwest of Tokyo, where the
quake was felt.
</P>
<P>
The temblor was the latest and largest of more than 2,300
earthquakes which have shaken Japan's Izu Peninsula south of Mount
Fuji since Monday.
</P>
<P>
A quake with a magnitude of 5.0 on the Richter scale hit the
area on Monday, causing landslides, rupturing water and gas pipes
and cracking roads and bridges.
</P>
<P>
Local police and fire stations said there were no immediate
reports of injury. Railway officials said local and Shinkansen
bullet train services were partially suspended. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
