<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Butterfly Museum Popular in Guilin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Strings of colorful artificial
butterflies hang from a large tree in Guilin, a scenic city in
south China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region, serving as a sign
of welcome to those visiting the museum for butterflies.
</P>
<P>
The Diecai Butterfly Museum has received tens of thousands of
visitors from both at home and abroad since it opened in August of
1995. It is being run jointly by Liu Yaping, a self-employed
businessman and the Binjiang Park in Guilin, best known for its
picturesque mountains and rivers.
</P>
<P>
Covering an area of 300 sq m, the museum displays some 5,000
butterflies in over 300 categories.
</P>
<P>
The exhibits include teinopalpus aureus, bhutanits thaidina,
and the Chinese agehana elwesi, which are rare Chinese butterflies
under state protection, and precious butterflies from South
America, Indonesia, and Japan, such as the M. Didus tingo masia.
</P>
<P>
According to Liu Yaping, some of the exhibits are each worth
more than 10,000 U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970304.0217 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Experts Call for Effective, Rational Use of Overseas Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Leading economists in China said
effective and rational use of overseas funds is crucial to the
country's future opening-up efforts.
</P>
<P>
The economists, who are here attending the Fifth Session of
the Eighth National Committee of the Chinese People's Political
Consultative Conference, expressed their approval of the part
concerning overseas investment in Premier Li Peng's government
work report.
</P>
<P>
In the report, Li said China should continue to effectively use
overseas funds, channel more funds into agricultural development,
infrastructure, comprehensive utilization of natural resources,
and high and new technology industries, and toward central and
western regions of China.
</P>
<P>
A report released by the State Statistics Bureau shows that
China used about 51 billion US dollars in overseas funds last
year, including 11 billion in loans and 40 billion in direct
investment.
</P>
<P>
Although meeting the pre-set target, experts said, there do
exist problems "which merit concern."
</P>
<P>
Among the problems they enumerate: some local authorities pay
more attention to the amount of overseas investment attracted than
to investment quality, neglecting assessment of state-owned assets
and the credit of investors; there has been a lack of effective
policy guidance on fund flow with the result that funds did not go
to basic, hi-tech industries that need investment fund most; and
that the growth of foreign investment in interior China is still
lower than in the eastern part.
</P>
<P>
Professor Wang Chuanlun from the People's University of China,
a CPPCC National Committee member, suggested strengthening
guidance over and management of overseas capital utilization.
</P>
<P>
"If we intend to acquire new technology and managerial
expertise, then we should attract direct investment from foreign
businesses, especially from ransnationals" he said.
</P>
<P>
Member Wang Linsheng, a professor of Beijing University of
Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation, said, "When we open
China's market in a planned way and try to attract more foreign
investment, we need to formulate policies to standardize
competition and prevent monopoly."
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government started major policy adjustments on
attracting foreign investment last year.
</P>
<P>
The overall import tariff level was reduced from 35 percent to
23 percent on April 1, 1996; on July 1, overseas-funded businesses
were given access to the country's foreign exchange buying and
selling system; and from December 1, the Chinese yuan became
convertible on the current account.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the central government gave provincial governments
the authority to approve of foreign-funded projects worth a
maximum of 30 million US dollars, from 10 million as had been the
case previously. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
