<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda Distribute Relief in East </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Uganda Authorities distributed
their first batch of relief in eastern Kumi district last Friday,
a report reaching here said today.
</P>
<P>
Almost each of over 5,600 residents in Aakum and Aakide in the
district received one kilogram of maize meal and one kilogram of
beans.
</P>
<P>
This was the first aid relief by the government to help more
than 37,000 people in the drought-hit district.
</P>
<P>
Joab Mutanga, the outgoing resident district commissioner of
Kumi, said, ''Aakide and Aakum were given the priority because
they were the worst hit areas.''
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said eastern Uganda is the most affected by
the dry spells in the country, and Kumi is one of the district
suffering the drought.
</P>
<P>
Valdo Odeke, the district agriculture officer of Kumi, said
people of eight of sixteen counties in his district are already
starving. Many people eat one meal while others eat once in two
or three days.
</P>
<P>
Rainy season is expected to be delayed for a month, and that
will deteriorate the food situation in the country, the
meteorology department warned yesterday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
