<HEADLINE> Beijing Mayor Expects More Funds from Japanese Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Beijing Mayor Jia Qinglin said
today he expects a Japanese bank to expand its business in the
Chinese capital.
</P>
<P>
The mayor said that the Bank of Tokyo-Mitsubishi Ltd. was the
first Japanese financial institution to establish business
contacts with Beijing, adding that he believes cooperation between
the bank and Beijing has bright potential.
</P>
<P>
Tsuneo Waki, chairman of the bank's board, told Jia that the
bank will make contributions to Beijing's economic construction.
</P>
<P>
Jia told Waki and his entourage that Beijing is presently
implementing the Ninth Five-Year Plan (1996-2000), during which
large amounts of overseas funds will be needed.
</P>
<P>
Given that, Waki said, the bank plans to invest more in the
city.
</P>
<P>
The bank, one of ten overseas banks setting up branches in
Beijing, was formed last year by the Bank of Tokyo and the Bank of
Mitsubishi. 
