<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Hosts International Symposium on Wetlands Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIDAIHE, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The International Workshop on
Wetlands and Water-Bird Conservation opened today in Beidaihe, a
sea-side resort in north China's Hebei Province.
</P>
<P>
Over 120 experts and government officials from Japan, Russia,
the Republic of Korea, Australia, the US and China will hold
academic discussions on the protection of wetlands and water-birds
in the world, and also conduct some on-the-spot investigations.
</P>
<P>
The four-day symposium will also determine the level and mode
of international cooperation for the protection of wetlands and
water-birds in northeast Asia, and will approve a "Beidaihe
Declaration" on the protection work.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, participants will discuss the establishment of a
protection network for cranes in northeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
Wetlands, a kind of important natural ecological system and
known as the earth's "kidney," play an invaluable role in
adjusting climate, conserving water, preventing soil-erosion and
resolving pollutants in addition to serving as habitats for a
variety of the world's rare water fowl.
</P>
<P>
Wetlands include all kinds of natural and artificial areas such
as marshlands, lakes, rivers, pools, reservoirs and rice fields.
</P>
<P>
China has 63 million hectares of wetlands, accounting for 11.9
percent of the world's total, which stands at 573 million hectares.
</P>
<P>
The country also has high and cold wetlands on west China's
Qinghai-Tibet Plateau, which is a rarity.
</P>
<P>
The symposium is sponsored by China's Ministry of Forestry,
Japan's Environmental Agency and the Asia-Pacific Branch of the
Wetlands International.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
