<BODY>
<HEADLINE> impact of pollution on investment in Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Environmental pollution may affect
investment in Zambia, particularly in its Copperbelt province, if
left unchecked.
</P>
<P>
The warning has been expressed by visiting south african
investor Stuart brooker who is leading a team of experts to carry
out feasibility studies on the establishment of a food processing
plant in Ndola, capital of Copperbelt province.
</P>
<P>
the local press today quoted brooker as saying that emissions
from lime, cement, copper refinery and other factories will
likely affect major investment prospects.
</P>
<P>
the dangerous effects of the emissions may cause diseases such
as tuberculosis and other chest ailments if left unchecked.
</P>
<P>
''foreign investors will not operate in an unhealthy
environment such as that prevailing on the Copperbelta because of
health risks,'' brooker said.
</P>
<P>
the south african businessman appealed to the Zambian
government to strengthen its law on environmental pollution
culprits to ensure a suitable environment to attract more foreign
investors to Zambia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
