<HEADLINE> Japanese Celebrity Won Chinese Honor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, March 4 (Xinhua) -- An influential Japanese businessman
has been granted the honorary title of "Ambassador of
Sino-Japanese Friendship" for his outstanding contributions to
educational development in China.
</P>
<P>
Since 1986, 69-year-old Ryojiro Kojima, president of the Kojima
Press Industry Co. Ltd, has visited northwest China's Qinghai
Province nine times and donated 500 million Japanese yen to build
an educational development center there.
</P>
<P>
With his financing, a well-equipped training center was also
set up at Qinghai University, while funds were established to
award outstanding young teachers and college students.
</P>
<P>
Kojima, who is also the province's first honorary citizen, said
that he would do more to boost education in Qinghai, where the
world-famous Yellow River and Yangtze River originate.
</P>
<P>
A source from the Sino-Japanese Friendship Association said
that since 1993, 33 Japanese people have received the honorary
title. 
</P>
</TEXT>
