<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Represent Africa at France's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Some 400 South African
artists will be representing the country at an
end-of-the-millennium cultural festival to be held in Nantes,
France in October, local daily the Star reported today.
</P>
<P>
Johannesburg is one of only three cities chosen to take part
in the festival and will represent Africa, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The artists chosen will represent a wide spectrum of South
African culture, said Victor Modise, Johannesburg council's head
of arts and culture.
</P>
<P>
"There will be musicians reflecting the wide range of musical
genius in South africa, from traditional to contemporary.
</P>
<P>
"There will be playwrights and actors, visual artists,
dancers, both classical and contemporary, poets and writers and
finally academics and intellectuals, who will take part in
various discussions and debates," Modise said.
</P>
<P>
Besides, lesser or more locally known artists will also fly to
France to introduce Europe to South African music, he said.
</P>
<P>
The other two cities chosen to participate in the Nantes
International Festival are New York and Tokyo, with the former
representing the "new world" and the latter representing the
Asian continent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
