<DOCNO> XIE19970304.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Unveils New Auto Emission Standards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The Canadian government today
unveiled new standards for auto emissions and gasoline content in
a bid to reduce pollutants from motor vehicles and fuels.
</P>
<P>
New emission standards for cars, which starts with 1998 models,
will reduce hydrocarbons by 30 percent and nitrogen oxide by 60
percent.
</P>
<P>
"One way to deal with the problems caused by automobile
pollution is to reduce the levels, amounts and toxicity of the
emissions coming out of the tail pipe," Environment Minister
Sergio Marchi was quoted as saying today.
</P>
<P>
Canada will also limit the benzene content of gasoline to one
percent, about half of current levels.
</P>
<P>
By 1999, annual emission of benzene will be reduced by about
3,000 tons, Marchi told an environmental workshop in Toronto.
</P>
<P>
The minister also announced improvements to the Canadian
Environment Protection Act, which would provide wider jurisdiction
to regulate the quality of fuel used by cars.
</P>
<P>
Though the new emission standards were greeted as "admirable,"
some environmentalists insist that they will barely make a dent in
the reduction target for greenhouse gases.
</P>
<P>
The government has vowed to cap greenhouse gas emissions at
1990 levels, but Canadian cars, factories and buildings are
pumping out ever-increasing amounts of pollution.
</P>
<P>
It's estimated that emissions of greenhouse gases have risen by
at least six percent since 1990. This makes it almost impossible
for Canada to fulfill the commitment it made at the Rio summit on
environment, reports said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970304.0236 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Africa's Exports Drop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Africa's share of global exports
reduced from 3.1 percent in the 1950s to only 1.2 percent in the
early 1990s, representing a foreign exchange loss of about 65
billion U.S. Dollars in 1990 prices.
</P>
<P>
The latest Standard Chartered Bank Africa quarterly review
attributed the decline in African exports to the continent's
heavy dependence on primary products with raw material accounting
for over 80 percent of its exports.
</P>
<P>
Overvaluation of African currencies has created loss of market
share even for the products in which sub-Saharan Africa has a
clear-cut comparative advantage, according to the review.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile a World Bank research also said that african
freight rates are often considerably higher than those on
similar goods from other regions making freight costs a much more
serious barrier to African exports than protectionism. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
