<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Economic Growth Tops Priority for Ethnic Regions: CPPCC Members </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Members of various ethnic groups
of the Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC)
National Committee cited it as an urgent task of national minority
regions to develop economy and catch up with the affluent coastal
area at an earlier date.
</P>
<P>
China's 55 minor ethnic groups distribute mainly in outlying
mountainous, desert and grassland regions, and some of them still
in primitive society decades ago, and their economy is in a
relatively backward stage because of geographical, historical and
other factors.
</P>
<P>
Members of the CPPCC National Committee from various ethnic
minority regions, who are attending the top advisory body's fifth
annual session in Beijing, noted that local governments have made
poverty alleviation and education the first priorities on their
medium and long-term work agenda.
</P>
<P>
Qabe Cedan Puncog, an expert of Tibetan history, said it is the
Tibetan people's wish to develop economy, shake off poverty, and
become well-to-do.
</P>
<P>
"Most Tibetans hope to lead a modern life and enjoy modern
civilization," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Professor Mahsut Akbar of the Uzbek ethnic group in
northwestern Xinjiang Uyghur Autonomous Region said that people of
national minorities, too, want to live a new life and have enough
to eat and wear, send their children to new-type schools and
improve the quality of their religious life.
</P>
<P>
All the members believed that their people have benefited from
the country's modernization drive.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to a hydroelectric station built by the government in
the late 1980s, people of the Blang ethnic group in southwest
China's Yunnan Province have since had access to television.
</P>
<P>
"Television is very popular with our people, especially with
the young people, as it has acquainted us with what's happening
outside and taught us how to use new fertilizers," said Lu
Shixian, a middle school headmaster of Blang ethnic origin.
</P>
<P>
Last year, China's Tibet Autonomous Region had its first listed
company, first solar power station, and first modern library, and
1.2 million Tibetan people participated in elections of township
people's congresses. A survey released in the year indicated that
the vast mority of Tibetan people felt contented with the economic
development over the past dozen years.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, the central government, along with provinces
and municipalities in the interior and coastal areas, has offered
much aid and investment to ethnic minority regions in the fields
of economy, science and technology, and culture.
</P>
<P>
However, Pan Lizhen, a biologist of the Mulam ethnic group in
south China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region, reminded other
members that ethnic regions should not rely on outside assistance
alone for development.
</P>
<P>
"What is more important is to have our own talents in science
and technology," said Pan, who is striving to introduce a new
animal fodder locally for the development of animal husbandry.
</P>
<P>
While seeking economic development, Mahsut said, the people of
ethnic minorities should be mindful against a handful of people
with ulterior motive to create confusion, turmoil and even go in
for separatism.
</P>
<P>
"What these sinister people fear are the modernization and a
happy life we are working for," he noted.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
