<HEADLINE> Foreign Investors Eye on Northeast China Economic Zone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, March 4 (Xinhua) -- A succession of prestigious
trans-national companies have come to the Changchun Economic
Development Zone in recent years, making it a vital economic
center in northeast China.
</P>
<P>
Changchun, approved by the State Council as an export-oriented
state development zone in 1993, absorbed 220 million US dollars of
overseas funds in 1996, making up 70 percent of the city's total
overseas investment.
</P>
<P>
To provide a better investment environment, the zone has raised
800 million yuan by issuing bonds and shares and selling land-use
rights to build 14 roads, lay water mains and gas pipelines and
hook up local companies with the Internet.
</P>
<P>
To date, over 180 overseas-funded enterprises have settled in
the zone, bringing in a total contractual volume of 530 million US
dollars. Eleven projects each involved an investment of more than
10 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Owens Corning Company, a leading fiber-glass manufacturer
in the United States, Pepsi Co Inc., also in the US, and the Lion
Group in Malaysia have invested in electronics, auto, grain
processing and refined chemical projects in Changchun.
</P>
<P>
With more overseas investors flowing into the region, the zone
will encourage joint development by several large companies in a
bid to expand production scale. Projects on the government's lists
include an "electronic city," which covers 50 ha of land, and the
Industrial Park of Taiwan region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
