<HEADLINE> South China City Economy Climbing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Economic growth is expected to move
moderately faster in the city of Haikou, capital of China's Hainan
Province and the country's largest special economic zone,
according to the city's Mayor Zeng Haorong.
</P>
<P>
Zeng told Xinhua News Agency in a recent interview that the
economy in Haikou started gaining strength in 1996 after a steady
two-year decline.
</P>
<P>
Haikou's economy registered a 1.6 percent rise in 1996 over
that of 1995, with a GDP of 9.88 billion yuan. Output of
agriculture rose 8.2 percent, while that of industry grew 6.9
percent.
</P>
<P>
Zeng attributed the upswing of the economy to massive
restructuring of its economic development focus -- from real
estate to sectors like industries, transport, tourism, commerce,
trade, banking, science and technology, and information.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, Haikou became one of the 50 cities in China slated for
experiments in optimizing capital structures. Cashing in on the
opportunity, the city extensively revamped its industrial
enterprises, bankrupting three firms, merging three others, and
reorganizing a dozen.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the city used 490 million US dollars of overseas
investment, most of which was channelled into infrastructure and
major industries.
</P>
<P>
This year, experts have a bright outlook for Haikou's
economy. GDP output is expected to grow five percent to hit 11
billion yuan, while investment in fixed assets is estimated at 6.5
billion yuan, an 8.3 percent rise over last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
