<HEADLINE> Northwestern Uganda Hit by Bombs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Northwestern Uganda' town of
Koboko was hit by bombs allegedly from southern Sudan last
Saturday, according to a report from today's New Vision paper.
</P>
<P>
Two grass thatched houses in the town were hit and set blazed,
said the report.
</P>
<P>
However, the report failed to tell if there were any
casualties.
</P>
<P>
Military sources in Koboko claimed that the bombs came from
areas west of the border town of Kaya in southern Sudan.
</P>
<P>
Travelers from Koboko which is located one kilometer east from
Zaire and 12 kilometers south from Kaya, said 10 bombs landed
around the town.
</P>
<P>
The Ugandan army did not counter attack with shelling, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
Francis Ayume, the Ugandan Minister for Lands, Housing and
Urban Development, visited the town after the shelling.
</P>
<P>
Colonel Wamala Katumba, the operation commander of Uganda
People's Defense Forces in West Nile, said the situation there
was under control.
</P>
<P>
No official response from the Ugandan authorities so far has
been available.
</P>
<P>
There was mounted tension in southern Sudan and rumors from
there said rebels from the Sudan People's Liberation Army (SPLA)
were preparing their offensive against Sudanese government
troops. The Christian SPLA took up arms in 1983 to fight the
Moslem North in Hhartoum for autonomy and other rights in the
south. 
</P>
</TEXT>
