<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fujian to Eliminate Absolute Poverty This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, March 4 (Xinhua) -- East China's Fujian Province has
decided to eliminate absolute poverty this year, three years
earlier than the country's scheduled target.
</P>
<P>
Fujian's 270,000 poor people, or one percent of the province's
total population, are mainly living in 113 remote towns in 11
counties. With a harsh natural environment and poor transportation
services, poverty-relief efforts in these areas are difficult.
</P>
<P>
The local government plans to send 200 provincial officials to
the poor towns to directly head the relief work this year. To
provide additional assistance, provincial government departments
will continue to set up sister-relationships with poor towns.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, 22,700 poor residents living in areas with no basic
living conditions will be moved to more prosperous areas.
</P>
<P>
The province has made substantial progress in the past several
years in pulling itself out of its circumstances. In 1996 alone,
Fujian raised 427,000 people out of poverty. But natural disasters
last year sent some 190,000 residents back into near-destitute
situations.
</P>
<P>
China set the poverty line at the annual per capita income
level of 530 yuan. Based on this calculation, the country now has
65 million people living in poverty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
