<HEADLINE> More State Firms in Shanghai Go Bankrupt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Latest statistics show that 44
large and medium-sized state-owned firms in Shanghai, the largest
city in China, went bankrupt last year.
</P>
<P>
During the year, the municipal courts dealt with 52 bankruptcy
cases involving state enterprises, recording total property valued
at three billion yuan and debt of 5.1 billion yuan. The
enterprises had a total work force of 60,000.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai has allowed more companies to file bankruptcy
applications over the past two years in a move to quicken its pace
of reform of the state-owned firms, according to the local
government.
</P>
<P>
Bankruptcy cases of large and medium-sized state-owned
enterprises have been on the rise across the country during this
period, especially in the old industrial bases such as Shanghai
and Liaoning Province in northeast China.
</P>
<P>
Officials attribute this mainly to the firms' outdated
technology and equipment, an irrational product mix and
mismanagement.  
</P>
</TEXT>
