<HEADLINE> Former Center of Chinese Revolution Beats Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Over 130,000 poor people were lifted
out of poverty last year in northwest China's Yan'an, the city
known as the cradle of the Chinese revolution.
</P>
<P>
In the 1930s, Yan'an was the headquarters of the Chinese
Communist Party, and its political reputation was later spread
overseas by Edgar Snow, an American reporter who visited the area
and wrote the book, "The Red Star Over China."
</P>
<P>
Yan'an has been involved in a poverty-relief campaign since
1986, and the number of poor people has dropped from 670,000
in that year to the current 250,000.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that since 1990, the city has spent over 50
million yuan (about 6.3 million US dollars) on more than 70
projects to develop its industry, infrastructural facilities and
technology. Some 1,000 villagers were organized by the government
to visit prosperous regions in other provinces to learn advanced
agricultural techniques.
</P>
<P>
The city has set up six major regional production bases,
covering a total area of 600,000-plus mu (over 40,000 hectares),
with two mu per capita.
</P>
<P>
Technical personnel have been dispatched to poor villages to
provide services and training for farmers, benefiting some 100,000
local residents. Eighty-two percent of the farmers have set up
their own business and have a stable income. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970304.0259 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> A Look at the U.S. Human Rights Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
7. Human Rights Violations Against Other Nations
</P>
<P>
The U.S. human rights record outside its territorial boundaries
is not that glorious either. Since its founding over 200 years
ago, the U.S. has launched more than 70 wars and acts of
aggression against other countries, killing countless foreign
civilians with its troops and weapons.
</P>
<P>
The United States is the only country in the world which has
actually used nuclear weapons. It has conducted more nuclear
tests than any other country and possesses the largest nuclear
arsenal. A 1995 report said that America had 25,000 nuclear
weapons. Since the explosion of its first atomic bomb in 1945,
America has conducted 1,030 nuclear tests, accounting for more
than half of the world's total of 2,037 tests.
</P>
<P>
Its military spending is also the largest in the world. In
1994, it amounted to 274.3 billion dollars, more than twice as
much as the combined spending of eight other countries including
Russia, China and India. Currently, its average daily spending on
nuclear weapons is 80 million dollars. From 1940 to 1995,
America's total nuclear weapons spending was four trillion
dollars. Its nuclear weapons spending in 1995 alone was 27 billion
dollars. If this money was used to solve the poverty problem in
third world countries, it would relieve hundreds of millions of
people from poverty.
</P>
<P>
The United States has long maintained many military bases in
various places outside its territorial boundaries and deployed
hundreds of thousands of troops there. Its overseas troops have
committed numerous human rights violations against local citizens.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970304.0260 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Facts &AMP; Figures for 1996: Telecommunications (14) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 4 (Xinhua) -- China's post and
telecommunications sector achieved a business turnover of 133.5
billion yuan in 1996, up 35.4 percent over 1995.
</P>
<P>
The capacity of program controlled exchanges increased from
more than 80 million ends in 1995 to more than 100 million ends at
the end of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The rate of access to telephone service nationwide rose from
4.66 percent in 1995 to 6.2 percent last year, while that in
cities grew from 17 percent to 22 percent.
</P>
<P>
A national roaming service was set up for mobile
telecommunications, with the digital mobile telecommunications
network covering 261 cities and more than 1,000 counties. The
network was also connected with those of some other countries and
regions.
</P>
<P>
The number of mobile phone users reached 140,000 at the end of
1996.
</P>
<P>
China invested 98 billion yuan in the post and
telecommunications sector last year, completed optic fiber cable
trunk lines that link Beijing-Taiyuan-Xi'an, Wuhan-Chongqing,
Jinan-Qingdao, and Nanjing-Hangzhou, and built or expanded 31
satellite stations.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970304.0261 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> A Look at the U.S. Human Rights Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The rape of a 12-year-old schoolgirl in Okinawa, Japan, in 1995
by three American servicemen and the beating to death of a South
Korean woman in 1996 by a U.S. soldier, are just two of the latest
examples. Statistics indicate that since 1967, a total of 34,900
cases of rape, beating and murder of local people by South
Korea-based American servicemen have been reported, on average
three cases a day. Since 1972, U.S. troops in Japan have committed
4,716 crimes, or 205 cases a year, against local people, 106 of
which were targeted against women.
</P>
<P>
According to reports in the February 10, 1997, edition of the
Washington Post, in late 1995 and early 1996 amid Okinawans'
furious protests against American soldiers' rape of the
schoolgirl, American troops there "accidentally" fired 1,520
uranium-tipped bullets on an island near Okinawa.
</P>
<P>
America is the world's largest arms dealer. Its overseas arms
sales since 1989, according to a December 12, 1994 Time magazine
article, hit 82.4 billion dollars, more than the combined total
(66.8 billion dollars) of all other countries in the world, and
now its share of the world's arms sales market has reached 70
percent.
</P>
<P>
The German pictorial Der Stern reported in 1995 that America
had captured three quarters of the post-Cold War world weapons
market, reaching 146 countries and regions. More and more American
weapons have been used to trigger wars and unrest, said the
pictorial. USA Today also reported in 1994 that warring parties in
39 of the 48 ethnic conflicts around the world in the previous
year obtained weapons from the United States. No wonder the
U.S. has been dubbed "the world's largest exporter of death."
</P>
<P>
America is also the world's leading waste exporter. To evade
the responsibility of harnessing pollution within U.S.
territory, the authorities and capitalists have been trying all
means, fair or foul, to export waste overseas, especially to
developing countries. Such toxic garbage is seriously damaging
the environment of these countries and jeopardizing the health of
their people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970304.0262 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> A Look at the U.S. Human Rights Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The United States reportedly produces 275 million tons of toxic
waste a year, with over 10 million tons exported to the third
world. In 1995 alone, a May 4, 1996 article in Thailand's New
Chinese Daily News reported, the United States exported 200
million pounds (90,800 tons) of plastic waste to about 30
countries and regions including China. U.S. businessman William
Ping Chen smuggled 238 tons of garbage to China in just six months
from July to December 1995.
</P>
<P>
While U.S. human rights reports rattle on about human rights
violations in other countries, it has been refusing to join the
major international conventions on human rights adopted by the
United Nations. They include the International Covenant on
Economic, Social and Cultural Rights; the International Convention
on the Suppression and Punishment of the Crime of Apartheid; the
Covenant on the Elimination of All Forms of Discrimination against
Women; and the Convention on the Rights of the Child.
</P>
<P>
As for the International Covenant on Civil and Political
Rights, the United States reluctantly ratified it only in 1992, 26
years after it was adopted by the United Nations. And it
restricted the covenant's implementation strictly within the
framework of its constitution by adding a string of reservations,
understandings, statements and agreements so that the document
would apply only to the federation, not to the states, and could
not come into force automatically. These preconditions make the
document not worth the paper it is written on.
</P>
<P>
The United States' hegemonic acts of refusing to accept
international norms and frequently infringing upon other
countries' sovereignty and human rights have earned it the
notoriety of being the most condemned country in the world at the
end of this century.
</P>
<P>
As a popular saying goes, one should first correct oneself
before trying to correct others. It is bizarre indeed that the
United States, with such a poor human rights record of its own,
should act as the world's human rights judge and concoct human
rights reports year after year, mounting "crusades" against other
countries.
</P>
<P>
If the United States insists on having its own way, it will
inevitably provoke more counterattacks from other countries. In
the end, it will only hurt itself with the very stick it has been
brandishing against others. We strongly advise the U.S. government
to put its own house in order before pointing its finger at other
countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970304.0263 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Official on Peace Talks, Fighting with KNU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, March 4 (Xinhua) -- A high-ranking Myanmar military
official said here today that the government's current mopping-up
operation against the Kayin National Union (KNU), the largest
anti-government ethnic armed group in the country, had inflicted
heavy losses to the KNU.
</P>
<P>
Colonel Kyaw Thein, head of the Office of Strategic Studies of
Myanmar Defense Services, disclosed at a news briefing that
government troops started the operation in areas of Kayin state
and Tanintharyi division on February 10 against the KNU, which has
been active along the Myanmar-Thai border for nearly 50 years.
</P>
<P>
He said the operation is still going.
</P>
<P>
"The situation of peace talks between the government and the
KNU right now depends on the KNU, whether they genuinely wish for
peace," he said. "If they wish for peace, the door is open."
</P>
<P>
The Myanmar government and the KNU started their first round of
peace talks in December 1995 after the government unilaterally
suspended all operations against the KNU in April 1992.
</P>
<P>
In the fourth round of talks in November last year, Kyaw Thein
said, the KNU backed down from all agreements reached previously
with the government and ignored calls to "re-enter the legal
fold."
</P>
<P>
He denounced the KNU for sponsoring meetings with some other
underground political organizations after the failure of the peace
talks and issuing statements against the government.
</P>
<P>
He also accused the KNU of allowing their camps based at the
Myanmar-Thai border to be used as staging points to "commit acts
of terrorism."
</P>
<P>
The KNU is the only remaining one of Myanmar's 16
anti-government ethnic armed groups which has yet to make peace
with the government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
