<HEADLINE> IMF Delegation to Visit Pakistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, March 4 (Xinhua) -- A five-member delegation of the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) will arrive here on Thursday on
a two-week visit to Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
The IMF team will hold extensive discussions with Pakistan
government officials for the third review of Stand-By Arrangement
(SBA) both on technical and policy matters, according to a local
press report today.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan has received two trenches of 80 million U.S. dollars
each from the reactivated and augmented SBA released by the IMF.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani government is facing a lot of problems in the
implementation of the SBA, which was agreed to and approved during
the caretaker government's tenure.
</P>
<P>
"We will apprise our position to the IMF team and we have
bright chances to get some conditions relaxed," the report quoted
an official source as saying.
</P>
<P>
After coming into power, the government of Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif has launched an extensive National Debt Retirement Program,
which has attracted a lot of money both in foreign and local
currencies.
</P>
<P>
The delegation will send its recommendations to the IMF
Executive Board for whether releasing or not the third trenche
from the SBA, the report said.  
</P>
