<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepal Denies Difference Over Major Hydro Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The Prime Minister's Office
(PMO) of Nepal has denied any difference within the government
over a major hydropower project in which a U.S. energy company has
shown its interest to develop.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Sher Bahadur Deuba's office Monday issued a
press release saying that the government wants to utilize and
develop the country's abundant water resources in the larger
interests of the nation and the people.
</P>
<P>
There is unanimity within the government that water resources
development activities should be transparent and based on the
concept of national consensus, the press release said.
</P>
<P>
Some local newspapers here recently reported that the PMO and
the Water Resources Ministry had a difference over whether to
allow an American group to invest and develop a 10,800-megawatt
hydropower project in West Nepal.
</P>
<P>
Enron Corp. of the United States last year contacted with the
PMO here and put forth its proposal for developing the Karnali
project, about 400 km from here, with some 9 billion US dollars on
a Build-Operate-Transfer (BOT) basis.
</P>
<P>
The PMO reportedly has been in favor of granting the Karnali
project to the U.S. company, which claims to be a leading
developer of independent energy projects in the world, in
accordance with the government's "first come, first serve" policy
on large hydropower projects.
</P>
<P>
However, the Water Resources Ministry delayed in deciding on
Enron's proposal and insisted that additional bids from other
foreign companies be invited for the project, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
Foreigners are highly interested in investing in Nepal's water
resources sector and proposals are coming in, the PMO's press
release said.
</P>
<P>
The Water Resources Ministry has initiated necessary steps
under the government's policy and will deal with any interested
private sector investor, it added.
</P>
<P>
The Nepali government has adopted a policy to encourage private
investment in developing the country's water resources.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Enron group, which expects to export power from
the Karnali project to India, has been lobbying for its
development plan, saying that any delay in the implementation of
the project would cost Nepal at least 2 billion dollars in power
revenue and tax every year.
</P>
<P>
According to the company, a process of competitive bidding for
such a big project would lower the values of Nepal's water
resources.  
</P>
</TEXT>
