<HEADLINE> Death Toll Rises to 127 in Pak Train Derailment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The death toll in the train
derailment, which occurred early Monday in central Pakistan, rose
to 127, the official Associated Press of Pakistan said today.
</P>
<P>
Rescue operations are still going on and the injured, about 450
people, have been shifted to various hospitals.
</P>
<P>
Five cars of the train, which was heading for Pakistan's
southern port city of Karachi, skidded off the tracks early Monday
morning outside the rural station of Mirshah near Khanewal,
northeast of Multan in Punjab province.
</P>
<P>
Passengers were enjoying sound sleep when the train derailed,
which could be one of the reasons for the high death toll, the APP
said.
</P>
<P>
The actual cause of the accident has not been found so far, but
some reports suggested that some problem in the brake system of
the train may have directly led to the derailment.
</P>
<P>
The train reportedly developed some problem in the brake system
just before approaching the Mirshah station, which made the driver
unable to stop the train, sources at the Khanewal station were
quoted as saying.  
</P>
