<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Bosses in Vietnam Blasted Over Labor Abuse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Firms from Taiwan, Hong Kong and
South Korea are the most sharply criticized companies in Vietnam
for alleged labor abuses, a Vietnamese labor official was quoted
as saying by a local magazine.
</P>
<P>
In an interview published in the latest issue of the Vietnam
Investment Review, Tu Le, a senior official from the Vietnam Labor
Union, said that overwork and physical maltreatment of workers are
the biggest problems.
</P>
<P>
Taiwan, Hong Kong and South Korea are among Vietnam's five
largest foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
Violations of labor rights generally occur in small joint
ventures or wholly foreign-owned ventures, in which the Vietnamese
side has minimal control, the official said.
</P>
<P>
Last week, he said, at Keyhing Toys, a wholly foreign-owned
company, more than 25 workers collapsed and 200 fell sick or
fainted because of acetone poisoning and overwork.
</P>
<P>
The company's employees had to work an average of nine to 10
hours a day, seven days a week for a salary of 200,000-250,000 VN
dong (18-22 U.S. dollars), in an atmosphere polluted by acetone.
</P>
<P>
The official alleged that in some factories, workers were
allowed to go to the toilet only once during working hours while
others were forced to sign contracts to make a specific number of
products in an impossibly short period.
</P>
<P>
Foreigners, due to their hot temper and language barrier, often
hit their workers and cut their salary for failing to say hello to
their bosses or for bad quality work, an official from the
Ministry of Labor, Invalids and Social Affairs said.
</P>
<P>
The best way to solve the problem is to impose tough punishment
for violations, officials stressed.
</P>
<P>
Last year, there were 63 labor disputes and strikes in Vietnam,
a 25 percent increase over 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
