<HEADLINE> Jakarta to Play Important Role in Satellite Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia will continue to play an
important role in the regional satellite business despite it is
facing with foreign competition, a senior telecommunications
official said.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia is not worried about foreign competition to its
position in the rapidly growing satellite business in Asia,
Djakaria Purawidjaja, director general of post and
telecommunications, said in Bali Island Monday when commenting on
reports that several countries in Southeast Asia were planning to
launch their own communication satellites soon.
</P>
<P>
"We cannot block technology development. Therefore, we cannot
prevent any country from launching its own satellite," reports
reaching here today quoted Purawidjaja as saying.
</P>
<P>
Despite the competition, he said, Indonesia would continue to
play an important role in the regional satellite business since
the country possessed certain comparative advantages over other
countries in ASEAN (Association of Southeast Asian Nations) and
even in Asia.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia was one of the first three countries after the United
States and Canada in the world to operate satellite since the
1970s so that it had thousands of experienced and qualified
experts and seven satellite operating companies.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia has operated three generations of Palapa
telecommunications satellite since 1970 to support its vast
communication areas as well as countries in the Asia-Pacific
region.
</P>
<P>
Thailand, Malaysia and Singapore, which each have embarked on
ambitious and costly programs to own and operate their own
satellites, relied on Indonesia's two Palapa satellites from the
1970s to the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
But since then the three countries have ordered satellites from
the United States, France and other Western countries and they
plan to launch and operate their own satellites soon.
</P>
<P>
Purawidjaja acknowledged that the mastery of satellite
technology by Indonesians was actually not better than other
countries but "we can provide better services thanks to our
qualified and experienced human resources."
</P>
<P>
He said Indonesian companies were world-class satellite
operators, providing optimism that Indonesia could compete with
other countries especially in ASEAN and Asia.  
</P>
</TEXT>
