<HEADLINE> Singapore Leaders in Defamation Suit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Senior Minister Lee Kuan Yew and
his son Deputy Prime Minister Lee Hsien Loong will be represented
by Queen's Counsel David Eady in their defamation suit against
Tang Liang Hong, a Singapore lawyer, the Straits Times reported
today.
</P>
<P>
It said that Eady, an experienced defamation lawyer, was
admitted by the High Court as the counsel for the Lees in the
first suit they filed last against Tang, the defeated opposition
Workers' Party election candidate.
</P>
<P>
Lee Kuan Yew and Lee Hsien Loong are suing the defendant for
his remarks in a June issue of the Hong Kong-based weekly, Yazhou
Zhoukan, about discounts on the Hotel Properties Limited (HPL)
apartment sold to the Lees.
</P>
<P>
A Queen's Counsel since 1983, Eady is known as the lawyer who
acted for Lord Denning, a well-respected British judge who was
sued for slander towards the end of his career in 1982, the
Straits Times report said.
</P>
<P>
It said that Eady also represented politicians, movie stars and
the British Broadcasting Corporation in numerous well-publicized
cases and was the lawyer for Lee Kuan Yew in his defamation suit
against J.B. Jeyaretnam, leader of the Singapore Workers' Party,
in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Lee, who was then prime minister, was awarded 260,000 Singapore
dollars (about 183,099 U.S. dollars at current exchange rate) in
damages on August 3, 1990, over the remarks made by Jeyaretnam on
the suicide of former national development minister Teh Cheang
Wan, who died in 1986 while being investigated for corruption.
</P>
<P>
The suit against Tang will be heard in the High Court on August
18, the report said, adding that Charles Gray, another Queen's
Counsel who is also a defamation specialist, was admitted last
November as the lawyer for Tang.
</P>
<P>
Tang is also facing a second defamation suit filed by the Lees
for his remarks on their purchases of HPL apartments at three
election rallies on December 31 last year.  
</P>
