<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Thai Govt Rushes to Calm Financial Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The Thai government is hastily
ushering in a big rescue package for the country's upset financial
market, which saw a suspension of share trading in the finance and
banking sectors Monday.
</P>
<P>
The government has designated three large local banks to
organize mergers, while ordering ten ailing finance firms to
increase their reserves or capital.
</P>
<P>
With the move, the government hopes that all commercial banks,
finance firms and credit financiers will add a total of 50 billion
baht (about 1.92 billion U.S. dollars) in reserves for substandard
loans within two years.
</P>
<P>
Thai Deputy Prime Minister and Finance Minister Amnuay Viravan
and Central Bank Governor Rerngchai Marakanond have required the
ten troubled finance firms to raise their capital by 8.2 billion
baht (about 315.4 million dollars) immediately.
</P>
<P>
The Stock Exchange of Thailand (SET) Monday ordered suspension
of share trading in the finance and banking sectors after some
finance firms reportedly suffered financial problems.
</P>
<P>
Local newspapers said that the suspension, the first one in the
21-year history of the SET, finally came after weeks of denials by
the government for serious problems in the financial sector.
</P>
<P>
The SET index lost 20.32 points to close at 707.24 on light
trading with 51 shares changing hands.
</P>
<P>
Thai Prime Minister Chavalit Yongchaiyudh called for investors
to remain calm, stressing the government would take care of
everything.
</P>
<P>
He urged people to refrain from rushing to liquidate investment
or withdraw from bank deposits.
</P>
<P>
Reactions to the government decision to suspend share trading
remained mixed.
</P>
<P>
Some analysts expressed welcome to the decision, but indicating
it came a bit late as rumors about difficulties in the financial
sector have been spreading over the past weeks.
</P>
<P>
With excessive expansion and over-lending to the property
sector, they said, some damage has been beyond repair.
</P>
<P>
Others said that the SET over-reacted. They said that the SET
suspended share trading in the two sectors, maybe it wanted to see
the government's reaction. But it should lift the suspension after
the government unveiled its rescue package.
</P>
<P>
SET President Singh Tangtatsawas said that the trading remains
halted because the authorities wanted to give time to investors to
analyze the new measures.
</P>
<P>
Singh said that the authorities are considering whether to
reopen trading for the two sectors, but the suspension of share
trading for the ten firms will remain.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
