<HEADLINE> IDB Expands Support to Private Sector in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The Inter-American Development
Bank (IDB) substantially increased its support of the private
sector in Latin America and the Caribbean last year.
</P>
<P>
The IDB approved six operations in 1996 for a total of 436
million U.S. dollars, more than doubled the 201.2 million dollars
in loans approved in 1995, according to an IDB news release today.
</P>
<P>
The loans included direct loans of 198 million dollars from the
bank and 238 million dollars of syndicated loans with funds
provided by private banks which signed agreements with the IDB,
the news release said.
</P>
<P>
The six projects approved in 1996 had a total of 958 million
dollars. Four of the projects were in the energy sector and two
others were in sanitation and transportation sectors.
</P>
<P>
The IDB said that the bank will give a priority to loans for
projects in the smaller countries of the region during 1997 in
order to attract private investment, accelerate economic growth
and meet infrastructure needs. 
