<HEADLINE> Sales of GM, Chrysler Slump in February </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Sales by the General Motors
Corporation (GM) on the United States market dropped by 7.5
percent in February, and Chrysler also saw a decline in the month.
</P>
<P>
General Motors said its car sales declined nearly 10 percent,
and sales of light trucks were down an estimated four percent.
</P>
<P>
Chrysler Corporation, the third largest car-maker in the U.S.,
said its sales were down three percent overall. Its car sales fell
seven percent while truck sales were flat.
</P>
<P>
The Ford Motor Company, the No. Two U.S. auto-maker, was
scheduled to announce its February sales on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Honda set a second consecutive monthly sales record.
Its U.S. sales increased nine percent, boosted by healthy demand for
its new CR-V sport utility vehicle and its Civic subcompact.
</P>
<P>
Other Japanese auto-makers will announce their sales in couple
of days.
</P>
<P>
Japanese car makers had particularly strong sales in January,
prompting America's Big Three automakers to complain that weakness
in the Japanese currency, the yen, was giving their competitors an
unfair advantage. A weak yen against the dollar makes Japanese
cars less costly. 
</P>
