<HEADLINE> China Sweeps Violators Out of Securities Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 4 (Xinhua) -- China will ban illegal operators
from its securities market beginning today, another harsh penalty
to stem market irregularities.
</P>
<P>
The securities watchdog, the China Securities Regulatory
Commission (CSRC), adopted a set of rules today that will
effectively strip the operating privileges, either temporarily or
permanently, of those who violate market order.
</P>
<P>
"Any market irregularities of securities institutions that are
reported are inevitably connected with individual actions, and the
new rules will help ensure a stable market order by wiping the
irresponsible individuals out of the market," said an official
with the commission.
</P>
<P>
The rules will govern senior management personnel in companies
listed in the securities market, in securities brokerages,
securities registration and settlement companies, and a number of
other securities intermediaries.
</P>
<P>
Violators who have been caught engaging in illegal activities
in the market will be banned from accepting any management
positions in listed companies or securities institutions for three
to ten years. In the most severe cases, the penalty will be a
permanent revocation of the right to engage in securities business.
</P>
<P>
"The commission will publicize the namelist of such market
violators through the media to warn securities institutions
against hiring them," said the CSRC official. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
