<DOCNO> XIE19970304.0308 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Poised to Become Biggest Market for Household Electrics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, March 4 (Xinhua) -- China is expected to become the
world's leading consumer of household electrical appliances within
a few years, thanks to a huge market potential and the country's
enormous population of 1.2 billion, experts predict.
</P>
<P>
The reasoning was made by experts and officials from the China
Association of Household Electrical Appliances under the Ministry
of Light Industry, which is scheduled to sponsor an international
exhibition on household electrics in Shanghai in October.
</P>
<P>
Major factors cited by the experts include what will soon be a
widespread trend of replacing used household electrical
appliances, a buying spree by an annual 7-8 million
soon-to-be-married couples, more space to accommodate household
electronics, including wide-screens and large-capacity
refrigerators, and marked rise in living standards within the vast
rural population.
</P>
<P>
During the 1997-2000 period, 70 to 85 percent of China's urban
households are expected to buy new color TV sets, refrigerators
and washing machines, while the rural areas will rapidly balloon
into a gigantic market for household electrical items due to
hoped-for improvement in both power supply and people's living
standards.
</P>
<P>
China's household electrical appliances sector has witnessed
rapid growth since the 1979 and has become an important industry
in the national economy.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, China's 33 key refrigerator producers churned out
9.6535 million fridges, of which 9.6343 million were sold.
</P>
<P>
Statistics also indicate that 6.9095 million air conditioners
were turned out by 39 major manufacturers last year, while the
output of washing machines stood at over 10 million. An
overwhelming majority of the air conditioners and washing machines
were sold.
</P>
<P>
In cosmopolitan cities, about 92 households out of every
hundred had had washing machines by the end of 1995, with ratios
of refrigerators and air conditioners hitting 88.95 percent and 17.09
percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
At the meantime, every hundred households in medium-and small
cities or townships had averaged about 17 color TVs, nearly 89
washing machines, 66 fridges and eight air conditioners. However,
the ratio of washing machines, refrigerators and air conditioners
in every hundred rural households were much lower, standing at
only 16, five, and 0.18 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
Experts said China's huge market potential in household
electrical appliances has lured international electrics giants and
caused an avalanche of Sino-overseas joint ventures in this
field.
</P>
<P>
The influx of overseas investors has ushered in hi-technology,
while the prevalence of international brand names has heightened
competition in China's household electrical appliances market.
</P>
<P>
Imported color TVs, air conditioners, washing machines and
video recorders are occupying a large slice of the China market,
with their market rate hitting 30.9 percent, 31.41 percent, 12.22
percent and 98.1 percent in the first half of 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970304.0309 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Aviation Sector Prepared for Direct Air Service across Strait </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The aviation sector on the Chinese
mainland has made adequate preparations for direct air service
across the Taiwan Strait, said China's top aviation official.
</P>
<P>
Chen Guangyi, director of the Civil Aviation Administration of
China (CAAC) and a member of China's top legislature, made the
remark when attending the ongoing Fifth Session of the Eighth
National People's Congress (NPC).
</P>
<P>
Chen, a NPC deputy from east China's Fujian province, said two
newly-built international airports in Fuzhou and Xiamen epitomize
the mainland's efforts to prepare for direct air links across
Taiwan Strait.
</P>
<P>
The three billion prepare Changle Airport in Fuzhou, provincial
capital of Fujian, is scheduled to become operational in coming
July, and the Gaoqi Airport in Xiamen has just completed a 1.8
billion yuan expansion project. Both airports are able to
accommodate Boeing 747s, the largest jetliner now in service.
</P>
<P>
Fujian will have four airports to service cross-strait flights,
provided two other smaller airports in two other port cities are
taken into account, said Chen.
</P>
<P>
More than one million air passengers have traveled across the
Strait annually in recent years, and passengers from Taiwan to the
mainland may travel with a single ticket by changing flight at
Macao, thanks to an agreement reached between the airlines on both
sides of the Straits years ago.
</P>
<P>
Chen urged the Taiwan authorities to size up the situation and
make the decision at the opportune time. "the establishment of
direct air links across the Strait is the trend of the times and
the aspiration of the people, and the relevant conditions are now
available," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, he added, if the Taiwan authorities deem that the
direct air service cannot be confined to Fujian province alone,
other big cities, such as Beijing, Shanghai and Guangzhou, can
also be open to cross-strait flights.
</P>
<P>
With Hong Kong's return to the embrace of the motherland
approaching, Chen said, the principles of "Hong Kong people
governing Hong Kong" and "a higher degree of autonomy" are also
applicable to Hong Kong's airline industry.
</P>
<P>
The CAAC will give an all-out support the development of Hong
Kong's air transport market and strictly respect the region's
autonomy in this regard, he said. "Hong Kong's status as an air
transport center will remain unchanged."
</P>
<P>
In spite of more air routes to open between the interior areas
and Hong Kong, the conventional practices with regard to the
opening of new routes and market development, will be maintained,
namely, air accesses can be obtained only with the consent of
other side on the basis of mutual reciprocity and mutual benefit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970304.0310 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Power Industry in Tibet Shows Momentum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The power industry department in the
Tibet Autonomous Region has worked out a detailed plan to make
sure that every town there has access to electric power by the end
of the century.
</P>
<P>
Over the next few years, a number of local power networks are
scheduled to go into operation. And by 2000, a backbone power net
in the central parts of Tibet, which will cover the major cities
of Lhasa and Xigaze, will be established.
</P>
<P>
Some power stations in remote areas also will be generating
electricity soon.
</P>
<P>
Through the year 2010, a large-scale power works in central
Tibet, five local power nets and a scattering of power stations in
remote areas will help fulfill the goal to provide electricity
throughout Tibet's townships.
</P>
<P>
By then, the total installed capacity of power in Tibet, which
now accommodates more than 2.3 million people in 1.2 million sq
km, will reach 1.19 million kw.  
</P>
</TEXT>
