<HEADLINE> Talks With Armed Rebels Collapse in Nicaragua </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANAGUA, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Peace talks between the government
and an armed group in Nicaragua were called off because of the
absence of the rebel delegation, said Interior Ministry
authorities today.
</P>
<P>
The talks were to have taken place Sunday between Interior
Minister Jose Antonio Alvarado and a faction of the 80 men, led by
Jose Sanchez Borge, from the North 3-80 Front in the community of
El Ayote, in the central department of Chontales.
</P>
<P>
The government calculates that there are about 500 re-armed men
in the north and central zones of the country.
</P>
<P>
Alvarado left here early Sunday morning for El Ayote, but
found, after travelling five hours over bad roads, that the
representatives of the group didn't show up at the planned venue.
</P>
<P>
According to the ministry source, the group failed to appear
because of a lack of coordination on the part of the government
delegates about the meeting place.
</P>
<P>
Alvarado did not rule out the possibility that Borge and his
men did not go to the meeting because they wanted to wait for the
results of a meeting, to be held March 8, between North 3-80 Front
leaders and the government.
</P>
<P>
Moises Obando, chairman of the El Ayote Peace Commission, said
the rebel group expressed its unwillingness to turn over its arms
as long as army and National Police remained in the area.
</P>
<P>
Alvarado said that the presence of both the army and the police
was important in the area where a lack of security prevailed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
