<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trade in Latin America grows in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The total trade volume in
Latin American countries amounted to 543 billion U.S. dollars in
1996, up 11 percent over 1995, according to the U.N. Economic
Commission for Latin America and the Caribbean (CEPAL).
</P>
<P>
The CEPAL said that exports from the region, including
intra-regional ones, climbed to 248 billion dollars while imports
totalled 295 billion dollars last year.
</P>
<P>
Commission figures show that the countries that increased their
export and import volumes most were Argentina, Brazil and Mexico,
since they increased their presence abroad significantly.
</P>
<P>
According to the CEPAL, most of the countries in Latin America
depend on imports of intermediate products, and their consumption
in world markets increase as their exports increase.
</P>
<P>
Exports from the region increased by 8-10 percent per year
during the 1990's, while imports increased by 12-13 percent, said
the organization.
</P>
<P>
It was said that the trade volume in Mexico made up 40 percent
of the Latin American trade in 1996. The import volume in the
country hit 88 billion dollars, an increase of 22 percent in 1996,
compared with 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
