<DOCNO> XIE19970304.0314 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South China Economic Zone To Improve Residents' Employment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, March 4 (Xinhua) -- South China's Shenzhen has come
up with a regulation that sets a ratio on local labor in the
city's employment scheme.
</P>
<P>
According to the regulation, local labor should account for 78
percent of the work force in wholesale and retail businesses, 50
percent in tourism and restaurants, 60 percent in the transport
industry, 80 percent in post and telecommunications, and 87
percent in finance and insurance.
</P>
<P>
'Local labor' in this case refers to people who have registered
as permanent residents in the city, said an official with the city
government. "The move is intended to promote employment among
local residents and to distribute labor resources in a more
reasonable way," he added.
</P>
<P>
Employers in need of workers should give public notice, the
regulation says, and those who cannot meet the required ratio
within a month can apply to the labor department for employment of
laborers from elsewhere. Employers are not allowed to reject the
application of local residents without providing a suitable
reason, it said.
</P>
<P>
Shenzhen is a special economic zone bordering Hong Kong, and
has established a new labor system to accommodate the market
economy. The city employs over a million people from other parts
of China, but stresses employment of local residents, which has
brought its unemployment rate to below 2.5 percent in the past two
years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
