<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian Court Rules on Priebke's Arrest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The arrest of former SS captain Erich
Priebke immediately following his acquittal on war crime charges
last August was justified, Italy's Constitutional Court ruled
today.
</P>
<P>
Priebke had appealed the decision by a Rome appeals court to
sign a warrant for his arrest after a military tribunal found him
guilty of mass murder, but freed him because extenuating
circumstances meant a 30-year statute of limitations applied..
</P>
<P>
Last September, the Court of Cassation judged his re-arrest
justified because Germany had requested Priebke's extradition to
try him for organizing the Ardeatine Caves massacre. In this, 335
men and boys were killed in 1944 to avenge the killing of 33
German soldiers by partisans.
</P>
<P>
Priebke will be tried for a second time in a military court,
following, earlier this month, the Court of Cassation's resolving
of a case of legal limbo in which the military and civil courts
said they were incompetent to hear the case.
</P>
<P>
Priebke was extradited from Argentina to Italy in 1994 to face
the war crime charges and has been in prison. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
