<HEADLINE> Facts &AMP; Figures for 1996: Legislation  (13) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The Eighth National People's
Congress (NPC) and its Standing Committee, China's top legislative
body, reviewed 31 draft laws in 1996, and approved 22 measures
during the year.
</P>
<P>
Among them, the revised version of the Criminal Procedural Law,
adopted in March of 1996 and effective on January 1 this year, has
been considered a milestone in the building of the country's legal
system.
</P>
<P>
Statistics showed that the Eighth NPC and its Standing
Committee have formulated 94 laws and decisions in the past four
years, accounting for nearly one third of the laws promulgated in
the past 18 years of reform and opening up.
</P>
<P>
According to the agenda, there are still nearly 30 laws and
decisions yet to be made in 1997, the last year of the Eighth
NPC's term of office.
</P>
<P>
These laws include the law on supervision, the securities law,
a unified contract law, and the law on state planning.  
