<HEADLINE> U.S. Approves 26 Billion Dollar Arms Exports in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The Clinton Administration
approved arms exports to 160 countries and regions worth 26
billion U.S. dollars in fiscal year 1996, an Arms Trade News
reported.
</P>
<P>
Of the total, 10.5 billion dollars consists of actual sales
made through the Pentagon's Foreign Military Sales program; more
than 14 billion dollars were licensed for export through the State
Department's Direct Commercial Sales program; and the remaining
828 million dollars of weapons were transferred through the
Pentagon's Excess Defense Articles program, the report said.
</P>
<P>
It said that Middle East countries received the lion's share of
Pentagon's exports with purchases totaling over 3.8 billion
dollars. The Far East bought some 3 billion dollars of U.S.
weapons.
</P>
<P>
The leading buyer of the weapons were Egypt with 1.4 billion
dollars in acquisitions; Saudi Arabia with 1.3 billion dollars;
South Korea with close to 1 billion dollars; and Israel signed
agreements totalling 883 million dollars, the report said.
</P>
<P>
It added that classified Pentagon exports increased by 208
million dollars from fiscal 1995 to 529 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The State Department approved exports to 154 countries and
regions, with the largest amount going to the Far East. Australia
and Japan were licensed for a total of 927 million dollars in
arms; Germany got 851 million dollars; and Taiwan was slated to
receive 787 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The report noted that the Pentagon sold arms to hostile NATO
neighbors Turkey and Greece in 1995 valued at 227 million dollars
and 205 million dollars respectively. Moreover, the State
Department issued 584 million dollars in licenses for arms buys by
Ankara and 253 million dollars worth of weapons for Athens.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
