<DOCNO> XIE19970304.0325 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand to Delay Liberalizing LPG Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The Thai government will delay
liberalizing the local liquefied petroleum gas (LPG) market until
the end of this year, according to a senior civil servant.
</P>
<P>
The civil servant was quoted today by local press as saying
that it was not timely to deregulate the LPG market just now
because of the very high price of LPG abroad.
</P>
<P>
The posted price of LPG in the Middle East now tops 300 U.S.
dollars per ton while the local ex-refinery price of LPG, which is
controlled by the government, is 245 dollars per ton, according to
the Petroleum Authority of Thailand.
</P>
<P>
If deregulation was undertaken now, the local LPG price could
rocket, possibly fueling political turmoil, the Department of
Commercial Registration warned.
</P>
<P>
LPG is the only oil product exempted from 1991 deregulation of
the oil market because it is used for cooking.
</P>
<P>
the civil servant said the government would be more inclined to
liberalize the local LPG market towards the end of this year when
world LPG prices were likely to have dropped to a regular level.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
