<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Crimes in Latin America Cost 200 Billion Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Crimes have cost Latin
America some 200 billion U.S. dollars in the past five years,
said Shahid Javed Burki, World Bank Vice-President for the region.
</P>
<P>
In Brazil, the annual losses caused by criminals represent 1
percent of the gross domestic product, which would equal to 7.5
billion dollars a year.
</P>
<P>
Secretary-General of the Organization of American States, Cesar
Gaviria, a former Colombian president, said that the annual murder
rate in Latin America of 30.7 for every 100,000 inhabitants is six
times higher than the world average.
</P>
<P>
Gaviria said that the increase in violence in the region is due
to social inequalities, disorderly urbanization, tolerance for the
consumption of alcohol, the possession of weapons, corruption and
impunity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
