<HEADLINE> Population Growth drops in Brazilian Cities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Population growth in the
big cities of Brazil dropped considerably between 1991-1996, the
Institute of Geography and Statistics says.
</P>
<P>
Sao Paulo, the biggest city, had a population growth of 1.5
percent in the last five years compared with 2.1 percent during
the previous decade, said the institute's report based on last
year's census published today.
</P>
<P>
Rio de Janeiro, the second largest city, had an annual
population growth of 0.8 percent during the recent five years, and
Belo Horizonte, the third largest city, 0.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
Department of Population and Social Indicators chief Luiz
Antonio de Oliveira said the demographical drop in the most
important cities was due to a drop in the birth rate and migration
flow, especially in Sao Paulo. 
</P>
