<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines to Renew Drive Against Dengue Fever </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 4 (Xinhua) -- In anticipation of the early onset
of rainy season this year, the Philippine Health Department will
again launch next week a campaign against the mosquito-borne
dengue fever, local newspaper the Manila Chronicle reported today.
</P>
<P>
Health authorities said Monday the early campaign will help
minimize the outbreak of the disease which reaches its peak in
rainy reason.
</P>
<P>
The large number of reported cases for January and February
also prompted the health department to move early, the paper said.
A total of 281 dengue fever cases were reported over the past two
months, which is much higher than the 100 cases for the same
period last year.
</P>
<P>
From January to July last year, 2,845 cases were reported by
the Health Department with 33 deaths.
</P>
<P>
Health authorities will re-launch its drive on March 19 to
alert the public against the danger of the dengue fever and ways
to prevent its spread.
</P>
<P>
The public is exhorted to cover all drums and water containers
and replace water in vases regularly to destroy mosquitoes'
breeding nest. They are also advised to burn their garbage.
</P>
<P>
Signs and symptoms of dengue fever include high fever, skin
rashes and blood in stool.
</P>
<P>
The Health Department also issued advisories on diseases common
in summer such as chicken pox, diarrhea and cholera. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
