<HEADLINE> Facts &AMP; Figures for 1996: Tourism (8) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Some 51.13 million tourists from
overseas, the largest number ever, visited China in 1996, up 10.22
percent over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The country's international tourism earnings hit an all time
high of 10.2 billion US dollars the same year, up 16.81 percent.
</P>
<P>
Domestic tourism earnings exceeded 163.8 billion yuan, up 19
percent. And total tourism earnings including those from overseas
hit 248.7 billion yuan, equivalent to four percent of China's GDP.
</P>
<P>
The growth of domestic tourism demonstrates that out of a
population of 1.2 billion almost every two Chinese made one trip
on average last year.
</P>
<P>
Among the 15 major source countries, Japan ranks first in the
number of tourists coming to China, a rise of 18.7 percent from
1995 and is followed by Republic of Korea, up 31.1 percent, and the
United States up 12 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
