<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Reports Initial Success in Reforming State Enterprises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Some of the measures listed by
Premier Li Peng in his government work report to rejuvenate the
loss-making state sector have proved effective in Shanghai, a
local official said here today.
</P>
<P>
"The policy of giving priority support for major state-owned
enterprises and allowing small ones greater freedom and
flexibility of operation has achieved initial success in this
major industrial city," said Xu Zhiyi, director of the Shanghai
Municipal Economic Commission, at a group meeting discussing
Premier Li Peng's government work report as a deputy to the
National People's Congress in session here.
</P>
<P>
"Other steps defined by the premier in his report, such as
standardizing bankruptcy proceedings, encouraging mergers and
supporting re-employment, have also proved feasible in Shanghai,"
Xu said.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has finally found the root to
problems plaguing state-owned enterprises and ways to solve
them, he said.
</P>
<P>
Since the early 1990's, Shanghai's economy with a concentration
of state firms has maintained a sustained, rapid and healthy
development, and achieved double-digit growth rates for six
consecutively years, according Xu.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai's GDP in 1996 was 13 percent greater than 1995, and
more than 97.8 percent of its industrial products were marketed.
</P>
<P>
He maintains that these have resulted from reform of the city's
state-owned sector in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Industrial restructuring has been stepped up, he said.
Industries that consume a lot of resources but are barely
profitable have been reduced in size, while priorities have been
given to the development of car, petro-chemical, metallurgical,
power, electronics, telecommunications and hi-tech industries.
These industries today contribute 56.2 percent of the city's
revenues, he said.
</P>
<P>
To optimize the distribution of state assets, the municipal
government has provided conditions for the emergence in recent
years of more than ten large enterprise groups, which hope to sell
100 billion yuan worth of products a year by the end of the
century, from today's 30 billion yuan, he said.
</P>
<P>
Restructuring measures in Shanghai include the purchase of
one firm by another, mergers, shareholding arrangement, property
rights transfer, and bankruptcy, he said.
</P>
<P>
Last year, he said, about 240 small state enterprises were
put in the charge of district and country governments, he said.
</P>
<P>
"With these measures, we hope to bring down the debt rate in
Shanghai's state firms by another seven percentage points this
year, to 80 percent for its state sector as a whole," Xu said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
