<HEADLINE> Fujimori Satisfied with Hostage Talks With Castro </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Peruvian President Alberto Fujimori
today expressed satisfaction with his talks here with his Cuban
counterpart, Fidel Castro, on solving the hostage crisis in Lima.
</P>
<P>
Fujimori described the talks as "productive", and said Cuba had
agreed to receive members of the Tupac Amaru Revolutionary
Movement (MRTA) who have been occupying the residence of the
Japanese ambassador in Lima since December 17.
</P>
<P>
This was on condition that a formal request be made, Fujimori
told a press conference given after the three-hour talk.
</P>
<P>
He said that the request would have to be filed by the Peruvian
and Japanese governments, signed by representatives of the
guarantor countries and accepted by the MRTA members who were
still holding 72 hostages in the Peruvian capital.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, the two leaders also discussed bilateral
cooperation in health and tourism, the Peruvian president noted.
</P>
<P>
Fujimori, who arrived in Havana this morning for a 12-hour
working visit, was accompanied by deputy Foreign Minister, Jorge
Voto Bernales. This is his first visit to the island as president.
</P>
<P>
The Peruvian President, in search for a peaceful solution to
the 75-day hostage crisis, made a trip to the Dominican Republic
ahead of his visit to Havana.
</P>
<P>
In talks with his Dominican counterpart, Leonel Fernandez, the
two tackled matters relating to the hostage crisis, including the
possibility of Santo Domingo receiving members of the MRTA
guerilla band. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
