<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines' Oil Import Increases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine net oil import bill
jumped 18 percent to 2.67 billion U.S. dollars in 1996 from 2.26
billion dollars in 1995 as world crude prices soared while local
consumption increased.
</P>
<P>
Citing data provided by the Energy Department, today's
newspaper the Philippine Star said the country's sustained
economic growth last year pushed up petroleum consumption by 5.8
percent to 131.6 million barrels in 1996 from the 1995 level.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the volume of crude importation was also higher
along with soaring prices on the world market.
</P>
<P>
The average crude cost of 19.32 dollars per barrel in 1996 was
16.2 percent higher than the 16.62 dollars per barrel posted in
1995.
</P>
<P>
Crude prices reached its peak last October at 22.59 dollars per
barrel, a result of higher demand for heating oil, strong buying
interests and successive leap of crude futures.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines' total crude requirement during the period was
almost 100 percent sourced through imports as local crude supplied
a paltry 0.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
Imported crude oil was acquired mostly from Middle East
countries, particularly Saudi Arabia which provided about 58
percent of the total. The Philippines also imported oil from some
African and Asian countries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
