<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> North China Region Uses Foreign Loans To Boost Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, March 4 (Xinhua) -- North China's Inner Mongolia has
borrowed 18.35 million US dollars from the World Bank to help poor
counties and leagues in education, public health, and farming.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the bank has provided the region with 25 million
US dollars in loans for rebuilding areas hit by an earthquake and
another 140 million yuan for improving the drinking water system
in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
During China's Eighth Five-Year Plan (1991-95) period, the area
signed 39 bilateral or multilateral contracts worth 700 million US
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The region also borrowed 50 million US dollars from the
governments of Spain and Belgium to import program-controlled
telephone switchboards.
</P>
<P>
A 943-km-long railway line has been built with a loan of 150
million US dollars from the World Bank, and local enterprises have
imported modern technology and equipment for technological
transformation with funds from other countries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
