<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Ministers Agree to Reduce Greenhouse Emissions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Environment ministers from the
European Union reached today an agreement to cut the bloc's
emissions of greenhouse gases by 15 percent of 1990 levels by
2010.
</P>
<P>
This objective enables the 15 EU countries to present a united
front at the meeting of parties to the Climate Change Convention
in Kyoto, Japan, in December.
</P>
<P>
Greenhouse gases, such as carbon dioxide from burning fossil
fuels, trap heat close to the earth's surface and are blamed for
what scientists fear will ba a long-term warming of the global
climate.
</P>
<P>
The ministers, who met in Brussels today and Tuesday, agreed on
how to share out individual cuts between countries for only 10
percentage points of the 15 percent pledged, an indication of the
difficulties the EU still faces with its announced target.
</P>
<P>
Dutch Environment Minister Margreet de Boer told reporters late
Sunday, when the 15 ministers met informally, that the 15 percent
figure was a firm commitment.
</P>
<P>
"We go to Kyoto with 15 percent and if that's agreed, then we
will negotiate about how to share out the remaining 5 percent
within the EU," she said.
</P>
<P>
In reaching a deal, ministers revised a previous proposal made
by the Netherlands, which holds the EU presidency, softening the
demand on most countries in striking agreement on the overall
figure, Dutch diplomats said.
</P>
<P>
Germany and Britain, two of the EU's major fossil-fuel users,
saw their allotted targets cut from 30 percent to 25 percent and
from 20 percent to 10 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
The target for France, with a majority of its electricity
coming from non-CO2-emitting nuclear power, was cut to zero from
the originally suggested 5 percent reduction while Italy's went
from the 10 percent cut proposed to 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
Other countries seeing their targets softened included Ireland,
to be allowed a 15 percent emissions increase instead of the
suggested 5 percent rise, Finland, granted an emissions freeze in
place of a 10 percent cut, and Greece, with a 30 percent increase
in place of 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Portugal's allowed emissions figure went up 15 percentage
points to 40 percent, Spain's rose two percentage points to 17
percent, and Luxembourg's 40 percent cut became 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
Belgium and the Dutch retained their 10 percent cuts while
Austria and Denmark kept their 25 percent cuts and Sweden its 5
percent rise. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970304.0359 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FIFA to Introduce New Game Rules from July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The International Federation of
Football Association (FIFA) has finalised rules concerning
players, goalkeepers and referees in a "much simpler and
contemporary language", according to a FIFA press release issued
today in Zurich.
</P>
<P>
At its 111th meeting held on March 1, 1997 in Belfast, the
International Football Association Board (IFAB) of the FIFA
decided to finalise the draft for a revised version of the Laws of
the Game. "The new version will contribute to a better
understanding of the Laws governing the game," says FIFA in the
press release.
</P>
<P>
Examining various specific issues, the IFAB also decided to
further extend the backpass ruling. As of July 1, 1997, when all
amendments will enter into force, an indirect free-kick will be
awarded if the goalkeeper handles the ball after receiving it
directly from a throw-in from his own team. For his part, the
goalkeeper may move on the goal line when a penalty-kick is
taken. Furthermore, a goal may be scored directly from kick-off.
</P>
<P>
The IFAB refused unanimously to authorize experiments with
video systems to assist the referee, including that requested by
the French Football Federation for the friendly international
match between France and Sweden on April 2, 1997.
</P>
<P>
Unsporting behavior, failing to respect the required distance
at a restart of play and delaying the restart of play will become
cautionable offences under the amended rules. But players who
enter the penalty area before the ball has been kicked need not
now be cautioned.
</P>
<P>
As a binding instruction to the referee, he has to consider
that the goalkeeper is wasting time and therefore has to award an
indirect free-kick, if the goalkeeper holds the ball for longer
than a maximum of six seconds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
