<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southwest China Province Redoubles Efforts To Combat Lake Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Southwest China's Yunnan Province
has vowed to improve water quality in scenic Dianchi Lake before
the end of this century and to restore its ecology by 2010.
</P>
<P>
The lake has a drainage area of 2,920 square kilometers and is
the main source of water for the industry, agriculture and
residents of the province's capital city of Kunming.
</P>
<P>
But, water quality has been deteriorating steadily in recent
years because of pollution, and the state, province, and city have
begun to pay greater attention to pollution control in the area.
</P>
<P>
Yunnan has promulgated a series of laws and regulations on
environmental protection in the lake area, and 23 plants with
serious pollution problems have been ordered to improve within a
certain period of time.
</P>
<P>
Construction projects in the region have also been strictly
watched, said an official with the city government.
</P>
<P>
The province has invested 420 million yuan (50.6 million US
dollars) in four sewage treatment plants since 1990, and its
capital city will be able to dispose of 365,000 cubic meters of
waste water daily by the end of this year. The figure accounts for
60 percent of the total that the city spews out, statistics show.
</P>
<P>
Yunnan has also spent 134 million yuan developing drinking
water resources, increasing the storage capacity of a major
reservoir to 229 million cubic meters from 70 million cubic
meters. A new waterworks is also under construction, and the city
has said its 800,000 residents will be able to drink better water
within two years.
</P>
<P>
In addition, with the support of the state, the province has
attracted 150 million dollars in loan from the World Bank for
environmental protection projects with the lake on the focus.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970304.0366 </DOCNO>
