<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany, France Agree on EU Reform Initiatives </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The German and French foreign
ministers said here today that they had agreed on a number of
initiatives on European Union (EU) reform, which would be jointly
submitted to the EU's ongoing Inter-Governmental Conference.
</P>
<P>
German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel and his French
counterpart, Herve de Charette, told reporters after a meeting in
Bonn that among other things, they had agreed that "strategic
decisions" of the EU should be made by consensus in the future,
and decisions on their implementations be made by "qualified
majority."
</P>
<P>
The two ministers also agreed that the role of the European
Commission president should be strengthened, and that the future
number of the commission members should be smaller than the number
of member states of an enlarged EU.
</P>
<P>
They also stressed the common will to gradually integrate the
Western European Union (WEU) into the EU structure, and said that
the government leaders of the EU should draw up guidelines for the
WEU's future mandate.
</P>
<P>
On the eastward expansion of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO), both sides expressed the confidence that a
compromise on NATO-Russian relations could be found before the
Western alliance's Madrid summit in July, either through a
"charter" or, as demanded by Moscow, through a binding treaty
which needs the approval of NATO members' parliaments.
</P>
<P>
The two ministers also stressed their governments'
determination to hold on to the January 1999 startup date of the
single European currency -- the Euro, saying that this would
encourage other EU members to make remarkable efforts in order to
qualify for the Euro. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970304.0368 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Admits Producing Large Amount of Deadly Nerve Gas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Iraq has admitted producing
large amounts of a deadly nerve gas agent in 1990 but up to now
has failed to convince U.N. experts that it had destroyed them as
claimed after the Gulf War, a U.N. official said today.
</P>
<P>
Rolf Ekeus, chief U.N. weapons inspector for Iraq, briefed the
Security Council today about the status of his team's efforts to
determine whether Iraq has complied with U.N. orders to scrap its
high-tech weapons programs.
</P>
<P>
According to Ekeus, as early as 1995, Iraq acknowledged having
produced small quantities of the nerve gas. But after further
investigation of the U.N. weapons inspection team, Iraq admitted
recently that it produced 3,800 kilograms of the deadly VX nerve
gas agent and destroyed them after the Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
Ekeus said the U.N. weapons inspectors were then taken to sites
in the desert where the destruction was said to have taken place
but they could not verify Baghdad's claims.
</P>
<P>
Following the briefing, the Security Council agreed to maintain
sanctions against Iraq. Iraq has to destroy all its chemical,
biological weapons and missiles before the council can remove the
sanctions imposed on it since 1990. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970304.0369 </DOCNO>
