<HEADLINE> New York Stocks End Declining </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Stocks on Wall Street ended a
three-session slump today even though interest rates rose again in
the bond market after the latest economic news heightened
inflation worries.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average gained 41.18 points to
6,918.92, after recovering from a nearly 50-point morning deficit.
The blue-chip barometer had lost about 160 points over the
previous three sessions amid worries the Federal Reserve is
planning to raise interest rates to lessen inflationary pressures.
</P>
<P>
Advancers outnumbered decliners by a slim margin on the New
York Stock Exchange, with the NYSE volume totaling 432.63 million
shares as against 508.28 million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list rose 4.49 to 795.31, and
the NYSE's composite index rose 1.83 to 417.34.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq composite index rose 2.19 to 1,311.19, and the
American Stock Exchange composite index rose 0.58 to 594.82.
</P>
<P>
Inflation worries continued to weigh on the bond market amid
more indications of strong economic growth.
</P>
<P>
The National Association of Purchasing Management reported that
the nation's manufacturing economy grew faster than expected in
February. It also reported that factories were paying higher
prices for supplies.
</P>
<P>
The Commerce Department reported that consumer spending jumped
0.7 percent, outpacing a 0.3 percent gain in incomes. Analysts had
predicted spending growth of 0.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
As bond prices fell today, the yield on the 30-year Treasury
rose as high as 6.86 percent, up from late Friday's 6.80 percent.
Later, the yield stood at about 6.83 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
