<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Absenteeism Costs UK Economy 13 Bln Pounds Each Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Absenteeism at work is growing
sharply in some parts of the British economy and is costing the
country at least 13 billion pounds (21 billion US dollars) each
year, according to a survey published today.
</P>
<P>
The Industrial Society, an independent training and advisory
body, said in the study that the proportion of the workforce
absent is now 3.6 percent, or 8.3 days per employee each year, and
it is up by a quarter in the past three years in the public
sector.
</P>
<P>
The survey of personnel managers in more than 300 businesses
and organizations said that the 13 billion pound losses did not
include falls in productivity, the cost of temporary staff,
overtime bills, damage to morale of customers and loss of
customers.
</P>
<P>
The society said that employees recorded colds and flu, stomach
upsets, headaches and back problems as the most common causes for
absence from work.
</P>
<P>
However, employers believed stress and low morale to be two of
the key likely causes.
</P>
<P>
The society pointed out that many organizations were too "lean
and mean."
</P>
<P>
"By reducing staff levels to such an extent, even minimal
levels of absenteeism put intolerable pressure on remaining
employees; this may in due course spread stress-related absence or
other problems across the organization," said the survey.
</P>
<P>
The society called on organizations to monitor absence rates
carefully, identify the true causes and costs, and look for
solutions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970304.0371 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tietmeyer Favors Duisenberg as 1st European </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 3 (Xinhua) -- German central bank president Hans
Tietmeyer today clearly indicated his support for his counterpart
of the Netherlands, Willem Duisenberg, to be the first president
of the European Central Bank (ECB) to be launched in 1999.
</P>
<P>
"With you (Duisenberg) as captain, the ECB crew would be able
to lead the Euro into the safe harbor of monetary stability," said
Tietmeyer in a speech at a ceremony in Frankfurt honoring
Duisenberg, who was chosen today by 20 international finance and
business journalists as "European Banker of the Year 1996."
</P>
<P>
Tietmeyer noted that Germany could only accept the planned
single European currency, the Euro, if it would be so stable as
the Netherlandish gulden.
</P>
<P>
At the ceremony, Duisenberg stressed the importance for the
future ECB to adopt a stability-oriented monetary policy, saying
that it would mean low inflation at home as well as a strong
common European money against the U.S. dollar and the Japanese
yen.
</P>
<P>
Duisenberg also called for strict adherence to the Maasticht
Treaty criteria for joining the Euro, which is due to launched by
January 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
He noted that it should not be dramatized if a few EU member
states fail to join the Euro in the first wave. "It is not an
excommunication," Duisenberg said, adding that with improved
efforts, those countries could still join in in 2002 when the Euro
is planned to be formally circulated.
</P>
<P>
Duisenberg, a professor for market economy who was twice
president of the Basel-based Bank for International Settlements
(BIS), was already elected to head the Frankfurt-based European
Monetary Institute (EMI) in July. The EMI is due to be replaced by
the ECB by its launching. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
