<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British, French Shares Down on Weak Wall Street </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Major stock markets in Europe ended
mixed today, with Frankfurt slightly up and London and Paris all
in the negative grounds, depressed by Wall Street's losses last
week and another weak start today.
</P>
<P>
The FTSE 100 index had dropped as low as 4,287.3 points earlier
in the day, but later struggled above the 4,300 level to finish
only slightly off and at its highest point of the day, down 1.2
points at 4,307.1, as Wall Street recovered most of its early
losses today.
</P>
<P>
Mildly positive factory output and consumer credit data today
had little impact, although the US interest rate specter still
hangs over the market, traders said.
</P>
<P>
Among the three major markets in Europe, the Frankfurt market,
which ended before New York opened, was the only one ending
marginally higher today, with the DAX-30 index 4.22 points higher
at 3,263.86.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that share prices were supported by strength in
the dollar and the bond market, but tradings were lackluster and
uninspired.
</P>
<P>
French shares also closed lower in subdued trade after Wall
Street's fall last Friday and a weak start today. However, hopes
of a short-term rate cut helped stop shares tumbling lower, with
the CAC-40 index closing down 7.29 points at 2,600.26.
</P>
<P>
London's FTSE 100 index ended down 1.2 points at 4,307.1. In
Frankfurt, the DAX-30 index closed up 4.22 points at 3,263.86. The
Paris CAC-40 index finished 7.29 points lower at 2,600.26.
</P>
</TEXT>
