<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Toronto Bars, Restaurants Ban Smoking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The toughest anti-smoking bylaw in
Canada took effect in Toronto today, making it illegal to smoke in
all of the city's bars and restaurants.
</P>
<P>
Some 20 to 25 health officials began to fan out across the
largest city of Canada in search of smoking violations, said
reports today.
</P>
<P>
Under the law, owners face fines ranging from 150 to 3,650 U.S.
dollars if they refuse to post no-smoking signs. Smokers who
refuse to stop smoking get the same penalties.
</P>
<P>
Bars and restaurants are permitted to allow smoking in 25
percent of their floor area -- but only after they create sealed,
separately ventilated smoking rooms.
</P>
<P>
So far, only two of the city's 4,500 licensed bars and
restaurants have applied for building permits to create rooms for
smokers.
</P>
<P>
The law applies only in the city of Toronto, not in five
adjoining suburbs, where smokers remain free to smoke.
</P>
<P>
The law has been opposed by the hospitality industry, claiming
that it would make bars and restaurants lose many of smoking
patrons.
</P>
<P>
But anti-smoking activists say the experience of other
countries show that most of the industry will not lose business.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
