<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat, Albright Hold Talks on Mideast Situation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat and U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright discussed at
length the controversial move by Israel to build Jewish homes in
Arab east Jerusalem in their nearly one-hour meeting, the State
Department said today.
</P>
<P>
Albright attended President Bill Clinton's talks with Arafat
this morning and she then had about a nearly one-hour one-on-one
meeting with Arafat, State Department spokesman Nicholas Burns
told reporters at a regular news briefing.
</P>
<P>
Their discussion "centered largely on the issue of the Israeli
proposal to build housing at Jabal Abu Ghenaim or Har Homa (in
Arab east Jerusalem). And they had a full and very, very detailed
discussion of that and all of its ramifications," Burns said.
</P>
<P>
But Burns declined to disclose the details of their
discussions, only saying, "the United States continues to believe
that this decision to build housing at Jabal Abu Ghenaim risks
undercutting a lot of the progress that has been made so far."
</P>
<P>
Earlier this morning, Clinton openly criticized Israel's
housing project in east Jerusalem, saying it could only build
"mistrust" between the Israelis and Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
"I would have preferred the decision not have been made because
I don't think it builds confidence. It builds mistrust," he told
reporters at the White House before starting talks with Arafat.
</P>
<P>
Arafat staying beside Clinton condemned the housing project,
saying, "The target is to squeeze and to isolate Jerusalem, but at
the same time to build settlements at the entrance of Bethlehem."
</P>
<P>
He said he was "sure" that Clinton "will push forward to
prevent" the Israeli move from building the Jewish homes in east
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Their talks were followed by a meeting between the U.S. and
Palestinian delegations, in which "economic issues were primarily
at the center of the discussions" with the attendance of Secretary
of the Treasury Bob Rubin and U.S. Aid Director Brian Atwood,
Burns said.
</P>
<P>
"As a result of the economic discussions, Secretary Albright
and Chairman Arafat have decided to form a joint U.S.-Palestinian
committee... to try to find ways, practically, to move the
relationship forward, whether it's on economic issues or foreign
policy issues or any other issues that are of importance to both
sides," Burns said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
