<HEADLINE> Britain Differs with US on SFOR's Mission in Bosnia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Britain said today that the
troops sent into Bosnia by the Western allies should leave
together, indicating differences with the U.S. on the issue.
</P>
<P>
"I regard the operation that we're undertaking as being a NATO
operation," British Defense Secretary Michael Portillo told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
The British defense secretary met with U.S. Defense Secretary
William Cohen at the Pentagon over the mission of the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization in Bosnia and the alliance's
expansion.
</P>
<P>
Cohen had repeatedly affirmed that the U.S. troops in Bosnia
will surely leave by mid-1998 when the mandate of the peacekeeping
force expires. He insists the Europeans should continue the job
of peacekeeping if needed.
</P>
<P>
However, Portillo said, "we went in together, we are working
together, and we shall leave together."
</P>
<P>
The United States contributes some 8,000 troops to the
so-called Stabilization Force (SFOR) in Bosnia. Britain, France
and other European countries are also major contributors.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of the war crimes in Bosnia, Cohen reiterated that
"the apprehension of war criminals is not part of the military
mission."
</P>
<P>
"It is a police function, however, and discussions are under
way at this time as to how a force can be assembled that would
carry out that particular mission," Cohen added.
</P>
<P>
Portillo stressed the importance of apprehending the war
criminals in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
"I think it will be very difficult to have a settlement in
Bosnia while the people who have been indicted for these war
crimes remain at large," he said.
</P>
<P>
On the enlargement of NATO, Portillo said, "I think Russia now
recognizes that there will be new members of NATO, and Russia is
now engaged constructively in creating with us a new NATO-Russia
charter."
</P>
<P>
"I believe that can be a very important part of the new security
architecture of Europe," he noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
